33// This header file defines the public API for Google Test. It should be
34// included by any test program that uses Google Test.

36// IMPORTANT NOTE: Due to limitation of the C++ language, we have to
37// leave some internal implementation details in this header file.
38// They are clearly marked by comments like this:
39//
40// // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
41//
42// Such code is NOT meant to be used by a user directly, and is subject
43// to CHANGE WITHOUT NOTICE. Therefore DO NOT DEPEND ON IT in a user
44// program!
45//
46// Acknowledgment: Google Test borrowed the idea of automatic test
47// registration from Barthelemy Dagenais' (barthelemy@prologique.com)
48// easyUnit framework.

128// Low-level types and utilities for porting Google Test to various
129// platforms. All macros ending with _ and symbols defined in an
130// internal namespace are subject to change without notice. Code
131// outside Google Test MUST NOT USE THEM DIRECTLY. Macros that don't
132// end with _ are part of Google Test's public API and can be used by
133// code outside Google Test.
134//
135// This file is fundamental to Google Test. All other Google Test source
136// files are expected to #include this. Therefore, it cannot #include
137// any other Google Test header.
138
139// GOOGLETEST_CM0001 DO NOT DELETE
140
141#ifndef GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_PORT_H_
142#define GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_PORT_H_
143
144// Environment-describing macros
145// -----------------------------
146//
147// Google Test can be used in many different environments. Macros in
148// this section tell Google Test what kind of environment it is being
149// used in, such that Google Test can provide environment-specific
150// features and implementations.
151//
152// Google Test tries to automatically detect the properties of its
153// environment, so users usually don't need to worry about these
154// macros. However, the automatic detection is not perfect.
155// Sometimes it's necessary for a user to define some of the following
156// macros in the build script to override Google Test's decisions.
157//
158// If the user doesn't define a macro in the list, Google Test will
159// provide a default definition. After this header is #included, all
160// macros in this list will be defined to either 1 or 0.
161//
162// Notes to maintainers:
163// - Each macro here is a user-tweakable knob; do not grow the list
164// lightly.
165// - Use #if to key off these macros. Don't use #ifdef or "#if
166// defined(...)", which will not work as these macros are ALWAYS
167// defined.
168//
169// GTEST_HAS_CLONE - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that clone(2)
170// is/isn't available.
171// GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that exceptions
172// are enabled.
173// GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that ::string
174// is/isn't available
175// GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that ::wstring
176// is/isn't available
177// GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that POSIX regular
178// expressions are/aren't available.
179// GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that <pthread.h>
180// is/isn't available.
181// GTEST_HAS_RTTI - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that RTTI is/isn't
182// enabled.
183// GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING - Define it to 1/0 to indicate that
184// std::wstring does/doesn't work (Google Test can
185// be used where std::wstring is unavailable).
186// GTEST_HAS_SEH - Define it to 1/0 to indicate whether the
187// compiler supports Microsoft's "Structured
188// Exception Handling".
189// GTEST_HAS_STREAM_REDIRECTION
190// - Define it to 1/0 to indicate whether the
191// platform supports I/O stream redirection using
192// dup() and dup2().
193// GTEST_LINKED_AS_SHARED_LIBRARY
194// - Define to 1 when compiling tests that use
195// Google Test as a shared library (known as
196// DLL on Windows).
197// GTEST_CREATE_SHARED_LIBRARY
198// - Define to 1 when compiling Google Test itself
199// as a shared library.
200// GTEST_DEFAULT_DEATH_TEST_STYLE
201// - The default value of --gtest_death_test_style.
202// The legacy default has been "fast" in the open
203// source version since 2008. The recommended value
204// is "threadsafe", and can be set in
205// custom/gtest-port.h.
206
207// Platform-indicating macros
208// --------------------------
209//
210// Macros indicating the platform on which Google Test is being used
211// (a macro is defined to 1 if compiled on the given platform;
212// otherwise UNDEFINED -- it's never defined to 0.). Google Test
213// defines these macros automatically. Code outside Google Test MUST
214// NOT define them.
215//
216// GTEST_OS_AIX - IBM AIX
217// GTEST_OS_CYGWIN - Cygwin
218// GTEST_OS_FREEBSD - FreeBSD
219// GTEST_OS_FUCHSIA - Fuchsia
220// GTEST_OS_HPUX - HP-UX
221// GTEST_OS_LINUX - Linux
222// GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID - Google Android
223// GTEST_OS_MAC - Mac OS X
224// GTEST_OS_IOS - iOS
225// GTEST_OS_NACL - Google Native Client (NaCl)
226// GTEST_OS_NETBSD - NetBSD
227// GTEST_OS_OPENBSD - OpenBSD
228// GTEST_OS_OS2 - OS/2
229// GTEST_OS_QNX - QNX
230// GTEST_OS_SOLARIS - Sun Solaris
231// GTEST_OS_WINDOWS - Windows (Desktop, MinGW, or Mobile)
232// GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_DESKTOP - Windows Desktop
233// GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MINGW - MinGW
234// GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE - Windows Mobile
235// GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_PHONE - Windows Phone
236// GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_RT - Windows Store App/WinRT
237// GTEST_OS_ZOS - z/OS
238//
239// Among the platforms, Cygwin, Linux, Max OS X, and Windows have the
240// most stable support. Since core members of the Google Test project
241// don't have access to other platforms, support for them may be less
242// stable. If you notice any problems on your platform, please notify
243// googletestframework@googlegroups.com (patches for fixing them are
244// even more welcome!).
245//
246// It is possible that none of the GTEST_OS_* macros are defined.
247
248// Feature-indicating macros
249// -------------------------
250//
251// Macros indicating which Google Test features are available (a macro
252// is defined to 1 if the corresponding feature is supported;
253// otherwise UNDEFINED -- it's never defined to 0.). Google Test
254// defines these macros automatically. Code outside Google Test MUST
255// NOT define them.
256//
257// These macros are public so that portable tests can be written.
258// Such tests typically surround code using a feature with an #if
259// which controls that code. For example:
260//
261// #if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
262// EXPECT_DEATH(DoSomethingDeadly());
263// #endif
264//
265// GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST - death tests
266// GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST - typed tests
267// GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST_P - type-parameterized tests
268// GTEST_IS_THREADSAFE - Google Test is thread-safe.
269// GOOGLETEST_CM0007 DO NOT DELETE
270// GTEST_USES_POSIX_RE - enhanced POSIX regex is used. Do not confuse with
271// GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE (see above) which users can
272// define themselves.
273// GTEST_USES_SIMPLE_RE - our own simple regex is used;
274// the above RE\b(s) are mutually exclusive.
275
276// Misc public macros
277// ------------------
278//
279// GTEST_FLAG(flag_name) - references the variable corresponding to
280// the given Google Test flag.
281
282// Internal utilities
283// ------------------
284//
285// The following macros and utilities are for Google Test's INTERNAL
286// use only. Code outside Google Test MUST NOT USE THEM DIRECTLY.
287//
288// Macros for basic C++ coding:
289// GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ - for disabling a gcc warning.
290// GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ - declares that a class' instances or a
291// variable don't have to be used.
292// GTEST_DISALLOW_ASSIGN_ - disables operator=.
293// GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_ - disables copy ctor and operator=.
294// GTEST_MUST_USE_RESULT_ - declares that a function's result must be used.
295// GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_PUSH_ - start code section where MSVC C4127 is
296// suppressed (constant conditional).
297// GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_POP_ - finish code section where MSVC C4127
298// is suppressed.
299//
300// Synchronization:
301// Mutex, MutexLock, ThreadLocal, GetThreadCount()
302// - synchronization primitives.
303//
304// Template meta programming:
305// IteratorTraits - partial implementation of std::iterator_traits, which
306// is not available in libCstd when compiled with Sun C++.
307//
308//
309// Regular expressions:
310// RE - a simple regular expression class using the POSIX
311// Extended Regular Expression syntax on UNIX-like platforms
312// GOOGLETEST_CM0008 DO NOT DELETE
313// or a reduced regular exception syntax on other
314// platforms, including Windows.
315// Logging:
316// GTEST_LOG_() - logs messages at the specified severity level.
317// LogToStderr() - directs all log messages to stderr.
318// FlushInfoLog() - flushes informational log messages.
319//
320// Stdout and stderr capturing:
321// CaptureStdout() - starts capturing stdout.
322// GetCapturedStdout() - stops capturing stdout and returns the captured
323// string.
324// CaptureStderr() - starts capturing stderr.
325// GetCapturedStderr() - stops capturing stderr and returns the captured
326// string.
327//
328// Integer types:
329// TypeWithSize - maps an integer to a int type.
330// Int32, UInt32, Int64, UInt64, TimeInMillis
331// - integers of known sizes.
332// BiggestInt - the biggest signed integer type.
333//
334// Command-line utilities:
335// GTEST_DECLARE_*() - declares a flag.
336// GTEST_DEFINE_*() - defines a flag.
337// GetInjectableArgvs() - returns the command line as a vector of strings.
338//
339// Environment variable utilities:
340// GetEnv() - gets the value of an environment variable.
341// BoolFromGTestEnv() - parses a bool environment variable.
342// Int32FromGTestEnv() - parses an Int32 environment variable.
343// StringFromGTestEnv() - parses a string environment variable.
344
345#include <ctype.h> // for isspace, etc
346#include <stddef.h> // for ptrdiff_t
347#include <stdio.h>
348#include <stdlib.h>
349#include <string.h>
350#include <memory>
351#include <type_traits>

406#ifndef GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_PORT_ARCH_H_

409// Determines the platform on which Google Test is compiled.
410#ifdef __CYGWIN__
411# define GTEST_OS_CYGWIN 1
412# elif defined(__MINGW__) || defined(__MINGW32__) || defined(__MINGW64__)
413# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MINGW 1
414# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS 1
415#elif defined _WIN32
416# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS 1
417# ifdef _WIN32_WCE
418# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE 1
419# elif defined(WINAPI_FAMILY)
420# include <winapifamily.h>
421# if WINAPI_FAMILY_PARTITION(WINAPI_PARTITION_DESKTOP)
422# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_DESKTOP 1
423# elif WINAPI_FAMILY_PARTITION(WINAPI_PARTITION_PHONE_APP)
424# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_PHONE 1
425# elif WINAPI_FAMILY_PARTITION(WINAPI_PARTITION_APP)
426# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_RT 1
427# elif WINAPI_FAMILY_PARTITION(WINAPI_PARTITION_TV_TITLE)
428# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_PHONE 1
429# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_TV_TITLE 1
430# else
431 // WINAPI_FAMILY defined but no known partition matched.
432 // Default to desktop.
433# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_DESKTOP 1
434# endif
435# else
436# define GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_DESKTOP 1
437# endif // _WIN32_WCE
438#elif defined __OS2__
439# define GTEST_OS_OS2 1
440#elif defined __APPLE__
441# define GTEST_OS_MAC 1
442# if TARGET_OS_IPHONE
443# define GTEST_OS_IOS 1
444# endif
445#elif defined __FreeBSD__
446# define GTEST_OS_FREEBSD 1
447#elif defined __Fuchsia__
448# define GTEST_OS_FUCHSIA 1
449#elif defined __linux__
450# define GTEST_OS_LINUX 1
451# if defined __ANDROID__
452# define GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID 1
453# endif
454#elif defined __MVS__
455# define GTEST_OS_ZOS 1
456#elif defined(__sun) && defined(__SVR4)
457# define GTEST_OS_SOLARIS 1
458#elif defined(_AIX)
459# define GTEST_OS_AIX 1
460#elif defined(__hpux)
461# define GTEST_OS_HPUX 1
462#elif defined __native_client__
463# define GTEST_OS_NACL 1
464#elif defined __NetBSD__
465# define GTEST_OS_NETBSD 1
466#elif defined __OpenBSD__
467# define GTEST_OS_OPENBSD 1
468#elif defined __QNX__
469# define GTEST_OS_QNX 1
470#endif // __CYGWIN__
471
472#endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_INTERNAL_GTEST_PORT_ARCH_H_

524// Determines the version of gcc that is used to compile this.
525#ifdef __GNUC__
526// 40302 means version 4.3.2.
527# define GTEST_GCC_VER_ \
528 (__GNUC__*10000 + __GNUC_MINOR__*100 + __GNUC_PATCHLEVEL__)
529#endif // __GNUC__

531// Macros for disabling Microsoft Visual C++ warnings.
532//
533// GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(4800 4385)
534// /* code that triggers warnings C4800 and C4385 */
535// GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_()
536#if defined(_MSC_VER)
537# define GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(warnings) \
538 __pragma(warning(push)) \
539 __pragma(warning(disable: warnings))
540# define GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_() \
541 __pragma(warning(pop))
542#else
543// Not all compilers are MSVC
544# define GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(warnings)
545# define GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_()
546#endif
547
548// Clang on Windows does not understand MSVC's pragma warning.
549// We need clang-specific way to disable function deprecation warning.
550#ifdef __clang__
551# define GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_DEPRECATED_PUSH_() \
552 _Pragma("clang diagnostic push") \
553 _Pragma("clang diagnostic ignored \"-Wdeprecated-declarations\"") \
554 _Pragma("clang diagnostic ignored \"-Wdeprecated-implementations\"")
555#define GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_DEPRECATED_POP_() \
556 _Pragma("clang diagnostic pop")
557#else
558# define GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_DEPRECATED_PUSH_() \
559 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(4996)
560# define GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_DEPRECATED_POP_() \
561 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_()
562#endif
563
564// Brings in definitions for functions used in the testing::internal::posix
565// namespace (read, write, close, chdir, isatty, stat). We do not currently
566// use them on Windows Mobile.
567#if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
568# if !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
569# include <direct.h>
570# include <io.h>
571# endif
572// In order to avoid having to include <windows.h>, use forward declaration
573#if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MINGW && !defined(__MINGW64_VERSION_MAJOR)
574// MinGW defined _CRITICAL_SECTION and _RTL_CRITICAL_SECTION as two
575// separate (equivalent) structs, instead of using typedef
576typedef struct _CRITICAL_SECTION GTEST_CRITICAL_SECTION;
577#else
578// Assume CRITICAL_SECTION is a typedef of _RTL_CRITICAL_SECTION.
579// This assumption is verified by
580// WindowsTypesTest.CRITICAL_SECTIONIs_RTL_CRITICAL_SECTION.
581typedef struct _RTL_CRITICAL_SECTION GTEST_CRITICAL_SECTION;
582#endif
583#else
584// This assumes that non-Windows OSes provide unistd.h. For OSes where this
585// is not the case, we need to include headers that provide the functions
586// mentioned above.
587# include <unistd.h>
588# include <strings.h>
589#endif // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
590
591#if GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID
592// Used to define __ANDROID_API__ matching the target NDK API level.
593# include <android/api-level.h> // NOLINT
594#endif
595
596// Defines this to true iff Google Test can use POSIX regular expressions.
597#ifndef GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE
598# if GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID
599// On Android, <regex.h> is only available starting with Gingerbread.
600# define GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE (__ANDROID_API__ >= 9)
601# else
602# define GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE (!GTEST_OS_WINDOWS)
603# endif
604#endif
605
606#if GTEST_USES_PCRE
607// The appropriate headers have already been included.
608
609#elif GTEST_HAS_POSIX_RE
610
611// On some platforms, <regex.h> needs someone to define size_t, and
612// won't compile otherwise. We can #include it here as we already
613// included <stdlib.h>, which is guaranteed to define size_t through
614// <stddef.h>.
615# include <regex.h> // NOLINT
616
617# define GTEST_USES_POSIX_RE 1
618
619#elif GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
620
621// <regex.h> is not available on Windows. Use our own simple regex
622// implementation instead.
623# define GTEST_USES_SIMPLE_RE 1
624
625#else
626
627// <regex.h> may not be available on this platform. Use our own
628// simple regex implementation instead.
629# define GTEST_USES_SIMPLE_RE 1
630
631#endif // GTEST_USES_PCRE
632
633#ifndef GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
634// The user didn't tell us whether exceptions are enabled, so we need
635// to figure it out.
636# if defined(_MSC_VER) && defined(_CPPUNWIND)
637// MSVC defines _CPPUNWIND to 1 iff exceptions are enabled.
638# define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
639# elif defined(__BORLANDC__)
640// C++Builder's implementation of the STL uses the _HAS_EXCEPTIONS
641// macro to enable exceptions, so we'll do the same.
642// Assumes that exceptions are enabled by default.
643# ifndef _HAS_EXCEPTIONS
644# define _HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
645# endif // _HAS_EXCEPTIONS
646# define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS _HAS_EXCEPTIONS
647# elif defined(__clang__)
648// clang defines __EXCEPTIONS iff exceptions are enabled before clang 220714,
649// but iff cleanups are enabled after that. In Obj-C++ files, there can be
650// cleanups for ObjC exceptions which also need cleanups, even if C++ exceptions
651// are disabled. clang has __has_feature(cxx_exceptions) which checks for C++
652// exceptions starting at clang r206352, but which checked for cleanups prior to
653// that. To reliably check for C++ exception availability with clang, check for
654// __EXCEPTIONS && __has_feature(cxx_exceptions).
655# define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS (__EXCEPTIONS && __has_feature(cxx_exceptions))
656# elif defined(__GNUC__) && __EXCEPTIONS
657// gcc defines __EXCEPTIONS to 1 iff exceptions are enabled.
658# define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
659# elif defined(__SUNPRO_CC)
660// Sun Pro CC supports exceptions. However, there is no compile-time way of
661// detecting whether they are enabled or not. Therefore, we assume that
662// they are enabled unless the user tells us otherwise.
663# define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
664# elif defined(__IBMCPP__) && __EXCEPTIONS
665// xlC defines __EXCEPTIONS to 1 iff exceptions are enabled.
666# define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
667# elif defined(__HP_aCC)
668// Exception handling is in effect by default in HP aCC compiler. It has to
669// be turned of by +noeh compiler option if desired.
670# define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 1
671# else
672// For other compilers, we assume exceptions are disabled to be
673// conservative.
674# define GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS 0
675# endif // defined(_MSC_VER) || defined(__BORLANDC__)
676#endif // GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
677
678#if !defined(GTEST_HAS_STD_STRING)
679// Even though we don't use this macro any longer, we keep it in case
680// some clients still depend on it.
681# define GTEST_HAS_STD_STRING 1
682#elif !GTEST_HAS_STD_STRING
683// The user told us that ::std::string isn't available.
684# error "::std::string isn't available."
685#endif // !defined(GTEST_HAS_STD_STRING)
686
687#ifndef GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
688# define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING 0
689#endif // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
690
691#ifndef GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
692// The user didn't tell us whether ::std::wstring is available, so we need
693// to figure it out.
694// Cygwin 1.7 and below doesn't support ::std::wstring.
695// Solaris' libc++ doesn't support it either. Android has
696// no support for it at least as recent as Froyo (2.2).
697# define GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING \
698 (!(GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID || GTEST_OS_CYGWIN || GTEST_OS_SOLARIS))
699
700#endif // GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
701
702#ifndef GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
703// The user didn't tell us whether ::wstring is available, so we need
704// to figure it out.
705# define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING \
706 (GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING && GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING)
707#endif // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
708
709// Determines whether RTTI is available.
710#ifndef GTEST_HAS_RTTI
711// The user didn't tell us whether RTTI is enabled, so we need to
712// figure it out.
713
714# ifdef _MSC_VER
715
716# ifdef _CPPRTTI // MSVC defines this macro iff RTTI is enabled.
717# define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 1
718# else
719# define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 0
720# endif
721
722// Starting with version 4.3.2, gcc defines __GXX_RTTI iff RTTI is enabled.
723# elif defined(__GNUC__)
724
725# ifdef __GXX_RTTI
726// When building against STLport with the Android NDK and with
727// -frtti -fno-exceptions, the build fails at link time with undefined
728// references to __cxa_bad_typeid. Note sure if STL or toolchain bug,
729// so disable RTTI when detected.
730# if GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID && defined(_STLPORT_MAJOR) && \
731 !defined(__EXCEPTIONS)
732# define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 0
733# else
734# define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 1
735# endif // GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID && __STLPORT_MAJOR && !__EXCEPTIONS
736# else
737# define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 0
738# endif // __GXX_RTTI
739
740// Clang defines __GXX_RTTI starting with version 3.0, but its manual recommends
741// using has_feature instead. has_feature(cxx_rtti) is supported since 2.7, the
742// first version with C++ support.
743# elif defined(__clang__)
744
745# define GTEST_HAS_RTTI __has_feature(cxx_rtti)
746
747// Starting with version 9.0 IBM Visual Age defines __RTTI_ALL__ to 1 if
748// both the typeid and dynamic_cast features are present.
749# elif defined(__IBMCPP__) && (__IBMCPP__ >= 900)
750
751# ifdef __RTTI_ALL__
752# define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 1
753# else
754# define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 0
755# endif
756
757# else
758
759// For all other compilers, we assume RTTI is enabled.
760# define GTEST_HAS_RTTI 1
761
762# endif // _MSC_VER
763
764#endif // GTEST_HAS_RTTI
765
766// It's this header's responsibility to #include <typeinfo> when RTTI
767// is enabled.
768#if GTEST_HAS_RTTI
769# include <typeinfo>
770#endif

863// Defines some utility macros.
864
865// The GNU compiler emits a warning if nested "if" statements are followed by
866// an "else" statement and braces are not used to explicitly disambiguate the
867// "else" binding. This leads to problems with code like:
868//
869// if (gate)
870// ASSERT_*(condition) << "Some message";
871//
872// The "switch (0) case 0:" idiom is used to suppress this.
873#ifdef __INTEL_COMPILER
874# define GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_
875#else
876# define GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ switch (0) case 0: default: // NOLINT
877#endif
878
879// Use this annotation at the end of a struct/class definition to
880// prevent the compiler from optimizing away instances that are never
881// used. This is useful when all interesting logic happens inside the
882// c'tor and / or d'tor. Example:
883//
884// struct Foo {
885// Foo() { ... }
886// } GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_;
887//
888// Also use it after a variable or parameter declaration to tell the
889// compiler the variable/parameter does not have to be used.
890#if defined(__GNUC__) && !defined(COMPILER_ICC)
891# define GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ __attribute__ ((unused))
892#elif defined(__clang__)
893# if __has_attribute(unused)
894# define GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ __attribute__ ((unused))
895# endif
896#endif
897#ifndef GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_
898# define GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_
899#endif
900
901// Use this annotation before a function that takes a printf format string.
902#if (defined(__GNUC__) || defined(__clang__)) && !defined(COMPILER_ICC)
903# if defined(__MINGW_PRINTF_FORMAT)
904// MinGW has two different printf implementations. Ensure the format macro
905// matches the selected implementation. See
906// https://sourceforge.net/p/mingw-w64/wiki2/gnu%20printf/.
907# define GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_PRINTF_(string_index, first_to_check) \
908 __attribute__((__format__(__MINGW_PRINTF_FORMAT, string_index, \
909 first_to_check)))
910# else
911# define GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_PRINTF_(string_index, first_to_check) \
912 __attribute__((__format__(__printf__, string_index, first_to_check)))
913# endif
914#else
915# define GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_PRINTF_(string_index, first_to_check)
916#endif
917
918
919// A macro to disallow operator=
920// This should be used in the private: declarations for a class.
921#define GTEST_DISALLOW_ASSIGN_(type) \
922 void operator=(type const &) = delete
923
924// A macro to disallow copy constructor and operator=
925// This should be used in the private: declarations for a class.
926#define GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(type) \
927 type(type const &) = delete; \
928 GTEST_DISALLOW_ASSIGN_(type)
929
930// Tell the compiler to warn about unused return values for functions declared
931// with this macro. The macro should be used on function declarations
932// following the argument list:
933//
934// Sprocket* AllocateSprocket() GTEST_MUST_USE_RESULT_;
935#if defined(__GNUC__) && !defined(COMPILER_ICC)
936# define GTEST_MUST_USE_RESULT_ __attribute__ ((warn_unused_result))
937#else
938# define GTEST_MUST_USE_RESULT_
939#endif // __GNUC__ && !COMPILER_ICC
940
941// MS C++ compiler emits warning when a conditional expression is compile time
942// constant. In some contexts this warning is false positive and needs to be
943// suppressed. Use the following two macros in such cases:
944//
945// GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_PUSH_()
946// while (true) {
947// GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_POP_()
948// }
949# define GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_PUSH_() \
950 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(4127)
951# define GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_POP_() \
952 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_()
953

1076// The GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_ is a legacy macro used to verify that a compile
1077// time expression is true (in new code, use static_assert instead). For
1078// example, you could use it to verify the size of a static array:
1079//
1080// GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_(GTEST_ARRAY_SIZE_(names) == NUM_NAMES,
1081// names_incorrect_size);
1082//
1083// The second argument to the macro must be a valid C++ identifier. If the
1084// expression is false, compiler will issue an error containing this identifier.
1085#define GTEST_COMPILE_ASSERT_(expr, msg) static_assert(expr, #msg)

1087// StaticAssertTypeEqHelper is used by StaticAssertTypeEq defined in gtest.h.
1088//
1089// This template is declared, but intentionally undefined.
1090template <typename T1, typename T2>
1091struct StaticAssertTypeEqHelper;
1092
1093template <typename T>
1094struct StaticAssertTypeEqHelper<T, T> {
1095 enum { value = true };
1096};

1098// Same as std::is_same<>.
1099template <typename T, typename U>
1100struct IsSame {
1101 enum { value = false };
1102};
1103template <typename T>
1104struct IsSame<T, T> {
1105 enum { value = true };
1106};

1123// A helper for suppressing warnings on constant condition. It just
1124// returns 'condition'.
1125GTEST_API_ bool IsTrue(bool condition);
1126
1127// Defines RE.
1128
1129#if GTEST_USES_PCRE
1130// if used, PCRE is injected by custom/gtest-port.h
1131#elif GTEST_USES_POSIX_RE || GTEST_USES_SIMPLE_RE
1132
1133// A simple C++ wrapper for <regex.h>. It uses the POSIX Extended
1134// Regular Expression syntax.
1135class GTEST_API_ RE {
1136 public:
1137 // A copy constructor is required by the Standard to initialize object
1138 // references from r-values.
1139 RE(const RE& other) { Init(other.pattern()); }
1140
1141 // Constructs an RE from a string.
1142 RE(const ::std::string& regex) { Init(regex.c_str()); } // NOLINT
1143
1144# if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
1145
1146 RE(const ::string& regex) { Init(regex.c_str()); } // NOLINT
1147
1148# endif // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
1149
1150 RE(const char* regex) { Init(regex); } // NOLINT
1151 ~RE();
1152
1153 // Returns the string representation of the regex.
1154 const char* pattern() const { return pattern_; }
1155
1156 // FullMatch(str, re) returns true iff regular expression re matches
1157 // the entire str.
1158 // PartialMatch(str, re) returns true iff regular expression re
1159 // matches a substring of str (including str itself).
1160 static bool FullMatch(const ::std::string& str, const RE& re) {
1161 return FullMatch(str.c_str(), re);
1162 }
1163 static bool PartialMatch(const ::std::string& str, const RE& re) {
1164 return PartialMatch(str.c_str(), re);
1165 }
1166
1167# if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
1168
1169 static bool FullMatch(const ::string& str, const RE& re) {
1170 return FullMatch(str.c_str(), re);
1171 }
1172 static bool PartialMatch(const ::string& str, const RE& re) {
1173 return PartialMatch(str.c_str(), re);
1174 }
1175
1176# endif // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
1177
1178 static bool FullMatch(const char* str, const RE& re);
1179 static bool PartialMatch(const char* str, const RE& re);
1180
1181 private:
1182 void Init(const char* regex);
1183 const char* pattern_;
1184 bool is_valid_;
1185
1186# if GTEST_USES_POSIX_RE
1187
1188 regex_t full_regex_; // For FullMatch().
1189 regex_t partial_regex_; // For PartialMatch().
1190
1191# else // GTEST_USES_SIMPLE_RE
1192
1193 const char* full_pattern_; // For FullMatch();
1194
1195# endif
1196
1197 GTEST_DISALLOW_ASSIGN_(RE);
1198};
1199
1200#endif // GTEST_USES_PCRE

1203// in an error message from the compiler used to compile this code.

1209GTEST_API_ ::std::string FormatCompilerIndependentFileLocation(const char* file,
1210 int line);

1212// Defines logging utilities:
1213// GTEST_LOG_(severity) - logs messages at the specified severity level. The
1214// message itself is streamed into the macro.
1215// LogToStderr() - directs all log messages to stderr.
1216// FlushInfoLog() - flushes informational log messages.
1217
1218enum GTestLogSeverity {
1219 GTEST_INFO,
1220 GTEST_WARNING,
1221 GTEST_ERROR,
1222 GTEST_FATAL
1223};

1254#if !defined(GTEST_CHECK_)
1255// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE.
1256//
1257// GTEST_CHECK_ is an all-mode assert. It aborts the program if the condition
1258// is not satisfied.
1259// Synopsys:
1260// GTEST_CHECK_(boolean_condition);
1261// or
1262// GTEST_CHECK_(boolean_condition) << "Additional message";
1263//
1264// This checks the condition and if the condition is not satisfied
1265// it prints message about the condition violation, including the
1266// condition itself, plus additional message streamed into it, if any,
1267// and then it aborts the program. It aborts the program irrespective of
1268// whether it is built in the debug mode or not.
1269# define GTEST_CHECK_(condition) \
1270 GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
1271 if (::testing::internal::IsTrue(condition)) \
1272 ; \
1273 else \
1274 GTEST_LOG_(FATAL) << "Condition " #condition " failed. "
1275#endif // !defined(GTEST_CHECK_)
1276
1277// An all-mode assert to verify that the given POSIX-style function
1278// call returns 0 (indicating success). Known limitation: this
1279// doesn't expand to a balanced 'if' statement, so enclose the macro
1280// in {} if you need to use it as the only statement in an 'if'
1281// branch.
1282#define GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(posix_call) \
1283 if (const int gtest_error = (posix_call)) \
1284 GTEST_LOG_(FATAL) << #posix_call << "failed with error " \
1285 << gtest_error
1286
1287// Adds reference to a type if it is not a reference type,
1288// otherwise leaves it unchanged. This is the same as
1289// tr1::add_reference, which is not widely available yet.
1290template <typename T>
1291struct AddReference { typedef T& type; }; // NOLINT
1292template <typename T>
1293struct AddReference<T&> { typedef T& type; }; // NOLINT
1294
1295// A handy wrapper around AddReference that works when the argument T
1296// depends on template parameters.
1297#define GTEST_ADD_REFERENCE_(T) \
1298 typename ::testing::internal::AddReference<T>::type
1299
1300// Transforms "T" into "const T&" according to standard reference collapsing
1301// rules (this is only needed as a backport for C++98 compilers that do not
1302// support reference collapsing). Specifically, it transforms:
1303//
1304// char ==> const char&
1305// const char ==> const char&
1306// char& ==> char&
1307// const char& ==> const char&
1308//
1309// Note that the non-const reference will not have "const" added. This is
1310// standard, and necessary so that "T" can always bind to "const T&".
1311template <typename T>
1312struct ConstRef { typedef const T& type; };
1313template <typename T>
1314struct ConstRef<T&> { typedef T& type; };
1315
1316// The argument T must depend on some template parameters.
1317#define GTEST_REFERENCE_TO_CONST_(T) \
1318 typename ::testing::internal::ConstRef<T>::type
1319
1320// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
1321//
1322// Use ImplicitCast_ as a safe version of static_cast for upcasting in
1323// the type hierarchy (e.g. casting a Foo* to a SuperclassOfFoo* or a
1324// const Foo*). When you use ImplicitCast_, the compiler checks that
1325// the cast is safe. Such explicit ImplicitCast_s are necessary in
1326// surprisingly many situations where C++ demands an exact type match
1327// instead of an argument type convertable to a target type.
1328//
1329// The syntax for using ImplicitCast_ is the same as for static_cast:
1330//
1331// ImplicitCast_<ToType>(expr)
1332//
1333// ImplicitCast_ would have been part of the C++ standard library,
1334// but the proposal was submitted too late. It will probably make
1335// its way into the language in the future.
1336//
1337// This relatively ugly name is intentional. It prevents clashes with
1338// similar functions users may have (e.g., implicit_cast). The internal
1339// namespace alone is not enough because the function can be found by ADL.
1340template<typename To>
1341inline To ImplicitCast_(To x) { return x; }
1342
1343// When you upcast (that is, cast a pointer from type Foo to type
1344// SuperclassOfFoo), it's fine to use ImplicitCast_<>, since upcasts
1345// always succeed. When you downcast (that is, cast a pointer from
1346// type Foo to type SubclassOfFoo), static_cast<> isn't safe, because
1347// how do you know the pointer is really of type SubclassOfFoo? It
1348// could be a bare Foo, or of type DifferentSubclassOfFoo. Thus,
1349// when you downcast, you should use this macro. In debug mode, we
1350// use dynamic_cast<> to double-check the downcast is legal (we die
1351// if it's not). In normal mode, we do the efficient static_cast<>
1352// instead. Thus, it's important to test in debug mode to make sure
1353// the cast is legal!
1354// This is the only place in the code we should use dynamic_cast<>.
1355// In particular, you SHOULDN'T be using dynamic_cast<> in order to
1356// do RTTI (eg code like this:
1357// if (dynamic_cast<Subclass1>(foo)) HandleASubclass1Object(foo);
1358// if (dynamic_cast<Subclass2>(foo)) HandleASubclass2Object(foo);
1359// You should design the code some other way not to need this.
1360//
1361// This relatively ugly name is intentional. It prevents clashes with
1362// similar functions users may have (e.g., down_cast). The internal
1363// namespace alone is not enough because the function can be found by ADL.
1364template<typename To, typename From> // use like this: DownCast_<T*>(foo);
1365inline To DownCast_(From* f) { // so we only accept pointers
1366 // Ensures that To is a sub-type of From *. This test is here only
1367 // for compile-time type checking, and has no overhead in an
1368 // optimized build at run-time, as it will be optimized away
1369 // completely.
1370 GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_PUSH_()
1371 if (false) {
1372 GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_POP_()
1373 const To to = nullptr;
1374 ::testing::internal::ImplicitCast_<From*>(to);
1375 }
1376
1377#if GTEST_HAS_RTTI
1378 // RTTI: debug mode only!
1379 GTEST_CHECK_(f == nullptr || dynamic_cast<To>(f) != nullptr);
1380#endif
1381 return static_cast<To>(f);
1382}
1383
1384// Downcasts the pointer of type Base to Derived.
1385// Derived must be a subclass of Base. The parameter MUST
1386// point to a class of type Derived, not any subclass of it.
1387// When RTTI is available, the function performs a runtime
1388// check to enforce this.
1389template <class Derived, class Base>
1390Derived* CheckedDowncastToActualType(Base* base) {
1391#if GTEST_HAS_RTTI
1392 GTEST_CHECK_(typeid(*base) == typeid(Derived));
1393#endif
1394
1395#if GTEST_HAS_DOWNCAST_
1396 return ::down_cast<Derived*>(base);
1397#elif GTEST_HAS_RTTI
1398 return dynamic_cast<Derived*>(base); // NOLINT
1399#else
1400 return static_cast<Derived*>(base); // Poor man's downcast.
1401#endif
1402}

1440// Defines synchronization primitives.
1441#if GTEST_IS_THREADSAFE
1442# if GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD
1443// Sleeps for (roughly) n milliseconds. This function is only for testing
1444// Google Test's own constructs. Don't use it in user tests, either
1445// directly or indirectly.
1446inline void SleepMilliseconds(int n) {
1447 const timespec time = {
1448 0, // 0 seconds.
1449 n * 1000L * 1000L, // And n ms.
1450 };
1451 nanosleep(&time, nullptr);
1452}
1453# endif // GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD
1454
1455# if GTEST_HAS_NOTIFICATION_
1456// Notification has already been imported into the namespace.
1457// Nothing to do here.
1458
1459# elif GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD
1460// Allows a controller thread to pause execution of newly created
1461// threads until notified. Instances of this class must be created
1462// and destroyed in the controller thread.
1463//
1464// This class is only for testing Google Test's own constructs. Do not
1465// use it in user tests, either directly or indirectly.
1466class Notification {
1467 public:
1468 Notification() : notified_(false) {
1469 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_mutex_init(&mutex_, nullptr));
1470 }
1471 ~Notification() {
1472 pthread_mutex_destroy(&mutex_);
1473 }
1474
1475 // Notifies all threads created with this notification to start. Must
1476 // be called from the controller thread.
1477 void Notify() {
1478 pthread_mutex_lock(&mutex_);
1479 notified_ = true;
1480 pthread_mutex_unlock(&mutex_);
1481 }
1482
1483 // Blocks until the controller thread notifies. Must be called from a test
1484 // thread.
1485 void WaitForNotification() {
1486 for (;;) {
1487 pthread_mutex_lock(&mutex_);
1488 const bool notified = notified_;
1489 pthread_mutex_unlock(&mutex_);
1490 if (notified)
1491 break;
1492 SleepMilliseconds(10);
1493 }
1494 }
1495
1496 private:
1497 pthread_mutex_t mutex_;
1498 bool notified_;
1499
1500 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(Notification);
1501};

1504
1505GTEST_API_ void SleepMilliseconds(int n);

1507// Provides leak-safe Windows kernel handle ownership.

1509class GTEST_API_ AutoHandle {
1510 public:
1511 // Assume that Win32 HANDLE type is equivalent to void*. Doing so allows us to
1512 // avoid including <windows.h> in this header file. Including <windows.h> is
1513 // undesirable because it defines a lot of symbols and macros that tend to
1514 // conflict with client code. This assumption is verified by
1515 // WindowsTypesTest.HANDLEIsVoidStar.
1516 typedef void* Handle;
1517 AutoHandle();
1518 explicit AutoHandle(Handle handle);
1519
1520 ~AutoHandle();
1521
1522 Handle Get() const;
1523 void Reset();
1524 void Reset(Handle handle);
1525
1526 private:
1527 // Returns true iff the handle is a valid handle object that can be closed.
1528 bool IsCloseable() const;

1530 Handle handle_;

1554// On MinGW, we can have both GTEST_OS_WINDOWS and GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD
1555// defined, but we don't want to use MinGW's pthreads implementation, which
1556// has conformance problems with some versions of the POSIX standard.
1557# if GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MINGW
1558
1559// As a C-function, ThreadFuncWithCLinkage cannot be templated itself.
1560// Consequently, it cannot select a correct instantiation of ThreadWithParam
1561// in order to call its Run(). Introducing ThreadWithParamBase as a
1562// non-templated base class for ThreadWithParam allows us to bypass this
1563// problem.
1564class ThreadWithParamBase {
1565 public:
1566 virtual ~ThreadWithParamBase() {}
1567 virtual void Run() = 0;
1568};
1569
1570// pthread_create() accepts a pointer to a function type with the C linkage.
1571// According to the Standard (7.5/1), function types with different linkages
1572// are different even if they are otherwise identical. Some compilers (for
1573// example, SunStudio) treat them as different types. Since class methods
1574// cannot be defined with C-linkage we need to define a free C-function to
1575// pass into pthread_create().
1576extern "C" inline void* ThreadFuncWithCLinkage(void* thread) {
1577 static_cast<ThreadWithParamBase*>(thread)->Run();
1578 return nullptr;
1579}
1580
1581// Helper class for testing Google Test's multi-threading constructs.
1582// To use it, write:
1583//
1584// void ThreadFunc(int param) { /* Do things with param */ }
1585// Notification thread_can_start;
1586// ...
1587// // The thread_can_start parameter is optional; you can supply NULL.
1588// ThreadWithParam<int> thread(&ThreadFunc, 5, &thread_can_start);
1589// thread_can_start.Notify();
1590//
1591// These classes are only for testing Google Test's own constructs. Do
1592// not use them in user tests, either directly or indirectly.
1593template <typename T>
1594class ThreadWithParam : public ThreadWithParamBase {
1595 public:
1596 typedef void UserThreadFunc(T);
1597
1598 ThreadWithParam(UserThreadFunc* func, T param, Notification* thread_can_start)
1599 : func_(func),
1600 param_(param),
1601 thread_can_start_(thread_can_start),
1602 finished_(false) {
1603 ThreadWithParamBase* const base = this;
1604 // The thread can be created only after all fields except thread_
1605 // have been initialized.
1606 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(
1607 pthread_create(&thread_, nullptr, &ThreadFuncWithCLinkage, base));
1608 }
1609 ~ThreadWithParam() override { Join(); }
1610
1611 void Join() {
1612 if (!finished_) {
1613 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_join(thread_, nullptr));
1614 finished_ = true;
1615 }
1616 }
1617
1618 void Run() override {
1619 if (thread_can_start_ != nullptr) thread_can_start_->WaitForNotification();
1620 func_(param_);
1621 }
1622
1623 private:
1624 UserThreadFunc* const func_; // User-supplied thread function.
1625 const T param_; // User-supplied parameter to the thread function.
1626 // When non-NULL, used to block execution until the controller thread
1627 // notifies.
1628 Notification* const thread_can_start_;
1629 bool finished_; // true iff we know that the thread function has finished.
1630 pthread_t thread_; // The native thread object.
1631
1632 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ThreadWithParam);
1633};
1634# endif // !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS && GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD ||
1635 // GTEST_HAS_MUTEX_AND_THREAD_LOCAL_

1638// Mutex and ThreadLocal have already been imported into the namespace.
1639// Nothing to do here.

1641# elif GTEST_OS_WINDOWS && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_PHONE && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_RT

1643// Mutex implements mutex on Windows platforms. It is used in conjunction
1644// with class MutexLock:
1645//
1646// Mutex mutex;
1647// ...
1648// MutexLock lock(&mutex); // Acquires the mutex and releases it at the
1649// // end of the current scope.
1650//
1651// A static Mutex *must* be defined or declared using one of the following
1652// macros:
1653// GTEST_DEFINE_STATIC_MUTEX_(g_some_mutex);
1654// GTEST_DECLARE_STATIC_MUTEX_(g_some_mutex);
1655//
1656// (A non-static Mutex is defined/declared in the usual way).
1657class GTEST_API_ Mutex {
1658 public:
1659 enum MutexType { kStatic = 0, kDynamic = 1 };
1660 // We rely on kStaticMutex being 0 as it is to what the linker initializes
1661 // type_ in static mutexes. critical_section_ will be initialized lazily
1662 // in ThreadSafeLazyInit().
1663 enum StaticConstructorSelector { kStaticMutex = 0 };
1664
1665 // This constructor intentionally does nothing. It relies on type_ being
1666 // statically initialized to 0 (effectively setting it to kStatic) and on
1667 // ThreadSafeLazyInit() to lazily initialize the rest of the members.
1668 explicit Mutex(StaticConstructorSelector /*dummy*/) {}
1669
1670 Mutex();
1671 ~Mutex();
1672
1673 void Lock();
1674
1675 void Unlock();
1676
1677 // Does nothing if the current thread holds the mutex. Otherwise, crashes
1678 // with high probability.
1679 void AssertHeld();
1680
1681 private:
1682 // Initializes owner_thread_id_ and critical_section_ in static mutexes.
1683 void ThreadSafeLazyInit();
1684
1685 // Per https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/oldnewthing/20040223-00/?p=40503,
1686 // we assume that 0 is an invalid value for thread IDs.
1687 unsigned int owner_thread_id_;
1688
1689 // For static mutexes, we rely on these members being initialized to zeros
1690 // by the linker.
1691 MutexType type_;
1692 long critical_section_init_phase_; // NOLINT
1693 GTEST_CRITICAL_SECTION* critical_section_;
1694
1695 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(Mutex);
1696};
1697
1698# define GTEST_DECLARE_STATIC_MUTEX_(mutex) \
1699 extern ::testing::internal::Mutex mutex
1700
1701# define GTEST_DEFINE_STATIC_MUTEX_(mutex) \
1702 ::testing::internal::Mutex mutex(::testing::internal::Mutex::kStaticMutex)
1703
1704// We cannot name this class MutexLock because the ctor declaration would
1705// conflict with a macro named MutexLock, which is defined on some
1706// platforms. That macro is used as a defensive measure to prevent against
1707// inadvertent misuses of MutexLock like "MutexLock(&mu)" rather than
1708// "MutexLock l(&mu)". Hence the typedef trick below.
1709class GTestMutexLock {
1710 public:
1711 explicit GTestMutexLock(Mutex* mutex)
1712 : mutex_(mutex) { mutex_->Lock(); }
1713
1714 ~GTestMutexLock() { mutex_->Unlock(); }
1715
1716 private:
1717 Mutex* const mutex_;
1718
1719 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(GTestMutexLock);
1720};

1815// Implements thread-local storage on Windows systems.
1816//
1817// // Thread 1
1818// ThreadLocal<int> tl(100); // 100 is the default value for each thread.
1819//
1820// // Thread 2
1821// tl.set(150); // Changes the value for thread 2 only.
1822// EXPECT_EQ(150, tl.get());
1823//
1824// // Thread 1
1825// EXPECT_EQ(100, tl.get()); // In thread 1, tl has the original value.
1826// tl.set(200);
1827// EXPECT_EQ(200, tl.get());
1828//
1829// The template type argument T must have a public copy constructor.
1830// In addition, the default ThreadLocal constructor requires T to have
1831// a public default constructor.
1832//
1833// The users of a TheadLocal instance have to make sure that all but one
1834// threads (including the main one) using that instance have exited before
1835// destroying it. Otherwise, the per-thread objects managed for them by the
1836// ThreadLocal instance are not guaranteed to be destroyed on all platforms.
1837//
1838// Google Test only uses global ThreadLocal objects. That means they
1839// will die after main() has returned. Therefore, no per-thread
1840// object managed by Google Test will be leaked as long as all threads
1841// using Google Test have exited when main() returns.
1842template <typename T>
1843class ThreadLocal : public ThreadLocalBase {
1844 public:
1845 ThreadLocal() : default_factory_(new DefaultValueHolderFactory()) {}
1846 explicit ThreadLocal(const T& value)
1847 : default_factory_(new InstanceValueHolderFactory(value)) {}
1848
1849 ~ThreadLocal() { ThreadLocalRegistry::OnThreadLocalDestroyed(this); }
1850
1851 T* pointer() { return GetOrCreateValue(); }
1852 const T* pointer() const { return GetOrCreateValue(); }
1853 const T& get() const { return *pointer(); }
1854 void set(const T& value) { *pointer() = value; }
1855
1856 private:
1857 // Holds a value of T. Can be deleted via its base class without the caller
1858 // knowing the type of T.
1859 class ValueHolder : public ThreadLocalValueHolderBase {
1860 public:
1861 ValueHolder() : value_() {}
1862 explicit ValueHolder(const T& value) : value_(value) {}
1863
1864 T* pointer() { return &value_; }
1865
1866 private:
1867 T value_;
1868 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ValueHolder);
1869 };
1870
1871
1872 T* GetOrCreateValue() const {
1873 return static_cast<ValueHolder*>(
1874 ThreadLocalRegistry::GetValueOnCurrentThread(this))->pointer();
1875 }
1876
1877 virtual ThreadLocalValueHolderBase* NewValueForCurrentThread() const {
1878 return default_factory_->MakeNewHolder();
1879 }
1880
1881 class ValueHolderFactory {
1882 public:
1883 ValueHolderFactory() {}
1884 virtual ~ValueHolderFactory() {}
1885 virtual ValueHolder* MakeNewHolder() const = 0;
1886
1887 private:
1888 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ValueHolderFactory);
1889 };
1890
1891 class DefaultValueHolderFactory : public ValueHolderFactory {
1892 public:
1893 DefaultValueHolderFactory() {}
1894 virtual ValueHolder* MakeNewHolder() const { return new ValueHolder(); }
1895
1896 private:
1897 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(DefaultValueHolderFactory);
1898 };
1899
1900 class InstanceValueHolderFactory : public ValueHolderFactory {
1901 public:
1902 explicit InstanceValueHolderFactory(const T& value) : value_(value) {}
1903 virtual ValueHolder* MakeNewHolder() const {
1904 return new ValueHolder(value_);
1905 }
1906
1907 private:
1908 const T value_; // The value for each thread.
1909
1910 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(InstanceValueHolderFactory);
1911 };
1912
1913 std::unique_ptr<ValueHolderFactory> default_factory_;
1914
1915 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ThreadLocal);
1916};

1918# elif GTEST_HAS_PTHREAD
1919
1920// MutexBase and Mutex implement mutex on pthreads-based platforms.
1921class MutexBase {
1922 public:
1923 // Acquires this mutex.
1924 void Lock() {
1925 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_mutex_lock(&mutex_));
1926 owner_ = pthread_self();
1927 has_owner_ = true;
1928 }
1929
1930 // Releases this mutex.
1931 void Unlock() {
1932 // Since the lock is being released the owner_ field should no longer be
1933 // considered valid. We don't protect writing to has_owner_ here, as it's
1934 // the caller's responsibility to ensure that the current thread holds the
1935 // mutex when this is called.
1936 has_owner_ = false;
1937 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_mutex_unlock(&mutex_));
1938 }
1939
1940 // Does nothing if the current thread holds the mutex. Otherwise, crashes
1941 // with high probability.
1942 void AssertHeld() const {
1943 GTEST_CHECK_(has_owner_ && pthread_equal(owner_, pthread_self()))
1944 << "The current thread is not holding the mutex @" << this;
1945 }
1946
1947 // A static mutex may be used before main() is entered. It may even
1948 // be used before the dynamic initialization stage. Therefore we
1949 // must be able to initialize a static mutex object at link time.
1950 // This means MutexBase has to be a POD and its member variables
1951 // have to be public.
1952 public:
1953 pthread_mutex_t mutex_; // The underlying pthread mutex.
1954 // has_owner_ indicates whether the owner_ field below contains a valid thread
1955 // ID and is therefore safe to inspect (e.g., to use in pthread_equal()). All
1956 // accesses to the owner_ field should be protected by a check of this field.
1957 // An alternative might be to memset() owner_ to all zeros, but there's no
1958 // guarantee that a zero'd pthread_t is necessarily invalid or even different
1959 // from pthread_self().
1960 bool has_owner_;
1961 pthread_t owner_; // The thread holding the mutex.
1962};
1963
1964// Forward-declares a static mutex.
1965# define GTEST_DECLARE_STATIC_MUTEX_(mutex) \
1966 extern ::testing::internal::MutexBase mutex
1967
1968// Defines and statically (i.e. at link time) initializes a static mutex.
1969// The initialization list here does not explicitly initialize each field,
1970// instead relying on default initialization for the unspecified fields. In
1971// particular, the owner_ field (a pthread_t) is not explicitly initialized.
1972// This allows initialization to work whether pthread_t is a scalar or struct.
1973// The flag -Wmissing-field-initializers must not be specified for this to work.
1974#define GTEST_DEFINE_STATIC_MUTEX_(mutex) \
1975 ::testing::internal::MutexBase mutex = {PTHREAD_MUTEX_INITIALIZER, false, 0}
1976
1977// The Mutex class can only be used for mutexes created at runtime. It
1978// shares its API with MutexBase otherwise.
1979class Mutex : public MutexBase {
1980 public:
1981 Mutex() {
1982 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_mutex_init(&mutex_, nullptr));
1983 has_owner_ = false;
1984 }
1985 ~Mutex() {
1986 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_mutex_destroy(&mutex_));
1987 }
1988
1989 private:
1990 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(Mutex);
1991};
1992
1993// We cannot name this class MutexLock because the ctor declaration would
1994// conflict with a macro named MutexLock, which is defined on some
1995// platforms. That macro is used as a defensive measure to prevent against
1996// inadvertent misuses of MutexLock like "MutexLock(&mu)" rather than
1997// "MutexLock l(&mu)". Hence the typedef trick below.
1998class GTestMutexLock {
1999 public:
2000 explicit GTestMutexLock(MutexBase* mutex)
2001 : mutex_(mutex) { mutex_->Lock(); }
2002
2003 ~GTestMutexLock() { mutex_->Unlock(); }
2004
2005 private:
2006 MutexBase* const mutex_;
2007
2008 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(GTestMutexLock);
2009};
2010
2011typedef GTestMutexLock MutexLock;
2012
2013// Helpers for ThreadLocal.
2014
2015// pthread_key_create() requires DeleteThreadLocalValue() to have
2016// C-linkage. Therefore it cannot be templatized to access
2017// ThreadLocal<T>. Hence the need for class
2018// ThreadLocalValueHolderBase.
2019class ThreadLocalValueHolderBase {
2020 public:
2021 virtual ~ThreadLocalValueHolderBase() {}
2022};
2023
2024// Called by pthread to delete thread-local data stored by
2025// pthread_setspecific().
2026extern "C" inline void DeleteThreadLocalValue(void* value_holder) {
2027 delete static_cast<ThreadLocalValueHolderBase*>(value_holder);
2028}
2029
2030// Implements thread-local storage on pthreads-based systems.
2031template <typename T>
2032class GTEST_API_ ThreadLocal {
2033 public:
2034 ThreadLocal()
2035 : key_(CreateKey()), default_factory_(new DefaultValueHolderFactory()) {}
2036 explicit ThreadLocal(const T& value)
2037 : key_(CreateKey()),
2038 default_factory_(new InstanceValueHolderFactory(value)) {}
2039
2040 ~ThreadLocal() {
2041 // Destroys the managed object for the current thread, if any.
2042 DeleteThreadLocalValue(pthread_getspecific(key_));
2043
2044 // Releases resources associated with the key. This will *not*
2045 // delete managed objects for other threads.
2046 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_key_delete(key_));
2047 }
2048
2049 T* pointer() { return GetOrCreateValue(); }
2050 const T* pointer() const { return GetOrCreateValue(); }
2051 const T& get() const { return *pointer(); }
2052 void set(const T& value) { *pointer() = value; }
2053
2054 private:
2055 // Holds a value of type T.
2056 class ValueHolder : public ThreadLocalValueHolderBase {
2057 public:
2058 ValueHolder() : value_() {}
2059 explicit ValueHolder(const T& value) : value_(value) {}
2060
2061 T* pointer() { return &value_; }
2062
2063 private:
2064 T value_;
2065 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ValueHolder);
2066 };
2067
2068 static pthread_key_t CreateKey() {
2069 pthread_key_t key;
2070 // When a thread exits, DeleteThreadLocalValue() will be called on
2071 // the object managed for that thread.
2072 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(
2073 pthread_key_create(&key, &DeleteThreadLocalValue));
2074 return key;
2075 }
2076
2077 T* GetOrCreateValue() const {
2078 ThreadLocalValueHolderBase* const holder =
2079 static_cast<ThreadLocalValueHolderBase*>(pthread_getspecific(key_));
2080 if (holder != nullptr) {
2081 return CheckedDowncastToActualType<ValueHolder>(holder)->pointer();
2082 }
2083
2084 ValueHolder* const new_holder = default_factory_->MakeNewHolder();
2085 ThreadLocalValueHolderBase* const holder_base = new_holder;
2086 GTEST_CHECK_POSIX_SUCCESS_(pthread_setspecific(key_, holder_base));
2087 return new_holder->pointer();
2088 }
2089
2090 class ValueHolderFactory {
2091 public:
2092 ValueHolderFactory() {}
2093 virtual ~ValueHolderFactory() {}
2094 virtual ValueHolder* MakeNewHolder() const = 0;
2095
2096 private:
2097 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ValueHolderFactory);
2098 };
2099
2100 class DefaultValueHolderFactory : public ValueHolderFactory {
2101 public:
2102 DefaultValueHolderFactory() {}
2103 virtual ValueHolder* MakeNewHolder() const { return new ValueHolder(); }
2104
2105 private:
2106 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(DefaultValueHolderFactory);
2107 };
2108
2109 class InstanceValueHolderFactory : public ValueHolderFactory {
2110 public:
2111 explicit InstanceValueHolderFactory(const T& value) : value_(value) {}
2112 virtual ValueHolder* MakeNewHolder() const {
2113 return new ValueHolder(value_);
2114 }
2115
2116 private:
2117 const T value_; // The value for each thread.
2118
2119 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(InstanceValueHolderFactory);
2120 };
2121
2122 // A key pthreads uses for looking up per-thread values.
2123 const pthread_key_t key_;
2124 std::unique_ptr<ValueHolderFactory> default_factory_;
2125
2126 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ThreadLocal);
2127};
2128
2129# endif // GTEST_HAS_MUTEX_AND_THREAD_LOCAL_

2225// Utilities for char.
2226
2227// isspace(int ch) and friends accept an unsigned char or EOF. char
2228// may be signed, depending on the compiler (or compiler flags).
2229// Therefore we need to cast a char to unsigned char before calling
2230// isspace(), etc.
2231
2232inline bool IsAlpha(char ch) {
2233 return isalpha(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
2234}
2235inline bool IsAlNum(char ch) {
2236 return isalnum(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
2237}
2238inline bool IsDigit(char ch) {
2239 return isdigit(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
2240}
2241inline bool IsLower(char ch) {
2242 return islower(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
2243}
2244inline bool IsSpace(char ch) {
2245 return isspace(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
2246}
2247inline bool IsUpper(char ch) {
2248 return isupper(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
2249}
2250inline bool IsXDigit(char ch) {
2251 return isxdigit(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)) != 0;
2252}
2253inline bool IsXDigit(wchar_t ch) {
2254 const unsigned char low_byte = static_cast<unsigned char>(ch);
2255 return ch == low_byte && isxdigit(low_byte) != 0;
2256}
2257
2258inline char ToLower(char ch) {
2259 return static_cast<char>(tolower(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)));
2260}
2261inline char ToUpper(char ch) {
2262 return static_cast<char>(toupper(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)));
2263}
2264
2265inline std::string StripTrailingSpaces(std::string str) {
2266 std::string::iterator it = str.end();
2267 while (it != str.begin() && IsSpace(*--it))
2268 it = str.erase(it);
2269 return str;
2270}

2368inline const char* GetEnv(const char* name) {
2369#if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE || GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_PHONE || GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_RT
2370 // We are on Windows CE, which has no environment variables.
2371 static_cast<void>(name); // To prevent 'unused argument' warning.
2372 return nullptr;
2373#elif defined(__BORLANDC__) || defined(__SunOS_5_8) || defined(__SunOS_5_9)
2374 // Environment variables which we programmatically clear will be set to the
2375 // empty string rather than unset (NULL). Handle that case.
2376 const char* const env = getenv(name);

2378#else

2396// MSVC "deprecates" snprintf and issues warnings wherever it is used. In
2397// order to avoid these warnings, we need to use _snprintf or _snprintf_s on
2398// MSVC-based platforms. We map the GTEST_SNPRINTF_ macro to the appropriate
2399// function in order to achieve that. We use macro definition here because
2400// snprintf is a variadic function.
2401#if _MSC_VER && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
2402// MSVC 2005 and above support variadic macros.
2403# define GTEST_SNPRINTF_(buffer, size, format, ...) \
2404 _snprintf_s(buffer, size, size, format, __VA_ARGS__)
2405#elif defined(_MSC_VER)
2406// Windows CE does not define _snprintf_s
2407# define GTEST_SNPRINTF_ _snprintf
2408#else
2409# define GTEST_SNPRINTF_ snprintf
2410#endif

2412// The maximum number a BiggestInt can represent. This definition
2413// works no matter BiggestInt is represented in one's complement or
2414// two's complement.
2415//
2416// We cannot rely on numeric_limits in STL, as __int64 and long long
2417// are not part of standard C++ and numeric_limits doesn't need to be
2418// defined for them.
2419const BiggestInt kMaxBiggestInt =
2420 ~(static_cast<BiggestInt>(1) << (8*sizeof(BiggestInt) - 1));

2422// This template class serves as a compile-time function from size to
2423// type. It maps a size in bytes to a primitive type with that
2424// size. e.g.
2425//
2426// TypeWithSize<4>::UInt
2427//
2428// is typedef-ed to be unsigned int (unsigned integer made up of 4
2429// bytes).
2430//
2431// Such functionality should belong to STL, but I cannot find it
2432// there.
2433//
2434// Google Test uses this class in the implementation of floating-point
2435// comparison.
2436//
2437// For now it only handles UInt (unsigned int) as that's all Google Test
2438// needs. Other types can be easily added in the future if need
2439// arises.
2440template <size_t size>
2441class TypeWithSize {
2442 public:
2443 // This prevents the user from using TypeWithSize<N> with incorrect
2444 // values of N.
2445 typedef void UInt;
2446};
2447
2448// The specialization for size 4.
2449template <>
2450class TypeWithSize<4> {
2451 public:
2452 // unsigned int has size 4 in both gcc and MSVC.
2453 //
2454 // As base/basictypes.h doesn't compile on Windows, we cannot use
2455 // uint32, uint64, and etc here.
2456 typedef int Int;
2457 typedef unsigned int UInt;
2458};
2459
2460// The specialization for size 8.
2461template <>
2462class TypeWithSize<8> {
2463 public:
2464#if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
2465 typedef __int64 Int;
2466 typedef unsigned __int64 UInt;
2467#else
2468 typedef long long Int; // NOLINT
2469 typedef unsigned long long UInt; // NOLINT
2470#endif // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
2471};
2472
2473// Integer types of known sizes.
2474typedef TypeWithSize<4>::Int Int32;
2475typedef TypeWithSize<4>::UInt UInt32;
2476typedef TypeWithSize<8>::Int Int64;
2477typedef TypeWithSize<8>::UInt UInt64;
2478typedef TypeWithSize<8>::Int TimeInMillis; // Represents time in milliseconds.

2517// Parses 'str' for a 32-bit signed integer. If successful, writes the result
2518// to *value and returns true; otherwise leaves *value unchanged and returns
2519// false.
2520bool ParseInt32(const Message& src_text, const char* str, Int32* value);

2526std::string OutputFlagAlsoCheckEnvVar();
2527const char* StringFromGTestEnv(const char* flag, const char* default_val);

2612// Ensures that there is at least one operator<< in the global namespace.
2613// See Message& operator<<(...) below for why.
2614void operator<<(const testing::internal::Secret&, int);
2615
2616namespace testing {
2617
2618// The Message class works like an ostream repeater.
2619//
2620// Typical usage:
2621//
2622// 1. You stream a bunch of values to a Message object.
2623// It will remember the text in a stringstream.
2624// 2. Then you stream the Message object to an ostream.
2625// This causes the text in the Message to be streamed
2626// to the ostream.
2627//
2628// For example;
2629//
2630// testing::Message foo;
2631// foo << 1 << " != " << 2;
2632// std::cout << foo;
2633//
2634// will print "1 != 2".
2635//
2636// Message is not intended to be inherited from. In particular, its
2637// destructor is not virtual.
2638//
2639// Note that stringstream behaves differently in gcc and in MSVC. You
2640// can stream a NULL char pointer to it in the former, but not in the
2641// latter (it causes an access violation if you do). The Message
2642// class hides this difference by treating a NULL char pointer as
2643// "(null)".
2644class GTEST_API_ Message {
2645 private:
2646 // The type of basic IO manipulators (endl, ends, and flush) for
2647 // narrow streams.
2648 typedef std::ostream& (*BasicNarrowIoManip)(std::ostream&);
2649
2650 public:
2651 // Constructs an empty Message.
2652 Message();
2653
2654 // Copy constructor.
2655 Message(const Message& msg) : ss_(new ::std::stringstream) { // NOLINT
2656 *ss_ << msg.GetString();
2657 }
2658
2659 // Constructs a Message from a C-string.
2660 explicit Message(const char* str) : ss_(new ::std::stringstream) {
2661 *ss_ << str;
2662 }
2663
2664 // Streams a non-pointer value to this object.
2665 template <typename T>
2666 inline Message& operator <<(const T& val) {
2667 // Some libraries overload << for STL containers. These
2668 // overloads are defined in the global namespace instead of ::std.
2669 //
2670 // C++'s symbol lookup rule (i.e. Koenig lookup) says that these
2671 // overloads are visible in either the std namespace or the global
2672 // namespace, but not other namespaces, including the testing
2673 // namespace which Google Test's Message class is in.
2674 //
2675 // To allow STL containers (and other types that has a << operator
2676 // defined in the global namespace) to be used in Google Test
2677 // assertions, testing::Message must access the custom << operator
2678 // from the global namespace. With this using declaration,
2679 // overloads of << defined in the global namespace and those
2680 // visible via Koenig lookup are both exposed in this function.
2681 using ::operator <<;
2682 *ss_ << val;
2683 return *this;
2684 }
2685
2686 // Streams a pointer value to this object.
2687 //
2688 // This function is an overload of the previous one. When you
2689 // stream a pointer to a Message, this definition will be used as it
2690 // is more specialized. (The C++ Standard, section
2691 // [temp.func.order].) If you stream a non-pointer, then the
2692 // previous definition will be used.
2693 //
2694 // The reason for this overload is that streaming a NULL pointer to
2695 // ostream is undefined behavior. Depending on the compiler, you
2696 // may get "0", "(nil)", "(null)", or an access violation. To
2697 // ensure consistent result across compilers, we always treat NULL
2698 // as "(null)".
2699 template <typename T>
2700 inline Message& operator <<(T* const& pointer) { // NOLINT
2701 if (pointer == nullptr) {
2702 *ss_ << "(null)";
2703 } else {
2704 *ss_ << pointer;
2705 }
2706 return *this;
2707 }
2708
2709 // Since the basic IO manipulators are overloaded for both narrow
2710 // and wide streams, we have to provide this specialized definition
2711 // of operator <<, even though its body is the same as the
2712 // templatized version above. Without this definition, streaming
2713 // endl or other basic IO manipulators to Message will confuse the
2714 // compiler.
2715 Message& operator <<(BasicNarrowIoManip val) {
2716 *ss_ << val;
2717 return *this;
2718 }
2719
2720 // Instead of 1/0, we want to see true/false for bool values.
2721 Message& operator <<(bool b) {
2722 return *this << (b ? "true" : "false");
2723 }
2724
2725 // These two overloads allow streaming a wide C string to a Message
2726 // using the UTF-8 encoding.
2727 Message& operator <<(const wchar_t* wide_c_str);
2728 Message& operator <<(wchar_t* wide_c_str);
2729
2730#if GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
2731 // Converts the given wide string to a narrow string using the UTF-8
2732 // encoding, and streams the result to this Message object.
2733 Message& operator <<(const ::std::wstring& wstr);
2734#endif // GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
2735
2736#if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
2737 // Converts the given wide string to a narrow string using the UTF-8
2738 // encoding, and streams the result to this Message object.
2739 Message& operator <<(const ::wstring& wstr);
2740#endif // GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
2741
2742 // Gets the text streamed to this object so far as an std::string.
2743 // Each '\0' character in the buffer is replaced with "\\0".
2744 //
2745 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
2746 std::string GetString() const;
2747
2748 private:
2749 // We'll hold the text streamed to this object here.
2750 const std::unique_ptr< ::std::stringstream> ss_;
2751
2752 // We declare (but don't implement) this to prevent the compiler
2753 // from implementing the assignment operator.
2754 void operator=(const Message&);
2755};
2756
2757// Streams a Message to an ostream.
2758inline std::ostream& operator <<(std::ostream& os, const Message& sb) {
2759 return os << sb.GetString();
2760}
2761
2762namespace internal {
2763
2764// Converts a streamable value to an std::string. A NULL pointer is
2765// converted to "(null)". When the input value is a ::string,
2766// ::std::string, ::wstring, or ::std::wstring object, each NUL
2767// character in it is replaced with "\\0".
2768template <typename T>
2769std::string StreamableToString(const T& streamable) {
2770 return (Message() << streamable).GetString();
2771}
2772
2773} // namespace internal
2774} // namespace testing

2876// String - an abstract class holding static string utilities.
2877class GTEST_API_ String {
2878 public:
2879 // Static utility methods
2880
2881 // Clones a 0-terminated C string, allocating memory using new. The
2882 // caller is responsible for deleting the return value using
2883 // delete[]. Returns the cloned string, or NULL if the input is
2884 // NULL.
2885 //
2886 // This is different from strdup() in string.h, which allocates
2887 // memory using malloc().
2888 static const char* CloneCString(const char* c_str);
2889
2890#if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
2891 // Windows CE does not have the 'ANSI' versions of Win32 APIs. To be
2892 // able to pass strings to Win32 APIs on CE we need to convert them
2893 // to 'Unicode', UTF-16.
2894
2895 // Creates a UTF-16 wide string from the given ANSI string, allocating
2896 // memory using new. The caller is responsible for deleting the return
2897 // value using delete[]. Returns the wide string, or NULL if the
2898 // input is NULL.
2899 //
2900 // The wide string is created using the ANSI codepage (CP_ACP) to
2901 // match the behaviour of the ANSI versions of Win32 calls and the
2902 // C runtime.
2903 static LPCWSTR AnsiToUtf16(const char* c_str);
2904
2905 // Creates an ANSI string from the given wide string, allocating
2906 // memory using new. The caller is responsible for deleting the return
2907 // value using delete[]. Returns the ANSI string, or NULL if the
2908 // input is NULL.
2909 //
2910 // The returned string is created using the ANSI codepage (CP_ACP) to
2911 // match the behaviour of the ANSI versions of Win32 calls and the
2912 // C runtime.
2913 static const char* Utf16ToAnsi(LPCWSTR utf16_str);
2914#endif
2915
2916 // Compares two C strings. Returns true iff they have the same content.
2917 //
2918 // Unlike strcmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s). A
2919 // NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL C string,
2920 // including the empty string.
2921 static bool CStringEquals(const char* lhs, const char* rhs);
2922
2923 // Converts a wide C string to a String using the UTF-8 encoding.
2924 // NULL will be converted to "(null)". If an error occurred during
2925 // the conversion, "(failed to convert from wide string)" is
2926 // returned.
2927 static std::string ShowWideCString(const wchar_t* wide_c_str);
2928
2929 // Compares two wide C strings. Returns true iff they have the same
2930 // content.
2931 //
2932 // Unlike wcscmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s). A
2933 // NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL C string,
2934 // including the empty string.
2935 static bool WideCStringEquals(const wchar_t* lhs, const wchar_t* rhs);
2936
2937 // Compares two C strings, ignoring case. Returns true iff they
2938 // have the same content.
2939 //
2940 // Unlike strcasecmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s).
2941 // A NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL C string,
2942 // including the empty string.
2943 static bool CaseInsensitiveCStringEquals(const char* lhs,
2944 const char* rhs);
2945
2946 // Compares two wide C strings, ignoring case. Returns true iff they
2947 // have the same content.
2948 //
2949 // Unlike wcscasecmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s).
2950 // A NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL wide C string,
2951 // including the empty string.
2952 // NB: The implementations on different platforms slightly differ.
2953 // On windows, this method uses _wcsicmp which compares according to LC_CTYPE
2954 // environment variable. On GNU platform this method uses wcscasecmp
2955 // which compares according to LC_CTYPE category of the current locale.
2956 // On MacOS X, it uses towlower, which also uses LC_CTYPE category of the
2957 // current locale.
2958 static bool CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(const wchar_t* lhs,
2959 const wchar_t* rhs);
2960
2961 // Returns true iff the given string ends with the given suffix, ignoring
2962 // case. Any string is considered to end with an empty suffix.
2963 static bool EndsWithCaseInsensitive(
2964 const std::string& str, const std::string& suffix);
2965
2966 // Formats an int value as "%02d".
2967 static std::string FormatIntWidth2(int value); // "%02d" for width == 2
2968
2969 // Formats an int value as "%X".
2970 static std::string FormatHexInt(int value);
2971
2972 // Formats a byte as "%02X".
2973 static std::string FormatByte(unsigned char value);
2974
2975 private:
2976 String(); // Not meant to be instantiated.
2977}; // class String

2979// Gets the content of the stringstream's buffer as an std::string. Each '\0'
2980// character in the buffer is replaced with "\\0".
2981GTEST_API_ std::string StringStreamToString(::std::stringstream* stream);

2983} // namespace internal
2984} // namespace testing
