8128// Prints the given number of bytes in the given object to the given
8129// ostream.
8130GTEST_API_ void PrintBytesInObjectTo(const unsigned char* obj_bytes,
8131 size_t count,
8132 ::std::ostream* os);
8133
8134// For selecting which printer to use when a given type has neither <<
8135// nor PrintTo().
8136enum TypeKind {
8137 kProtobuf, // a protobuf type
8138 kConvertibleToInteger, // a type implicitly convertible to BiggestInt
8139 // (e.g. a named or unnamed enum type)
8140#if GTEST_HAS_ABSL
8141 kConvertibleToStringView, // a type implicitly convertible to
8142 // absl::string_view
8143#endif
8144 kOtherType // anything else
8145};
8146
8147// TypeWithoutFormatter<T, kTypeKind>::PrintValue(value, os) is called
8148// by the universal printer to print a value of type T when neither
8149// operator<< nor PrintTo() is defined for T, where kTypeKind is the
8150// "kind" of T as defined by enum TypeKind.
8151template <typename T, TypeKind kTypeKind>
8152class TypeWithoutFormatter {
8153 public:
8154 // This default version is called when kTypeKind is kOtherType.
8155 static void PrintValue(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8156 PrintBytesInObjectTo(static_cast<const unsigned char*>(
8157 reinterpret_cast<const void*>(&value)),
8158 sizeof(value), os);
8159 }
8160};
8161
8162// We print a protobuf using its ShortDebugString() when the string
8163// doesn't exceed this many characters; otherwise we print it using
8164// DebugString() for better readability.
8165const size_t kProtobufOneLinerMaxLength = 50;
8166
8167template <typename T>
8168class TypeWithoutFormatter<T, kProtobuf> {
8169 public:
8170 static void PrintValue(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8171 std::string pretty_str = value.ShortDebugString();
8172 if (pretty_str.length() > kProtobufOneLinerMaxLength) {
8173 pretty_str = "\n" + value.DebugString();
8174 }
8175 *os << ("<" + pretty_str + ">");
8176 }
8177};
8178
8179template <typename T>
8180class TypeWithoutFormatter<T, kConvertibleToInteger> {
8181 public:
8182 // Since T has no << operator or PrintTo() but can be implicitly
8183 // converted to BiggestInt, we print it as a BiggestInt.
8184 //
8185 // Most likely T is an enum type (either named or unnamed), in which
8186 // case printing it as an integer is the desired behavior. In case
8187 // T is not an enum, printing it as an integer is the best we can do
8188 // given that it has no user-defined printer.
8189 static void PrintValue(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8190 const internal::BiggestInt kBigInt = value;
8191 *os << kBigInt;
8192 }
8193};
8194
8195#if GTEST_HAS_ABSL
8196template <typename T>
8197class TypeWithoutFormatter<T, kConvertibleToStringView> {
8198 public:
8199 // Since T has neither operator<< nor PrintTo() but can be implicitly
8200 // converted to absl::string_view, we print it as a absl::string_view.
8201 //
8202 // Note: the implementation is further below, as it depends on
8203 // internal::PrintTo symbol which is defined later in the file.
8204 static void PrintValue(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os);
8205};
8206#endif
8207
8208// Prints the given value to the given ostream. If the value is a
8209// protocol message, its debug string is printed; if it's an enum or
8210// of a type implicitly convertible to BiggestInt, it's printed as an
8211// integer; otherwise the bytes in the value are printed. This is
8212// what UniversalPrinter<T>::Print() does when it knows nothing about
8213// type T and T has neither << operator nor PrintTo().
8214//
8215// A user can override this behavior for a class type Foo by defining
8216// a << operator in the namespace where Foo is defined.
8217//
8218// We put this operator in namespace 'internal2' instead of 'internal'
8219// to simplify the implementation, as much code in 'internal' needs to
8220// use << in STL, which would conflict with our own << were it defined
8221// in 'internal'.
8222//
8223// Note that this operator<< takes a generic std::basic_ostream<Char,
8224// CharTraits> type instead of the more restricted std::ostream. If
8225// we define it to take an std::ostream instead, we'll get an
8226// "ambiguous overloads" compiler error when trying to print a type
8227// Foo that supports streaming to std::basic_ostream<Char,
8228// CharTraits>, as the compiler cannot tell whether
8229// operator<<(std::ostream&, const T&) or
8230// operator<<(std::basic_stream<Char, CharTraits>, const Foo&) is more
8231// specific.
8232template <typename Char, typename CharTraits, typename T>
8233::std::basic_ostream<Char, CharTraits>& operator<<(
8234 ::std::basic_ostream<Char, CharTraits>& os, const T& x) {
8235 TypeWithoutFormatter<T, (internal::IsAProtocolMessage<T>::value
8236 ? kProtobuf
8237 : std::is_convertible<
8238 const T&, internal::BiggestInt>::value
8239 ? kConvertibleToInteger
8240 :
8241#if GTEST_HAS_ABSL
8242 std::is_convertible<
8243 const T&, absl::string_view>::value
8244 ? kConvertibleToStringView
8245 :
8246#endif
8247 kOtherType)>::PrintValue(x, &os);
8248 return os;
8249}
8250
8251} // namespace internal2
8252} // namespace testing
8253
8254// This namespace MUST NOT BE NESTED IN ::testing, or the name look-up
8255// magic needed for implementing UniversalPrinter won't work.
8256namespace testing_internal {
8257
8258// Used to print a value that is not an STL-style container when the
8259// user doesn't define PrintTo() for it.
8260template <typename T>
8261void DefaultPrintNonContainerTo(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8262 // With the following statement, during unqualified name lookup,
8263 // testing::internal2::operator<< appears as if it was declared in
8264 // the nearest enclosing namespace that contains both
8265 // ::testing_internal and ::testing::internal2, i.e. the global
8266 // namespace. For more details, refer to the C++ Standard section
8267 // 7.3.4-1 [namespace.udir]. This allows us to fall back onto
8268 // testing::internal2::operator<< in case T doesn't come with a <<
8269 // operator.
8270 //
8271 // We cannot write 'using ::testing::internal2::operator<<;', which
8272 // gcc 3.3 fails to compile due to a compiler bug.
8273 using namespace ::testing::internal2; // NOLINT
8274
8275 // Assuming T is defined in namespace foo, in the next statement,
8276 // the compiler will consider all of:
8277 //
8278 // 1. foo::operator<< (thanks to Koenig look-up),
8279 // 2. ::operator<< (as the current namespace is enclosed in ::),
8280 // 3. testing::internal2::operator<< (thanks to the using statement above).
8281 //
8282 // The operator<< whose type matches T best will be picked.
8283 //
8284 // We deliberately allow #2 to be a candidate, as sometimes it's
8285 // impossible to define #1 (e.g. when foo is ::std, defining
8286 // anything in it is undefined behavior unless you are a compiler
8287 // vendor.).
8288 *os << value;
8289}
8290
8291} // namespace testing_internal
8292
8293namespace testing {
8294namespace internal {
8295
8296// FormatForComparison<ToPrint, OtherOperand>::Format(value) formats a
8297// value of type ToPrint that is an operand of a comparison assertion
8298// (e.g. ASSERT_EQ). OtherOperand is the type of the other operand in
8299// the comparison, and is used to help determine the best way to
8300// format the value. In particular, when the value is a C string
8301// (char pointer) and the other operand is an STL string object, we
8302// want to format the C string as a string, since we know it is
8303// compared by value with the string object. If the value is a char
8304// pointer but the other operand is not an STL string object, we don't
8305// know whether the pointer is supposed to point to a NUL-terminated
8306// string, and thus want to print it as a pointer to be safe.
8307//
8308// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
8309
8310// The default case.
8311template <typename ToPrint, typename OtherOperand>
8312class FormatForComparison {
8313 public:
8314 static ::std::string Format(const ToPrint& value) {
8315 return ::testing::PrintToString(value);
8316 }
8317};
8318
8319// Array.
8320template <typename ToPrint, size_t N, typename OtherOperand>
8321class FormatForComparison<ToPrint[N], OtherOperand> {
8322 public:
8323 static ::std::string Format(const ToPrint* value) {
8324 return FormatForComparison<const ToPrint*, OtherOperand>::Format(value);
8325 }
8326};
8327
8328// By default, print C string as pointers to be safe, as we don't know
8329// whether they actually point to a NUL-terminated string.
8330
8331#define GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_POINTER_(CharType) \
8332 template <typename OtherOperand> \
8333 class FormatForComparison<CharType*, OtherOperand> { \
8334 public: \
8335 static ::std::string Format(CharType* value) { \
8336 return ::testing::PrintToString(static_cast<const void*>(value)); \
8337 } \
8338 }
8339
8340GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_POINTER_(char);
8341GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_POINTER_(const char);
8342GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_POINTER_(wchar_t);
8343GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_POINTER_(const wchar_t);
8344
8345#undef GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_POINTER_
8346
8347// If a C string is compared with an STL string object, we know it's meant
8348// to point to a NUL-terminated string, and thus can print it as a string.
8349
8350#define GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_(CharType, OtherStringType) \
8351 template <> \
8352 class FormatForComparison<CharType*, OtherStringType> { \
8353 public: \
8354 static ::std::string Format(CharType* value) { \
8355 return ::testing::PrintToString(value); \
8356 } \
8357 }
8358
8359GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_(char, ::std::string);
8360GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_(const char, ::std::string);
8361
8362#if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
8363GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_(char, ::string);
8364GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_(const char, ::string);
8365#endif
8366
8367#if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
8368GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_(wchar_t, ::wstring);
8369GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_(const wchar_t, ::wstring);
8370#endif
8371
8372#if GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
8373GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_(wchar_t, ::std::wstring);
8374GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_(const wchar_t, ::std::wstring);
8375#endif
8376
8377#undef GTEST_IMPL_FORMAT_C_STRING_AS_STRING_
8378
8379// Formats a comparison assertion (e.g. ASSERT_EQ, EXPECT_LT, and etc)
8380// operand to be used in a failure message. The type (but not value)
8381// of the other operand may affect the format. This allows us to
8382// print a char* as a raw pointer when it is compared against another
8383// char* or void*, and print it as a C string when it is compared
8384// against an std::string object, for example.
8385//
8386// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
8387template <typename T1, typename T2>
8388std::string FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(
8389 const T1& value, const T2& /* other_operand */) {
8390 return FormatForComparison<T1, T2>::Format(value);
8391}
8392
8393// UniversalPrinter<T>::Print(value, ostream_ptr) prints the given
8394// value to the given ostream. The caller must ensure that
8395// 'ostream_ptr' is not NULL, or the behavior is undefined.
8396//
8397// We define UniversalPrinter as a class template (as opposed to a
8398// function template), as we need to partially specialize it for
8399// reference types, which cannot be done with function templates.
8400template <typename T>
8401class UniversalPrinter;
8402
8403template <typename T>
8404void UniversalPrint(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os);
8405
8406enum DefaultPrinterType {
8407 kPrintContainer,
8408 kPrintPointer,
8409 kPrintFunctionPointer,
8410 kPrintOther,
8411};
8412template <DefaultPrinterType type> struct WrapPrinterType {};
8413
8414// Used to print an STL-style container when the user doesn't define
8415// a PrintTo() for it.
8416template <typename C>
8417void DefaultPrintTo(WrapPrinterType<kPrintContainer> /* dummy */,
8418 const C& container, ::std::ostream* os) {
8419 const size_t kMaxCount = 32; // The maximum number of elements to print.
8420 *os << '{';
8421 size_t count = 0;
8422 for (typename C::const_iterator it = container.begin();
8423 it != container.end(); ++it, ++count) {
8424 if (count > 0) {
8425 *os << ',';
8426 if (count == kMaxCount) { // Enough has been printed.
8427 *os << " ...";
8428 break;
8429 }
8430 }
8431 *os << ' ';
8432 // We cannot call PrintTo(*it, os) here as PrintTo() doesn't
8433 // handle *it being a native array.
8434 internal::UniversalPrint(*it, os);
8435 }
8436
8437 if (count > 0) {
8438 *os << ' ';
8439 }
8440 *os << '}';
8441}
8442
8443// Used to print a pointer that is neither a char pointer nor a member
8444// pointer, when the user doesn't define PrintTo() for it. (A member
8445// variable pointer or member function pointer doesn't really point to
8446// a location in the address space. Their representation is
8447// implementation-defined. Therefore they will be printed as raw
8448// bytes.)
8449template <typename T>
8450void DefaultPrintTo(WrapPrinterType<kPrintPointer> /* dummy */,
8451 T* p, ::std::ostream* os) {
8452 if (p == nullptr) {
8453 *os << "NULL";
8454 } else {
8455 // T is not a function type. We just call << to print p,
8456 // relying on ADL to pick up user-defined << for their pointer
8457 // types, if any.
8458 *os << p;
8459 }
8460}
8461template <typename T>
8462void DefaultPrintTo(WrapPrinterType<kPrintFunctionPointer> /* dummy */,
8463 T* p, ::std::ostream* os) {
8464 if (p == nullptr) {
8465 *os << "NULL";
8466 } else {
8467 // T is a function type, so '*os << p' doesn't do what we want
8468 // (it just prints p as bool). We want to print p as a const
8469 // void*.
8470 *os << reinterpret_cast<const void*>(p);
8471 }
8472}
8473
8474// Used to print a non-container, non-pointer value when the user
8475// doesn't define PrintTo() for it.
8476template <typename T>
8477void DefaultPrintTo(WrapPrinterType<kPrintOther> /* dummy */,
8478 const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8479 ::testing_internal::DefaultPrintNonContainerTo(value, os);
8480}
8481
8482// Prints the given value using the << operator if it has one;
8483// otherwise prints the bytes in it. This is what
8484// UniversalPrinter<T>::Print() does when PrintTo() is not specialized
8485// or overloaded for type T.
8486//
8487// A user can override this behavior for a class type Foo by defining
8488// an overload of PrintTo() in the namespace where Foo is defined. We
8489// give the user this option as sometimes defining a << operator for
8490// Foo is not desirable (e.g. the coding style may prevent doing it,
8491// or there is already a << operator but it doesn't do what the user
8492// wants).
8493template <typename T>
8494void PrintTo(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8495 // DefaultPrintTo() is overloaded. The type of its first argument
8496 // determines which version will be picked.
8497 //
8498 // Note that we check for container types here, prior to we check
8499 // for protocol message types in our operator<<. The rationale is:
8500 //
8501 // For protocol messages, we want to give people a chance to
8502 // override Google Mock's format by defining a PrintTo() or
8503 // operator<<. For STL containers, other formats can be
8504 // incompatible with Google Mock's format for the container
8505 // elements; therefore we check for container types here to ensure
8506 // that our format is used.
8507 //
8508 // Note that MSVC and clang-cl do allow an implicit conversion from
8509 // pointer-to-function to pointer-to-object, but clang-cl warns on it.
8510 // So don't use ImplicitlyConvertible if it can be helped since it will
8511 // cause this warning, and use a separate overload of DefaultPrintTo for
8512 // function pointers so that the `*os << p` in the object pointer overload
8513 // doesn't cause that warning either.
8514 DefaultPrintTo(
8515 WrapPrinterType <
8516 (sizeof(IsContainerTest<T>(0)) == sizeof(IsContainer)) &&
8517 !IsRecursiveContainer<T>::value
8518 ? kPrintContainer
8519 : !std::is_pointer<T>::value
8520 ? kPrintOther
8521 : std::is_function<typename std::remove_pointer<T>::type>::value
8522 ? kPrintFunctionPointer
8523 : kPrintPointer > (),
8524 value, os);
8525}
8526
8527// The following list of PrintTo() overloads tells
8528// UniversalPrinter<T>::Print() how to print standard types (built-in
8529// types, strings, plain arrays, and pointers).
8530
8531// Overloads for various char types.
8532GTEST_API_ void PrintTo(unsigned char c, ::std::ostream* os);
8533GTEST_API_ void PrintTo(signed char c, ::std::ostream* os);
8534inline void PrintTo(char c, ::std::ostream* os) {
8535 // When printing a plain char, we always treat it as unsigned. This
8536 // way, the output won't be affected by whether the compiler thinks
8537 // char is signed or not.
8538 PrintTo(static_cast<unsigned char>(c), os);
8539}
8540
8541// Overloads for other simple built-in types.
8542inline void PrintTo(bool x, ::std::ostream* os) {
8543 *os << (x ? "true" : "false");
8544}
8545
8546// Overload for wchar_t type.
8547// Prints a wchar_t as a symbol if it is printable or as its internal
8548// code otherwise and also as its decimal code (except for L'\0').
8549// The L'\0' char is printed as "L'\\0'". The decimal code is printed
8550// as signed integer when wchar_t is implemented by the compiler
8551// as a signed type and is printed as an unsigned integer when wchar_t
8552// is implemented as an unsigned type.
8553GTEST_API_ void PrintTo(wchar_t wc, ::std::ostream* os);
8554
8555// Overloads for C strings.
8556GTEST_API_ void PrintTo(const char* s, ::std::ostream* os);
8557inline void PrintTo(char* s, ::std::ostream* os) {
8558 PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const char*>(s), os);
8559}
8560
8561// signed/unsigned char is often used for representing binary data, so
8562// we print pointers to it as void* to be safe.
8563inline void PrintTo(const signed char* s, ::std::ostream* os) {
8564 PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const void*>(s), os);
8565}
8566inline void PrintTo(signed char* s, ::std::ostream* os) {
8567 PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const void*>(s), os);
8568}
8569inline void PrintTo(const unsigned char* s, ::std::ostream* os) {
8570 PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const void*>(s), os);
8571}
8572inline void PrintTo(unsigned char* s, ::std::ostream* os) {
8573 PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const void*>(s), os);
8574}
8575
8576// MSVC can be configured to define wchar_t as a typedef of unsigned
8577// short. It defines _NATIVE_WCHAR_T_DEFINED when wchar_t is a native
8578// type. When wchar_t is a typedef, defining an overload for const
8579// wchar_t* would cause unsigned short* be printed as a wide string,
8580// possibly causing invalid memory accesses.
8581#if !defined(_MSC_VER) || defined(_NATIVE_WCHAR_T_DEFINED)
8582// Overloads for wide C strings
8583GTEST_API_ void PrintTo(const wchar_t* s, ::std::ostream* os);
8584inline void PrintTo(wchar_t* s, ::std::ostream* os) {
8585 PrintTo(ImplicitCast_<const wchar_t*>(s), os);
8586}
8587#endif
8588
8589// Overload for C arrays. Multi-dimensional arrays are printed
8590// properly.
8591
8592// Prints the given number of elements in an array, without printing
8593// the curly braces.
8594template <typename T>
8595void PrintRawArrayTo(const T a[], size_t count, ::std::ostream* os) {
8596 UniversalPrint(a[0], os);
8597 for (size_t i = 1; i != count; i++) {
8598 *os << ", ";
8599 UniversalPrint(a[i], os);
8600 }
8601}

8641void PrintTo(std::reference_wrapper<T> ref, ::std::ostream* os) {

8643 PrintTo(ref.get(), os);

8646// Helper function for printing a tuple. T must be instantiated with
8647// a tuple type.
8648template <typename T>
8649void PrintTupleTo(const T&, std::integral_constant<size_t, 0>,
8650 ::std::ostream*) {}
8651
8652template <typename T, size_t I>
8653void PrintTupleTo(const T& t, std::integral_constant<size_t, I>,
8654 ::std::ostream* os) {
8655 PrintTupleTo(t, std::integral_constant<size_t, I - 1>(), os);
8656 GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_PUSH_()
8657 if (I > 1) {
8658 GTEST_INTENTIONAL_CONST_COND_POP_()
8659 *os << ", ";
8660 }
8661 UniversalPrinter<typename std::tuple_element<I - 1, T>::type>::Print(
8662 std::get<I - 1>(t), os);
8663}
8664
8665template <typename... Types>
8666void PrintTo(const ::std::tuple<Types...>& t, ::std::ostream* os) {
8667 *os << "(";
8668 PrintTupleTo(t, std::integral_constant<size_t, sizeof...(Types)>(), os);
8669 *os << ")";
8670}
8671
8672// Overload for std::pair.
8673template <typename T1, typename T2>
8674void PrintTo(const ::std::pair<T1, T2>& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8675 *os << '(';
8676 // We cannot use UniversalPrint(value.first, os) here, as T1 may be
8677 // a reference type. The same for printing value.second.
8678 UniversalPrinter<T1>::Print(value.first, os);
8679 *os << ", ";
8680 UniversalPrinter<T2>::Print(value.second, os);
8681 *os << ')';
8682}
8683
8684// Implements printing a non-reference type T by letting the compiler
8685// pick the right overload of PrintTo() for T.
8686template <typename T>
8687class UniversalPrinter {
8688 public:
8689 // MSVC warns about adding const to a function type, so we want to
8690 // disable the warning.
8691 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(4180)
8692
8693 // Note: we deliberately don't call this PrintTo(), as that name
8694 // conflicts with ::testing::internal::PrintTo in the body of the
8695 // function.
8696 static void Print(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8697 // By default, ::testing::internal::PrintTo() is used for printing
8698 // the value.
8699 //
8700 // Thanks to Koenig look-up, if T is a class and has its own
8701 // PrintTo() function defined in its namespace, that function will
8702 // be visible here. Since it is more specific than the generic ones
8703 // in ::testing::internal, it will be picked by the compiler in the
8704 // following statement - exactly what we want.
8705 PrintTo(value, os);
8706 }
8707
8708 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_()
8709};
8710
8711#if GTEST_HAS_ABSL
8712
8713// Printer for absl::optional
8714
8715template <typename T>
8716class UniversalPrinter<::absl::optional<T>> {
8717 public:
8718 static void Print(const ::absl::optional<T>& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8719 *os << '(';
8720 if (!value) {
8721 *os << "nullopt";
8722 } else {
8723 UniversalPrint(*value, os);
8724 }
8725 *os << ')';
8726 }
8727};
8728
8729// Printer for absl::variant
8730
8731template <typename... T>
8732class UniversalPrinter<::absl::variant<T...>> {
8733 public:
8734 static void Print(const ::absl::variant<T...>& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8735 *os << '(';
8736 absl::visit(Visitor{os}, value);
8737 *os << ')';
8738 }
8739
8740 private:
8741 struct Visitor {
8742 template <typename U>
8743 void operator()(const U& u) const {
8744 *os << "'" << GetTypeName<U>() << "' with value ";
8745 UniversalPrint(u, os);
8746 }
8747 ::std::ostream* os;
8748 };
8749};
8750
8751#endif // GTEST_HAS_ABSL
8752
8753// UniversalPrintArray(begin, len, os) prints an array of 'len'
8754// elements, starting at address 'begin'.
8755template <typename T>
8756void UniversalPrintArray(const T* begin, size_t len, ::std::ostream* os) {
8757 if (len == 0) {
8758 *os << "{}";
8759 } else {
8760 *os << "{ ";
8761 const size_t kThreshold = 18;
8762 const size_t kChunkSize = 8;
8763 // If the array has more than kThreshold elements, we'll have to
8764 // omit some details by printing only the first and the last
8765 // kChunkSize elements.
8766 if (len <= kThreshold) {
8767 PrintRawArrayTo(begin, len, os);
8768 } else {
8769 PrintRawArrayTo(begin, kChunkSize, os);
8770 *os << ", ..., ";
8771 PrintRawArrayTo(begin + len - kChunkSize, kChunkSize, os);
8772 }
8773 *os << " }";
8774 }
8775}
8776// This overload prints a (const) char array compactly.
8777GTEST_API_ void UniversalPrintArray(
8778 const char* begin, size_t len, ::std::ostream* os);
8779
8780// This overload prints a (const) wchar_t array compactly.
8781GTEST_API_ void UniversalPrintArray(
8782 const wchar_t* begin, size_t len, ::std::ostream* os);
8783
8784// Implements printing an array type T[N].
8785template <typename T, size_t N>
8786class UniversalPrinter<T[N]> {
8787 public:
8788 // Prints the given array, omitting some elements when there are too
8789 // many.
8790 static void Print(const T (&a)[N], ::std::ostream* os) {
8791 UniversalPrintArray(a, N, os);
8792 }
8793};
8794
8795// Implements printing a reference type T&.
8796template <typename T>
8797class UniversalPrinter<T&> {
8798 public:
8799 // MSVC warns about adding const to a function type, so we want to
8800 // disable the warning.
8801 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(4180)
8802
8803 static void Print(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8804 // Prints the address of the value. We use reinterpret_cast here
8805 // as static_cast doesn't compile when T is a function type.
8806 *os << "@" << reinterpret_cast<const void*>(&value) << " ";
8807
8808 // Then prints the value itself.
8809 UniversalPrint(value, os);
8810 }
8811
8812 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_()
8813};
8814
8815// Prints a value tersely: for a reference type, the referenced value
8816// (but not the address) is printed; for a (const) char pointer, the
8817// NUL-terminated string (but not the pointer) is printed.
8818
8819template <typename T>
8820class UniversalTersePrinter {
8821 public:
8822 static void Print(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8823 UniversalPrint(value, os);
8824 }
8825};
8826template <typename T>
8827class UniversalTersePrinter<T&> {
8828 public:
8829 static void Print(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8830 UniversalPrint(value, os);
8831 }
8832};
8833template <typename T, size_t N>
8834class UniversalTersePrinter<T[N]> {
8835 public:
8836 static void Print(const T (&value)[N], ::std::ostream* os) {
8837 UniversalPrinter<T[N]>::Print(value, os);
8838 }
8839};
8840template <>
8841class UniversalTersePrinter<const char*> {
8842 public:
8843 static void Print(const char* str, ::std::ostream* os) {
8844 if (str == nullptr) {
8845 *os << "NULL";
8846 } else {
8847 UniversalPrint(std::string(str), os);
8848 }
8849 }
8850};
8851template <>
8852class UniversalTersePrinter<char*> {
8853 public:
8854 static void Print(char* str, ::std::ostream* os) {
8855 UniversalTersePrinter<const char*>::Print(str, os);
8856 }
8857};
8858
8859#if GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING
8860template <>
8861class UniversalTersePrinter<const wchar_t*> {
8862 public:
8863 static void Print(const wchar_t* str, ::std::ostream* os) {
8864 if (str == nullptr) {
8865 *os << "NULL";
8866 } else {
8867 UniversalPrint(::std::wstring(str), os);
8868 }
8869 }
8870};
8871#endif
8872
8873template <>
8874class UniversalTersePrinter<wchar_t*> {
8875 public:
8876 static void Print(wchar_t* str, ::std::ostream* os) {
8877 UniversalTersePrinter<const wchar_t*>::Print(str, os);
8878 }
8879};
8880
8881template <typename T>
8882void UniversalTersePrint(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8883 UniversalTersePrinter<T>::Print(value, os);
8884}
8885
8886// Prints a value using the type inferred by the compiler. The
8887// difference between this and UniversalTersePrint() is that for a
8888// (const) char pointer, this prints both the pointer and the
8889// NUL-terminated string.
8890template <typename T>
8891void UniversalPrint(const T& value, ::std::ostream* os) {
8892 // A workarond for the bug in VC++ 7.1 that prevents us from instantiating
8893 // UniversalPrinter with T directly.
8894 typedef T T1;
8895 UniversalPrinter<T1>::Print(value, os);
8896}
8897
8898typedef ::std::vector< ::std::string> Strings;
8899
8900 // Tersely prints the first N fields of a tuple to a string vector,
8901 // one element for each field.
8902template <typename Tuple>
8903void TersePrintPrefixToStrings(const Tuple&, std::integral_constant<size_t, 0>,
8904 Strings*) {}
8905template <typename Tuple, size_t I>
8906void TersePrintPrefixToStrings(const Tuple& t,
8907 std::integral_constant<size_t, I>,
8908 Strings* strings) {
8909 TersePrintPrefixToStrings(t, std::integral_constant<size_t, I - 1>(),
8910 strings);
8911 ::std::stringstream ss;
8912 UniversalTersePrint(std::get<I - 1>(t), &ss);
8913 strings->push_back(ss.str());
8914}
8915
8916// Prints the fields of a tuple tersely to a string vector, one
8917// element for each field. See the comment before
8918// UniversalTersePrint() for how we define "tersely".
8919template <typename Tuple>
8920Strings UniversalTersePrintTupleFieldsToStrings(const Tuple& value) {
8921 Strings result;
8922 TersePrintPrefixToStrings(
8923 value, std::integral_constant<size_t, std::tuple_size<Tuple>::value>(),
8924 &result);
8925 return result;
8926}

8997GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(
8998 4251 5046 /* class A needs to have dll-interface to be used by clients of
8999 class B */
9000 /* Symbol involving type with internal linkage not defined */)
9001
9002namespace testing {
9003
9004// To implement a matcher Foo for type T, define:
9005// 1. a class FooMatcherImpl that implements the
9006// MatcherInterface<T> interface, and
9007// 2. a factory function that creates a Matcher<T> object from a
9008// FooMatcherImpl*.
9009//
9010// The two-level delegation design makes it possible to allow a user
9011// to write "v" instead of "Eq(v)" where a Matcher is expected, which
9012// is impossible if we pass matchers by pointers. It also eases
9013// ownership management as Matcher objects can now be copied like
9014// plain values.
9015
9016// MatchResultListener is an abstract class. Its << operator can be
9017// used by a matcher to explain why a value matches or doesn't match.
9018//
9019class MatchResultListener {
9020 public:
9021 // Creates a listener object with the given underlying ostream. The
9022 // listener does not own the ostream, and does not dereference it
9023 // in the constructor or destructor.
9024 explicit MatchResultListener(::std::ostream* os) : stream_(os) {}
9025 virtual ~MatchResultListener() = 0; // Makes this class abstract.
9026
9027 // Streams x to the underlying ostream; does nothing if the ostream
9028 // is NULL.
9029 template <typename T>
9030 MatchResultListener& operator<<(const T& x) {
9031 if (stream_ != nullptr) *stream_ << x;
9032 return *this;
9033 }
9034
9035 // Returns the underlying ostream.
9036 ::std::ostream* stream() { return stream_; }
9037
9038 // Returns true iff the listener is interested in an explanation of
9039 // the match result. A matcher's MatchAndExplain() method can use
9040 // this information to avoid generating the explanation when no one
9041 // intends to hear it.
9042 bool IsInterested() const { return stream_ != nullptr; }
9043
9044 private:
9045 ::std::ostream* const stream_;
9046
9047 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(MatchResultListener);
9048};
9049
9050inline MatchResultListener::~MatchResultListener() {
9051}
9052
9053// An instance of a subclass of this knows how to describe itself as a
9054// matcher.
9055class MatcherDescriberInterface {
9056 public:
9057 virtual ~MatcherDescriberInterface() {}
9058
9059 // Describes this matcher to an ostream. The function should print
9060 // a verb phrase that describes the property a value matching this
9061 // matcher should have. The subject of the verb phrase is the value
9062 // being matched. For example, the DescribeTo() method of the Gt(7)
9063 // matcher prints "is greater than 7".
9064 virtual void DescribeTo(::std::ostream* os) const = 0;
9065
9066 // Describes the negation of this matcher to an ostream. For
9067 // example, if the description of this matcher is "is greater than
9068 // 7", the negated description could be "is not greater than 7".
9069 // You are not required to override this when implementing
9070 // MatcherInterface, but it is highly advised so that your matcher
9071 // can produce good error messages.
9072 virtual void DescribeNegationTo(::std::ostream* os) const {
9073 *os << "not (";
9074 DescribeTo(os);
9075 *os << ")";
9076 }
9077};
9078
9079// The implementation of a matcher.
9080template <typename T>
9081class MatcherInterface : public MatcherDescriberInterface {
9082 public:
9083 // Returns true iff the matcher matches x; also explains the match
9084 // result to 'listener' if necessary (see the next paragraph), in
9085 // the form of a non-restrictive relative clause ("which ...",
9086 // "whose ...", etc) that describes x. For example, the
9087 // MatchAndExplain() method of the Pointee(...) matcher should
9088 // generate an explanation like "which points to ...".
9089 //
9090 // Implementations of MatchAndExplain() should add an explanation of
9091 // the match result *if and only if* they can provide additional
9092 // information that's not already present (or not obvious) in the
9093 // print-out of x and the matcher's description. Whether the match
9094 // succeeds is not a factor in deciding whether an explanation is
9095 // needed, as sometimes the caller needs to print a failure message
9096 // when the match succeeds (e.g. when the matcher is used inside
9097 // Not()).
9098 //
9099 // For example, a "has at least 10 elements" matcher should explain
9100 // what the actual element count is, regardless of the match result,
9101 // as it is useful information to the reader; on the other hand, an
9102 // "is empty" matcher probably only needs to explain what the actual
9103 // size is when the match fails, as it's redundant to say that the
9104 // size is 0 when the value is already known to be empty.
9105 //
9106 // You should override this method when defining a new matcher.
9107 //
9108 // It's the responsibility of the caller (Google Test) to guarantee
9109 // that 'listener' is not NULL. This helps to simplify a matcher's
9110 // implementation when it doesn't care about the performance, as it
9111 // can talk to 'listener' without checking its validity first.
9112 // However, in order to implement dummy listeners efficiently,
9113 // listener->stream() may be NULL.
9114 virtual bool MatchAndExplain(T x, MatchResultListener* listener) const = 0;
9115
9116 // Inherits these methods from MatcherDescriberInterface:
9117 // virtual void DescribeTo(::std::ostream* os) const = 0;
9118 // virtual void DescribeNegationTo(::std::ostream* os) const;
9119};
9120
9121namespace internal {
9122
9123// Converts a MatcherInterface<T> to a MatcherInterface<const T&>.
9124template <typename T>
9125class MatcherInterfaceAdapter : public MatcherInterface<const T&> {
9126 public:
9127 explicit MatcherInterfaceAdapter(const MatcherInterface<T>* impl)
9128 : impl_(impl) {}
9129 ~MatcherInterfaceAdapter() override { delete impl_; }
9130
9131 void DescribeTo(::std::ostream* os) const override { impl_->DescribeTo(os); }
9132
9133 void DescribeNegationTo(::std::ostream* os) const override {
9134 impl_->DescribeNegationTo(os);
9135 }
9136
9137 bool MatchAndExplain(const T& x,
9138 MatchResultListener* listener) const override {
9139 return impl_->MatchAndExplain(x, listener);
9140 }
9141
9142 private:
9143 const MatcherInterface<T>* const impl_;
9144
9145 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(MatcherInterfaceAdapter);
9146};

9148struct AnyEq {
9149 template <typename A, typename B>
9150 bool operator()(const A& a, const B& b) const { return a == b; }
9151};
9152struct AnyNe {
9153 template <typename A, typename B>
9154 bool operator()(const A& a, const B& b) const { return a != b; }
9155};
9156struct AnyLt {
9157 template <typename A, typename B>
9158 bool operator()(const A& a, const B& b) const { return a < b; }
9159};
9160struct AnyGt {
9161 template <typename A, typename B>
9162 bool operator()(const A& a, const B& b) const { return a > b; }
9163};
9164struct AnyLe {
9165 template <typename A, typename B>
9166 bool operator()(const A& a, const B& b) const { return a <= b; }
9167};
9168struct AnyGe {
9169 template <typename A, typename B>
9170 bool operator()(const A& a, const B& b) const { return a >= b; }
9171};

9173// A match result listener that ignores the explanation.
9174class DummyMatchResultListener : public MatchResultListener {
9175 public:
9176 DummyMatchResultListener() : MatchResultListener(nullptr) {}
9177
9178 private:
9179 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(DummyMatchResultListener);
9180};
9181
9182// A match result listener that forwards the explanation to a given
9183// ostream. The difference between this and MatchResultListener is
9184// that the former is concrete.
9185class StreamMatchResultListener : public MatchResultListener {
9186 public:
9187 explicit StreamMatchResultListener(::std::ostream* os)
9188 : MatchResultListener(os) {}
9189
9190 private:
9191 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(StreamMatchResultListener);
9192};
9193
9194// An internal class for implementing Matcher<T>, which will derive
9195// from it. We put functionalities common to all Matcher<T>
9196// specializations here to avoid code duplication.
9197template <typename T>
9198class MatcherBase {
9199 public:
9200 // Returns true iff the matcher matches x; also explains the match
9201 // result to 'listener'.
9202 bool MatchAndExplain(const T& x, MatchResultListener* listener) const {
9203 return impl_->MatchAndExplain(x, listener);
9204 }
9205
9206 // Returns true iff this matcher matches x.
9207 bool Matches(const T& x) const {
9208 DummyMatchResultListener dummy;
9209 return MatchAndExplain(x, &dummy);
9210 }
9211
9212 // Describes this matcher to an ostream.
9213 void DescribeTo(::std::ostream* os) const { impl_->DescribeTo(os); }
9214
9215 // Describes the negation of this matcher to an ostream.
9216 void DescribeNegationTo(::std::ostream* os) const {
9217 impl_->DescribeNegationTo(os);
9218 }
9219
9220 // Explains why x matches, or doesn't match, the matcher.
9221 void ExplainMatchResultTo(const T& x, ::std::ostream* os) const {
9222 StreamMatchResultListener listener(os);
9223 MatchAndExplain(x, &listener);
9224 }
9225
9226 // Returns the describer for this matcher object; retains ownership
9227 // of the describer, which is only guaranteed to be alive when
9228 // this matcher object is alive.
9229 const MatcherDescriberInterface* GetDescriber() const {
9230 return impl_.get();
9231 }
9232
9233 protected:
9234 MatcherBase() {}
9235
9236 // Constructs a matcher from its implementation.
9237 explicit MatcherBase(const MatcherInterface<const T&>* impl) : impl_(impl) {}
9238
9239 template <typename U>
9240 explicit MatcherBase(
9241 const MatcherInterface<U>* impl,
9242 typename internal::EnableIf<
9243 !internal::IsSame<U, const U&>::value>::type* = nullptr)
9244 : impl_(new internal::MatcherInterfaceAdapter<U>(impl)) {}
9245
9246 MatcherBase(const MatcherBase&) = default;
9247 MatcherBase& operator=(const MatcherBase&) = default;
9248 MatcherBase(MatcherBase&&) = default;
9249 MatcherBase& operator=(MatcherBase&&) = default;
9250
9251 virtual ~MatcherBase() {}
9252
9253 private:
9254 std::shared_ptr<const MatcherInterface<const T&>> impl_;
9255};
9256
9257} // namespace internal
9258
9259// A Matcher<T> is a copyable and IMMUTABLE (except by assignment)
9260// object that can check whether a value of type T matches. The
9261// implementation of Matcher<T> is just a std::shared_ptr to const
9262// MatcherInterface<T>. Don't inherit from Matcher!
9263template <typename T>
9264class Matcher : public internal::MatcherBase<T> {
9265 public:
9266 // Constructs a null matcher. Needed for storing Matcher objects in STL
9267 // containers. A default-constructed matcher is not yet initialized. You
9268 // cannot use it until a valid value has been assigned to it.
9269 explicit Matcher() {} // NOLINT
9270
9271 // Constructs a matcher from its implementation.
9272 explicit Matcher(const MatcherInterface<const T&>* impl)
9273 : internal::MatcherBase<T>(impl) {}
9274
9275 template <typename U>
9276 explicit Matcher(const MatcherInterface<U>* impl,
9277 typename internal::EnableIf<
9278 !internal::IsSame<U, const U&>::value>::type* = nullptr)
9279 : internal::MatcherBase<T>(impl) {}
9280
9281 // Implicit constructor here allows people to write
9282 // EXPECT_CALL(foo, Bar(5)) instead of EXPECT_CALL(foo, Bar(Eq(5))) sometimes
9283 Matcher(T value); // NOLINT
9284};

9445// Prints a matcher in a human-readable format.
9446template <typename T>
9447std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, const Matcher<T>& matcher) {
9448 matcher.DescribeTo(&os);
9449 return os;
9450}

9452// The PolymorphicMatcher class template makes it easy to implement a
9453// polymorphic matcher (i.e. a matcher that can match values of more
9454// than one type, e.g. Eq(n) and NotNull()).
9455//
9456// To define a polymorphic matcher, a user should provide an Impl
9457// class that has a DescribeTo() method and a DescribeNegationTo()
9458// method, and define a member function (or member function template)
9459//
9460// bool MatchAndExplain(const Value& value,
9461// MatchResultListener* listener) const;
9462//
9463// See the definition of NotNull() for a complete example.
9464template <class Impl>
9465class PolymorphicMatcher {
9466 public:
9467 explicit PolymorphicMatcher(const Impl& an_impl) : impl_(an_impl) {}
9468
9469 // Returns a mutable reference to the underlying matcher
9470 // implementation object.
9471 Impl& mutable_impl() { return impl_; }
9472
9473 // Returns an immutable reference to the underlying matcher
9474 // implementation object.
9475 const Impl& impl() const { return impl_; }
9476
9477 template <typename T>
9478 operator Matcher<T>() const {
9479 return Matcher<T>(new MonomorphicImpl<const T&>(impl_));
9480 }
9481
9482 private:
9483 template <typename T>
9484 class MonomorphicImpl : public MatcherInterface<T> {
9485 public:
9486 explicit MonomorphicImpl(const Impl& impl) : impl_(impl) {}
9487
9488 virtual void DescribeTo(::std::ostream* os) const { impl_.DescribeTo(os); }
9489
9490 virtual void DescribeNegationTo(::std::ostream* os) const {
9491 impl_.DescribeNegationTo(os);
9492 }
9493
9494 virtual bool MatchAndExplain(T x, MatchResultListener* listener) const {
9495 return impl_.MatchAndExplain(x, listener);
9496 }
9497
9498 private:
9499 const Impl impl_;
9500 };
9501
9502 Impl impl_;
9503};
9504
9505// Creates a matcher from its implementation. This is easier to use
9506// than the Matcher<T> constructor as it doesn't require you to
9507// explicitly write the template argument, e.g.
9508//
9509// MakeMatcher(foo);
9510// vs
9511// Matcher<const string&>(foo);
9512template <typename T>
9513inline Matcher<T> MakeMatcher(const MatcherInterface<T>* impl) {
9514 return Matcher<T>(impl);
9515}
9516
9517// Creates a polymorphic matcher from its implementation. This is
9518// easier to use than the PolymorphicMatcher<Impl> constructor as it
9519// doesn't require you to explicitly write the template argument, e.g.
9520//
9521// MakePolymorphicMatcher(foo);
9522// vs
9523// PolymorphicMatcher<TypeOfFoo>(foo);
9524template <class Impl>
9525inline PolymorphicMatcher<Impl> MakePolymorphicMatcher(const Impl& impl) {
9526 return PolymorphicMatcher<Impl>(impl);
9527}

9529namespace internal {
9530// Implements a matcher that compares a given value with a
9531// pre-supplied value using one of the ==, <=, <, etc, operators. The
9532// two values being compared don't have to have the same type.
9533//
9534// The matcher defined here is polymorphic (for example, Eq(5) can be
9535// used to match an int, a short, a double, etc). Therefore we use
9536// a template type conversion operator in the implementation.
9537//
9538// The following template definition assumes that the Rhs parameter is
9539// a "bare" type (i.e. neither 'const T' nor 'T&').
9540template <typename D, typename Rhs, typename Op>
9541class ComparisonBase {
9542 public:
9543 explicit ComparisonBase(const Rhs& rhs) : rhs_(rhs) {}
9544 template <typename Lhs>
9545 operator Matcher<Lhs>() const {
9546 return MakeMatcher(new Impl<Lhs>(rhs_));
9547 }
9548
9549 private:
9550 template <typename Lhs>
9551 class Impl : public MatcherInterface<Lhs> {
9552 public:
9553 explicit Impl(const Rhs& rhs) : rhs_(rhs) {}
9554 bool MatchAndExplain(Lhs lhs,
9555 MatchResultListener* /* listener */) const override {
9556 return Op()(lhs, rhs_);
9557 }
9558 void DescribeTo(::std::ostream* os) const override {
9559 *os << D::Desc() << " ";
9560 UniversalPrint(rhs_, os);
9561 }
9562 void DescribeNegationTo(::std::ostream* os) const override {
9563 *os << D::NegatedDesc() << " ";
9564 UniversalPrint(rhs_, os);
9565 }
9566
9567 private:
9568 Rhs rhs_;
9569 };
9570 Rhs rhs_;
9571};
9572
9573template <typename Rhs>
9574class EqMatcher : public ComparisonBase<EqMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyEq> {
9575 public:
9576 explicit EqMatcher(const Rhs& rhs)
9577 : ComparisonBase<EqMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyEq>(rhs) { }
9578 static const char* Desc() { return "is equal to"; }
9579 static const char* NegatedDesc() { return "isn't equal to"; }
9580};
9581template <typename Rhs>
9582class NeMatcher : public ComparisonBase<NeMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyNe> {
9583 public:
9584 explicit NeMatcher(const Rhs& rhs)
9585 : ComparisonBase<NeMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyNe>(rhs) { }
9586 static const char* Desc() { return "isn't equal to"; }
9587 static const char* NegatedDesc() { return "is equal to"; }
9588};
9589template <typename Rhs>
9590class LtMatcher : public ComparisonBase<LtMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyLt> {
9591 public:
9592 explicit LtMatcher(const Rhs& rhs)
9593 : ComparisonBase<LtMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyLt>(rhs) { }
9594 static const char* Desc() { return "is <"; }
9595 static const char* NegatedDesc() { return "isn't <"; }
9596};
9597template <typename Rhs>
9598class GtMatcher : public ComparisonBase<GtMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyGt> {
9599 public:
9600 explicit GtMatcher(const Rhs& rhs)
9601 : ComparisonBase<GtMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyGt>(rhs) { }
9602 static const char* Desc() { return "is >"; }
9603 static const char* NegatedDesc() { return "isn't >"; }
9604};
9605template <typename Rhs>
9606class LeMatcher : public ComparisonBase<LeMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyLe> {
9607 public:
9608 explicit LeMatcher(const Rhs& rhs)
9609 : ComparisonBase<LeMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyLe>(rhs) { }
9610 static const char* Desc() { return "is <="; }
9611 static const char* NegatedDesc() { return "isn't <="; }
9612};
9613template <typename Rhs>
9614class GeMatcher : public ComparisonBase<GeMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyGe> {
9615 public:
9616 explicit GeMatcher(const Rhs& rhs)
9617 : ComparisonBase<GeMatcher<Rhs>, Rhs, AnyGe>(rhs) { }
9618 static const char* Desc() { return "is >="; }
9619 static const char* NegatedDesc() { return "isn't >="; }
9620};
9621
9622// Implements polymorphic matchers MatchesRegex(regex) and
9623// ContainsRegex(regex), which can be used as a Matcher<T> as long as
9624// T can be converted to a string.
9625class MatchesRegexMatcher {
9626 public:
9627 MatchesRegexMatcher(const RE* regex, bool full_match)
9628 : regex_(regex), full_match_(full_match) {}
9629
9630#if GTEST_HAS_ABSL
9631 bool MatchAndExplain(const absl::string_view& s,
9632 MatchResultListener* listener) const {
9633 return MatchAndExplain(string(s), listener);
9634 }
9635#endif // GTEST_HAS_ABSL
9636
9637 // Accepts pointer types, particularly:
9638 // const char*
9639 // char*
9640 // const wchar_t*
9641 // wchar_t*
9642 template <typename CharType>
9643 bool MatchAndExplain(CharType* s, MatchResultListener* listener) const {
9644 return s != nullptr && MatchAndExplain(std::string(s), listener);
9645 }
9646
9647 // Matches anything that can convert to std::string.
9648 //
9649 // This is a template, not just a plain function with const std::string&,
9650 // because absl::string_view has some interfering non-explicit constructors.
9651 template <class MatcheeStringType>
9652 bool MatchAndExplain(const MatcheeStringType& s,
9653 MatchResultListener* /* listener */) const {
9654 const std::string& s2(s);
9655 return full_match_ ? RE::FullMatch(s2, *regex_)
9656 : RE::PartialMatch(s2, *regex_);
9657 }
9658
9659 void DescribeTo(::std::ostream* os) const {
9660 *os << (full_match_ ? "matches" : "contains") << " regular expression ";
9661 UniversalPrinter<std::string>::Print(regex_->pattern(), os);
9662 }
9663
9664 void DescribeNegationTo(::std::ostream* os) const {
9665 *os << "doesn't " << (full_match_ ? "match" : "contain")
9666 << " regular expression ";
9667 UniversalPrinter<std::string>::Print(regex_->pattern(), os);
9668 }
9669
9670 private:
9671 const std::shared_ptr<const RE> regex_;
9672 const bool full_match_;
9673};
9674} // namespace internal
9675
9676// Matches a string that fully matches regular expression 'regex'.
9677// The matcher takes ownership of 'regex'.
9678inline PolymorphicMatcher<internal::MatchesRegexMatcher> MatchesRegex(
9679 const internal::RE* regex) {
9680 return MakePolymorphicMatcher(internal::MatchesRegexMatcher(regex, true));
9681}
9682inline PolymorphicMatcher<internal::MatchesRegexMatcher> MatchesRegex(
9683 const std::string& regex) {
9684 return MatchesRegex(new internal::RE(regex));
9685}
9686
9687// Matches a string that contains regular expression 'regex'.
9688// The matcher takes ownership of 'regex'.
9689inline PolymorphicMatcher<internal::MatchesRegexMatcher> ContainsRegex(
9690 const internal::RE* regex) {
9691 return MakePolymorphicMatcher(internal::MatchesRegexMatcher(regex, false));
9692}
9693inline PolymorphicMatcher<internal::MatchesRegexMatcher> ContainsRegex(
9694 const std::string& regex) {
9695 return ContainsRegex(new internal::RE(regex));
9696}
9697
9698// Creates a polymorphic matcher that matches anything equal to x.
9699// Note: if the parameter of Eq() were declared as const T&, Eq("foo")
9700// wouldn't compile.
9701template <typename T>
9702inline internal::EqMatcher<T> Eq(T x) { return internal::EqMatcher<T>(x); }
9703
9704// Constructs a Matcher<T> from a 'value' of type T. The constructed
9705// matcher matches any value that's equal to 'value'.
9706template <typename T>
9707Matcher<T>::Matcher(T value) { *this = Eq(value); }
9708
9709// Creates a monomorphic matcher that matches anything with type Lhs
9710// and equal to rhs. A user may need to use this instead of Eq(...)
9711// in order to resolve an overloading ambiguity.
9712//
9713// TypedEq<T>(x) is just a convenient short-hand for Matcher<T>(Eq(x))
9714// or Matcher<T>(x), but more readable than the latter.
9715//
9716// We could define similar monomorphic matchers for other comparison
9717// operations (e.g. TypedLt, TypedGe, and etc), but decided not to do
9718// it yet as those are used much less than Eq() in practice. A user
9719// can always write Matcher<T>(Lt(5)) to be explicit about the type,
9720// for example.
9721template <typename Lhs, typename Rhs>
9722inline Matcher<Lhs> TypedEq(const Rhs& rhs) { return Eq(rhs); }
9723
9724// Creates a polymorphic matcher that matches anything >= x.
9725template <typename Rhs>
9726inline internal::GeMatcher<Rhs> Ge(Rhs x) {
9727 return internal::GeMatcher<Rhs>(x);
9728}
9729
9730// Creates a polymorphic matcher that matches anything > x.
9731template <typename Rhs>
9732inline internal::GtMatcher<Rhs> Gt(Rhs x) {
9733 return internal::GtMatcher<Rhs>(x);
9734}
9735
9736// Creates a polymorphic matcher that matches anything <= x.
9737template <typename Rhs>
9738inline internal::LeMatcher<Rhs> Le(Rhs x) {
9739 return internal::LeMatcher<Rhs>(x);
9740}
9741
9742// Creates a polymorphic matcher that matches anything < x.
9743template <typename Rhs>
9744inline internal::LtMatcher<Rhs> Lt(Rhs x) {
9745 return internal::LtMatcher<Rhs>(x);
9746}
9747
9748// Creates a polymorphic matcher that matches anything != x.
9749template <typename Rhs>
9750inline internal::NeMatcher<Rhs> Ne(Rhs x) {
9751 return internal::NeMatcher<Rhs>(x);
9752}
9753} // namespace testing

9757#endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_MATCHERS_H_

9768const char kDeathTestStyleFlag[] = "death_test_style";
9769const char kDeathTestUseFork[] = "death_test_use_fork";

9774GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(4251 \
9775/* class A needs to have dll-interface to be used by clients of class B */)
9776
9777// DeathTest is a class that hides much of the complexity of the
9778// GTEST_DEATH_TEST_ macro. It is abstract; its static Create method
9779// returns a concrete class that depends on the prevailing death test
9780// style, as defined by the --gtest_death_test_style and/or
9781// --gtest_internal_run_death_test flags.
9782
9783// In describing the results of death tests, these terms are used with
9784// the corresponding definitions:
9785//
9786// exit status: The integer exit information in the format specified
9787// by wait(2)
9788// exit code: The integer code passed to exit(3), _exit(2), or
9789// returned from main()
9790class GTEST_API_ DeathTest {
9791 public:
9792 // Create returns false if there was an error determining the
9793 // appropriate action to take for the current death test; for example,
9794 // if the gtest_death_test_style flag is set to an invalid value.
9795 // The LastMessage method will return a more detailed message in that
9796 // case. Otherwise, the DeathTest pointer pointed to by the "test"
9797 // argument is set. If the death test should be skipped, the pointer
9798 // is set to NULL; otherwise, it is set to the address of a new concrete
9799 // DeathTest object that controls the execution of the current test.
9800 static bool Create(const char* statement, Matcher<const std::string&> matcher,
9801 const char* file, int line, DeathTest** test);
9802 DeathTest();
9803 virtual ~DeathTest() { }
9804
9805 // A helper class that aborts a death test when it's deleted.
9806 class ReturnSentinel {
9807 public:
9808 explicit ReturnSentinel(DeathTest* test) : test_(test) { }
9809 ~ReturnSentinel() { test_->Abort(TEST_ENCOUNTERED_RETURN_STATEMENT); }
9810 private:
9811 DeathTest* const test_;
9812 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ReturnSentinel);
9813 } GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_;
9814
9815 // An enumeration of possible roles that may be taken when a death
9816 // test is encountered. EXECUTE means that the death test logic should
9817 // be executed immediately. OVERSEE means that the program should prepare
9818 // the appropriate environment for a child process to execute the death
9819 // test, then wait for it to complete.
9820 enum TestRole { OVERSEE_TEST, EXECUTE_TEST };
9821
9822 // An enumeration of the three reasons that a test might be aborted.
9823 enum AbortReason {
9824 TEST_ENCOUNTERED_RETURN_STATEMENT,
9825 TEST_THREW_EXCEPTION,
9826 TEST_DID_NOT_DIE
9827 };
9828
9829 // Assumes one of the above roles.
9830 virtual TestRole AssumeRole() = 0;
9831
9832 // Waits for the death test to finish and returns its status.
9833 virtual int Wait() = 0;
9834
9835 // Returns true if the death test passed; that is, the test process
9836 // exited during the test, its exit status matches a user-supplied
9837 // predicate, and its stderr output matches a user-supplied regular
9838 // expression.
9839 // The user-supplied predicate may be a macro expression rather
9840 // than a function pointer or functor, or else Wait and Passed could
9841 // be combined.
9842 virtual bool Passed(bool exit_status_ok) = 0;
9843
9844 // Signals that the death test did not die as expected.
9845 virtual void Abort(AbortReason reason) = 0;
9846
9847 // Returns a human-readable outcome message regarding the outcome of
9848 // the last death test.
9849 static const char* LastMessage();
9850
9851 static void set_last_death_test_message(const std::string& message);
9852
9853 private:
9854 // A string containing a description of the outcome of the last death test.
9855 static std::string last_death_test_message_;
9856
9857 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(DeathTest);
9858};
9859
9860GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_() // 4251
9861
9862// Factory interface for death tests. May be mocked out for testing.
9863class DeathTestFactory {
9864 public:
9865 virtual ~DeathTestFactory() { }
9866 virtual bool Create(const char* statement,
9867 Matcher<const std::string&> matcher, const char* file,
9868 int line, DeathTest** test) = 0;
9869};
9870
9871// A concrete DeathTestFactory implementation for normal use.
9872class DefaultDeathTestFactory : public DeathTestFactory {
9873 public:
9874 bool Create(const char* statement, Matcher<const std::string&> matcher,
9875 const char* file, int line, DeathTest** test) override;
9876};

9878// Returns true if exit_status describes a process that was terminated
9879// by a signal, or exited normally with a nonzero exit code.
9880GTEST_API_ bool ExitedUnsuccessfully(int exit_status);
9881
9882// A string passed to EXPECT_DEATH (etc.) is caught by one of these overloads
9883// and interpreted as a regex (rather than an Eq matcher) for legacy
9884// compatibility.
9885inline Matcher<const ::std::string&> MakeDeathTestMatcher(
9886 ::testing::internal::RE regex) {
9887 return ContainsRegex(regex.pattern());
9888}
9889inline Matcher<const ::std::string&> MakeDeathTestMatcher(const char* regex) {
9890 return ContainsRegex(regex);
9891}
9892inline Matcher<const ::std::string&> MakeDeathTestMatcher(
9893 const ::std::string& regex) {
9894 return ContainsRegex(regex);
9895}
9896#if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
9897inline Matcher<const ::std::string&> MakeDeathTestMatcher(
9898 const ::string& regex) {
9899 return ContainsRegex(regex);
9900}
9901#endif
9902
9903// If a Matcher<const ::std::string&> is passed to EXPECT_DEATH (etc.), it's
9904// used directly.
9905inline Matcher<const ::std::string&> MakeDeathTestMatcher(
9906 Matcher<const ::std::string&> matcher) {
9907 return matcher;
9908}
9909
9910// Traps C++ exceptions escaping statement and reports them as test
9911// failures. Note that trapping SEH exceptions is not implemented here.
9912# if GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
9913# define GTEST_EXECUTE_DEATH_TEST_STATEMENT_(statement, death_test) \
9914 try { \
9915 GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement); \
9916 } catch (const ::std::exception& gtest_exception) { \
9917 fprintf(\
9918 stderr, \
9919 "\n%s: Caught std::exception-derived exception escaping the " \
9920 "death test statement. Exception message: %s\n", \
9921 ::testing::internal::FormatFileLocation(__FILE__, __LINE__).c_str(), \
9922 gtest_exception.what()); \
9923 fflush(stderr); \
9924 death_test->Abort(::testing::internal::DeathTest::TEST_THREW_EXCEPTION); \
9925 } catch (...) { \
9926 death_test->Abort(::testing::internal::DeathTest::TEST_THREW_EXCEPTION); \
9927 }
9928
9929# else
9930# define GTEST_EXECUTE_DEATH_TEST_STATEMENT_(statement, death_test) \
9931 GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement)
9932
9933# endif
9934
9935// This macro is for implementing ASSERT_DEATH*, EXPECT_DEATH*,
9936// ASSERT_EXIT*, and EXPECT_EXIT*.
9937#define GTEST_DEATH_TEST_(statement, predicate, regex_or_matcher, fail) \
9938 GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
9939 if (::testing::internal::AlwaysTrue()) { \
9940 ::testing::internal::DeathTest* gtest_dt; \
9941 if (!::testing::internal::DeathTest::Create( \
9942 #statement, \
9943 ::testing::internal::MakeDeathTestMatcher(regex_or_matcher), \
9944 __FILE__, __LINE__, &gtest_dt)) { \
9945 goto GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_, __LINE__); \
9946 } \
9947 if (gtest_dt != nullptr) { \
9948 std::unique_ptr< ::testing::internal::DeathTest> gtest_dt_ptr(gtest_dt); \
9949 switch (gtest_dt->AssumeRole()) { \
9950 case ::testing::internal::DeathTest::OVERSEE_TEST: \
9951 if (!gtest_dt->Passed(predicate(gtest_dt->Wait()))) { \
9952 goto GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_, __LINE__); \
9953 } \
9954 break; \
9955 case ::testing::internal::DeathTest::EXECUTE_TEST: { \
9956 ::testing::internal::DeathTest::ReturnSentinel gtest_sentinel( \
9957 gtest_dt); \
9958 GTEST_EXECUTE_DEATH_TEST_STATEMENT_(statement, gtest_dt); \
9959 gtest_dt->Abort(::testing::internal::DeathTest::TEST_DID_NOT_DIE); \
9960 break; \
9961 } \
9962 default: \
9963 break; \
9964 } \
9965 } \
9966 } else \
9967 GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_label_, __LINE__) \
9968 : fail(::testing::internal::DeathTest::LastMessage())
9969// The symbol "fail" here expands to something into which a message
9970// can be streamed.
9971
9972// This macro is for implementing ASSERT/EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH when compiled in
9973// NDEBUG mode. In this case we need the statements to be executed and the macro
9974// must accept a streamed message even though the message is never printed.
9975// The regex object is not evaluated, but it is used to prevent "unused"
9976// warnings and to avoid an expression that doesn't compile in debug mode.
9977#define GTEST_EXECUTE_STATEMENT_(statement, regex_or_matcher) \
9978 GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
9979 if (::testing::internal::AlwaysTrue()) { \
9980 GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement); \
9981 } else if (!::testing::internal::AlwaysTrue()) { \
9982 ::testing::internal::MakeDeathTestMatcher(regex_or_matcher); \
9983 } else \
9984 ::testing::Message()
9985

9987// --gtest_internal_run_death_test flag, as it existed when
9988// RUN_ALL_TESTS was called.

9999 if (write_fd_ >= 0)

10001 }

10004 int line() const { return line_; }
10005 int index() const { return index_; }
10006 int write_fd() const { return write_fd_; }
10007
10008 private:
10009 std::string file_;

10031// This flag controls the style of death tests. Valid values are "threadsafe",
10032// meaning that the death test child process will re-execute the test binary
10033// from the start, running only a single death test, or "fast",
10034// meaning that the child process will execute the test logic immediately
10035// after forking.
10036GTEST_DECLARE_string_(death_test_style);
10037
10038#if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
10039
10040namespace internal {
10041
10042// Returns a Boolean value indicating whether the caller is currently
10043// executing in the context of the death test child process. Tools such as
10044// Valgrind heap checkers may need this to modify their behavior in death
10045// tests. IMPORTANT: This is an internal utility. Using it may break the
10046// implementation of death tests. User code MUST NOT use it.
10047GTEST_API_ bool InDeathTestChild();
10048
10049} // namespace internal
10050
10051// The following macros are useful for writing death tests.
10052
10053// Here's what happens when an ASSERT_DEATH* or EXPECT_DEATH* is
10054// executed:
10055//
10056// 1. It generates a warning if there is more than one active
10057// thread. This is because it's safe to fork() or clone() only
10058// when there is a single thread.
10059//
10060// 2. The parent process clone()s a sub-process and runs the death
10061// test in it; the sub-process exits with code 0 at the end of the
10062// death test, if it hasn't exited already.
10063//
10064// 3. The parent process waits for the sub-process to terminate.
10065//
10066// 4. The parent process checks the exit code and error message of
10067// the sub-process.
10068//
10069// Examples:
10070//
10071// ASSERT_DEATH(server.SendMessage(56, "Hello"), "Invalid port number");
10072// for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
10073// EXPECT_DEATH(server.ProcessRequest(i),
10074// "Invalid request .* in ProcessRequest()")
10075// << "Failed to die on request " << i;
10076// }
10077//
10078// ASSERT_EXIT(server.ExitNow(), ::testing::ExitedWithCode(0), "Exiting");
10079//
10080// bool KilledBySIGHUP(int exit_code) {
10081// return WIFSIGNALED(exit_code) && WTERMSIG(exit_code) == SIGHUP;
10082// }
10083//
10084// ASSERT_EXIT(client.HangUpServer(), KilledBySIGHUP, "Hanging up!");
10085//
10086// On the regular expressions used in death tests:
10087//
10088// GOOGLETEST_CM0005 DO NOT DELETE
10089// On POSIX-compliant systems (*nix), we use the <regex.h> library,
10090// which uses the POSIX extended regex syntax.
10091//
10092// On other platforms (e.g. Windows or Mac), we only support a simple regex
10093// syntax implemented as part of Google Test. This limited
10094// implementation should be enough most of the time when writing
10095// death tests; though it lacks many features you can find in PCRE
10096// or POSIX extended regex syntax. For example, we don't support
10097// union ("x|y"), grouping ("(xy)"), brackets ("[xy]"), and
10098// repetition count ("x{5,7}"), among others.
10099//
10100// Below is the syntax that we do support. We chose it to be a
10101// subset of both PCRE and POSIX extended regex, so it's easy to
10102// learn wherever you come from. In the following: 'A' denotes a
10103// literal character, period (.), or a single \\ escape sequence;
10104// 'x' and 'y' denote regular expressions; 'm' and 'n' are for
10105// natural numbers.
10106//
10107// c matches any literal character c
10108// \\d matches any decimal digit
10109// \\D matches any character that's not a decimal digit
10110// \\f matches \f
10111// \\n matches \n
10112// \\r matches \r
10113// \\s matches any ASCII whitespace, including \n
10114// \\S matches any character that's not a whitespace
10115// \\t matches \t
10116// \\v matches \v
10117// \\w matches any letter, _, or decimal digit
10118// \\W matches any character that \\w doesn't match
10119// \\c matches any literal character c, which must be a punctuation
10120// . matches any single character except \n
10121// A? matches 0 or 1 occurrences of A
10122// A* matches 0 or many occurrences of A
10123// A+ matches 1 or many occurrences of A
10124// ^ matches the beginning of a string (not that of each line)
10125// $ matches the end of a string (not that of each line)
10126// xy matches x followed by y
10127//
10128// If you accidentally use PCRE or POSIX extended regex features
10129// not implemented by us, you will get a run-time failure. In that
10130// case, please try to rewrite your regular expression within the
10131// above syntax.
10132//
10133// This implementation is *not* meant to be as highly tuned or robust
10134// as a compiled regex library, but should perform well enough for a
10135// death test, which already incurs significant overhead by launching
10136// a child process.
10137//
10138// Known caveats:
10139//
10140// A "threadsafe" style death test obtains the path to the test
10141// program from argv[0] and re-executes it in the sub-process. For
10142// simplicity, the current implementation doesn't search the PATH
10143// when launching the sub-process. This means that the user must
10144// invoke the test program via a path that contains at least one
10145// path separator (e.g. path/to/foo_test and
10146// /absolute/path/to/bar_test are fine, but foo_test is not). This
10147// is rarely a problem as people usually don't put the test binary
10148// directory in PATH.
10149//
10150
10151// Asserts that a given statement causes the program to exit, with an
10152// integer exit status that satisfies predicate, and emitting error output
10153// that matches regex.
10154# define ASSERT_EXIT(statement, predicate, regex) \
10155 GTEST_DEATH_TEST_(statement, predicate, regex, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
10156
10157// Like ASSERT_EXIT, but continues on to successive tests in the
10158// test suite, if any:
10159# define EXPECT_EXIT(statement, predicate, regex) \
10160 GTEST_DEATH_TEST_(statement, predicate, regex, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
10161
10162// Asserts that a given statement causes the program to exit, either by
10163// explicitly exiting with a nonzero exit code or being killed by a
10164// signal, and emitting error output that matches regex.
10165# define ASSERT_DEATH(statement, regex) \
10166 ASSERT_EXIT(statement, ::testing::internal::ExitedUnsuccessfully, regex)
10167
10168// Like ASSERT_DEATH, but continues on to successive tests in the
10169// test suite, if any:
10170# define EXPECT_DEATH(statement, regex) \
10171 EXPECT_EXIT(statement, ::testing::internal::ExitedUnsuccessfully, regex)
10172
10173// Two predicate classes that can be used in {ASSERT,EXPECT}_EXIT*:
10174
10175// Tests that an exit code describes a normal exit with a given exit code.
10176class GTEST_API_ ExitedWithCode {
10177 public:
10178 explicit ExitedWithCode(int exit_code);
10179 bool operator()(int exit_status) const;
10180 private:
10181 // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
10182 void operator=(const ExitedWithCode& other);
10183
10184 const int exit_code_;
10185};
10186
10187# if !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS && !GTEST_OS_FUCHSIA
10188// Tests that an exit code describes an exit due to termination by a
10189// given signal.
10190// GOOGLETEST_CM0006 DO NOT DELETE
10191class GTEST_API_ KilledBySignal {
10192 public:
10193 explicit KilledBySignal(int signum);
10194 bool operator()(int exit_status) const;
10195 private:
10196 const int signum_;
10197};
10198# endif // !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
10199
10200// EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH asserts that the given statements die in debug mode.
10201// The death testing framework causes this to have interesting semantics,
10202// since the sideeffects of the call are only visible in opt mode, and not
10203// in debug mode.
10204//
10205// In practice, this can be used to test functions that utilize the
10206// LOG(DFATAL) macro using the following style:
10207//
10208// int DieInDebugOr12(int* sideeffect) {
10209// if (sideeffect) {
10210// *sideeffect = 12;
10211// }
10212// LOG(DFATAL) << "death";
10213// return 12;
10214// }
10215//
10216// TEST(TestSuite, TestDieOr12WorksInDgbAndOpt) {
10217// int sideeffect = 0;
10218// // Only asserts in dbg.
10219// EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH(DieInDebugOr12(&sideeffect), "death");
10220//
10221// #ifdef NDEBUG
10222// // opt-mode has sideeffect visible.
10223// EXPECT_EQ(12, sideeffect);
10224// #else
10225// // dbg-mode no visible sideeffect.
10226// EXPECT_EQ(0, sideeffect);
10227// #endif
10228// }
10229//
10230// This will assert that DieInDebugReturn12InOpt() crashes in debug
10231// mode, usually due to a DCHECK or LOG(DFATAL), but returns the
10232// appropriate fallback value (12 in this case) in opt mode. If you
10233// need to test that a function has appropriate side-effects in opt
10234// mode, include assertions against the side-effects. A general
10235// pattern for this is:
10236//
10237// EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH({
10238// // Side-effects here will have an effect after this statement in
10239// // opt mode, but none in debug mode.
10240// EXPECT_EQ(12, DieInDebugOr12(&sideeffect));
10241// }, "death");
10242//
10243# ifdef NDEBUG
10244
10245# define EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
10246 GTEST_EXECUTE_STATEMENT_(statement, regex)
10247
10248# define ASSERT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
10249 GTEST_EXECUTE_STATEMENT_(statement, regex)
10250
10251# else
10252
10253# define EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
10254 EXPECT_DEATH(statement, regex)
10255
10256# define ASSERT_DEBUG_DEATH(statement, regex) \
10257 ASSERT_DEATH(statement, regex)
10258
10259# endif // NDEBUG for EXPECT_DEBUG_DEATH
10260#endif // GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
10261
10262// This macro is used for implementing macros such as
10263// EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED and ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED on systems where
10264// death tests are not supported. Those macros must compile on such systems
10265// iff EXPECT_DEATH and ASSERT_DEATH compile with the same parameters on
10266// systems that support death tests. This allows one to write such a macro
10267// on a system that does not support death tests and be sure that it will
10268// compile on a death-test supporting system. It is exposed publicly so that
10269// systems that have death-tests with stricter requirements than
10270// GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST can write their own equivalent of
10271// EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED and ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED.
10272//
10273// Parameters:
10274// statement - A statement that a macro such as EXPECT_DEATH would test
10275// for program termination. This macro has to make sure this
10276// statement is compiled but not executed, to ensure that
10277// EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED compiles with a certain
10278// parameter iff EXPECT_DEATH compiles with it.
10279// regex - A regex that a macro such as EXPECT_DEATH would use to test
10280// the output of statement. This parameter has to be
10281// compiled but not evaluated by this macro, to ensure that
10282// this macro only accepts expressions that a macro such as
10283// EXPECT_DEATH would accept.
10284// terminator - Must be an empty statement for EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED
10285// and a return statement for ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED.
10286// This ensures that ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED will not
10287// compile inside functions where ASSERT_DEATH doesn't
10288// compile.
10289//
10290// The branch that has an always false condition is used to ensure that
10291// statement and regex are compiled (and thus syntactically correct) but
10292// never executed. The unreachable code macro protects the terminator
10293// statement from generating an 'unreachable code' warning in case
10294// statement unconditionally returns or throws. The Message constructor at
10295// the end allows the syntax of streaming additional messages into the
10296// macro, for compilational compatibility with EXPECT_DEATH/ASSERT_DEATH.
10297# define GTEST_UNSUPPORTED_DEATH_TEST(statement, regex, terminator) \
10298 GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
10299 if (::testing::internal::AlwaysTrue()) { \
10300 GTEST_LOG_(WARNING) \
10301 << "Death tests are not supported on this platform.\n" \
10302 << "Statement '" #statement "' cannot be verified."; \
10303 } else if (::testing::internal::AlwaysFalse()) { \
10304 ::testing::internal::RE::PartialMatch(".*", (regex)); \
10305 GTEST_SUPPRESS_UNREACHABLE_CODE_WARNING_BELOW_(statement); \
10306 terminator; \
10307 } else \
10308 ::testing::Message()
10309
10310// EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) and
10311// ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) expand to real death tests if
10312// death tests are supported; otherwise they just issue a warning. This is
10313// useful when you are combining death test assertions with normal test
10314// assertions in one test.
10315#if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
10316# define EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
10317 EXPECT_DEATH(statement, regex)
10318# define ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
10319 ASSERT_DEATH(statement, regex)
10320#else
10321# define EXPECT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
10322 GTEST_UNSUPPORTED_DEATH_TEST(statement, regex, )
10323# define ASSERT_DEATH_IF_SUPPORTED(statement, regex) \
10324 GTEST_UNSUPPORTED_DEATH_TEST(statement, regex, return)
10325#endif
10326
10327} // namespace testing
10328
10329#endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_DEATH_TEST_H_
