10373// Value-parameterized tests allow you to test your code with different
10374// parameters without writing multiple copies of the same test.
10375//
10376// Here is how you use value-parameterized tests:
10377
10378#if 0
10379
10380// To write value-parameterized tests, first you should define a fixture
10381// class. It is usually derived from testing::TestWithParam<T> (see below for
10382// another inheritance scheme that's sometimes useful in more complicated
10383// class hierarchies), where the type of your parameter values.
10384// TestWithParam<T> is itself derived from testing::Test. T can be any
10385// copyable type. If it's a raw pointer, you are responsible for managing the
10386// lifespan of the pointed values.
10387
10388class FooTest : public ::testing::TestWithParam<const char*> {
10389 // You can implement all the usual class fixture members here.
10390};
10391
10392// Then, use the TEST_P macro to define as many parameterized tests
10393// for this fixture as you want. The _P suffix is for "parameterized"
10394// or "pattern", whichever you prefer to think.
10395
10396TEST_P(FooTest, DoesBlah) {
10397 // Inside a test, access the test parameter with the GetParam() method
10398 // of the TestWithParam<T> class:
10399 EXPECT_TRUE(foo.Blah(GetParam()));
10400 ...
10401}
10402
10403TEST_P(FooTest, HasBlahBlah) {
10404 ...
10405}
10406
10407// Finally, you can use INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P to instantiate the test
10408// case with any set of parameters you want. Google Test defines a number
10409// of functions for generating test parameters. They return what we call
10410// (surprise!) parameter generators. Here is a summary of them, which
10411// are all in the testing namespace:
10412//
10413//
10414// Range(begin, end [, step]) - Yields values {begin, begin+step,
10415// begin+step+step, ...}. The values do not
10416// include end. step defaults to 1.
10417// Values(v1, v2, ..., vN) - Yields values {v1, v2, ..., vN}.
10418// ValuesIn(container) - Yields values from a C-style array, an STL
10419// ValuesIn(begin,end) container, or an iterator range [begin, end).
10420// Bool() - Yields sequence {false, true}.
10421// Combine(g1, g2, ..., gN) - Yields all combinations (the Cartesian product
10422// for the math savvy) of the values generated
10423// by the N generators.
10424//
10425// For more details, see comments at the definitions of these functions below
10426// in this file.
10427//
10428// The following statement will instantiate tests from the FooTest test suite
10429// each with parameter values "meeny", "miny", and "moe".
10430
10431INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(InstantiationName,
10432 FooTest,
10433 Values("meeny", "miny", "moe"));
10434
10435// To distinguish different instances of the pattern, (yes, you
10436// can instantiate it more then once) the first argument to the
10437// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P macro is a prefix that will be added to the
10438// actual test suite name. Remember to pick unique prefixes for different
10439// instantiations. The tests from the instantiation above will have
10440// these names:
10441//
10442// * InstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/0 for "meeny"
10443// * InstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/1 for "miny"
10444// * InstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/2 for "moe"
10445// * InstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/0 for "meeny"
10446// * InstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/1 for "miny"
10447// * InstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/2 for "moe"
10448//
10449// You can use these names in --gtest_filter.
10450//
10451// This statement will instantiate all tests from FooTest again, each
10452// with parameter values "cat" and "dog":
10453
10454const char* pets[] = {"cat", "dog"};
10455INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(AnotherInstantiationName, FooTest, ValuesIn(pets));
10456
10457// The tests from the instantiation above will have these names:
10458//
10459// * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/0 for "cat"
10460// * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.DoesBlah/1 for "dog"
10461// * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/0 for "cat"
10462// * AnotherInstantiationName/FooTest.HasBlahBlah/1 for "dog"
10463//
10464// Please note that INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P will instantiate all tests
10465// in the given test suite, whether their definitions come before or
10466// AFTER the INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P statement.
10467//
10468// Please also note that generator expressions (including parameters to the
10469// generators) are evaluated in InitGoogleTest(), after main() has started.
10470// This allows the user on one hand, to adjust generator parameters in order
10471// to dynamically determine a set of tests to run and on the other hand,
10472// give the user a chance to inspect the generated tests with Google Test
10473// reflection API before RUN_ALL_TESTS() is executed.
10474//
10475// You can see samples/sample7_unittest.cc and samples/sample8_unittest.cc
10476// for more examples.
10477//
10478// In the future, we plan to publish the API for defining new parameter
10479// generators. But for now this interface remains part of the internal
10480// implementation and is subject to change.
10481//
10482//
10483// A parameterized test fixture must be derived from testing::Test and from
10484// testing::WithParamInterface<T>, where T is the type of the parameter
10485// values. Inheriting from TestWithParam<T> satisfies that requirement because
10486// TestWithParam<T> inherits from both Test and WithParamInterface. In more
10487// complicated hierarchies, however, it is occasionally useful to inherit
10488// separately from Test and WithParamInterface. For example:
10489
10490class BaseTest : public ::testing::Test {
10491 // You can inherit all the usual members for a non-parameterized test
10492 // fixture here.
10493};
10494
10495class DerivedTest : public BaseTest, public ::testing::WithParamInterface<int> {
10496 // The usual test fixture members go here too.
10497};
10498
10499TEST_F(BaseTest, HasFoo) {
10500 // This is an ordinary non-parameterized test.
10501}
10502
10503TEST_P(DerivedTest, DoesBlah) {
10504 // GetParam works just the same here as if you inherit from TestWithParam.
10505 EXPECT_TRUE(foo.Blah(GetParam()));
10506}

10595// Interface for iterating over elements provided by an implementation
10596// of ParamGeneratorInterface<T>.
10597template <typename T>
10598class ParamIteratorInterface {
10599 public:
10600 virtual ~ParamIteratorInterface() {}
10601 // A pointer to the base generator instance.
10602 // Used only for the purposes of iterator comparison
10603 // to make sure that two iterators belong to the same generator.
10604 virtual const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* BaseGenerator() const = 0;
10605 // Advances iterator to point to the next element
10606 // provided by the generator. The caller is responsible
10607 // for not calling Advance() on an iterator equal to
10608 // BaseGenerator()->End().
10609 virtual void Advance() = 0;
10610 // Clones the iterator object. Used for implementing copy semantics
10611 // of ParamIterator<T>.
10612 virtual ParamIteratorInterface* Clone() const = 0;
10613 // Dereferences the current iterator and provides (read-only) access
10614 // to the pointed value. It is the caller's responsibility not to call
10615 // Current() on an iterator equal to BaseGenerator()->End().
10616 // Used for implementing ParamGenerator<T>::operator*().
10617 virtual const T* Current() const = 0;
10618 // Determines whether the given iterator and other point to the same
10619 // element in the sequence generated by the generator.
10620 // Used for implementing ParamGenerator<T>::operator==().
10621 virtual bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface& other) const = 0;
10622};
10623
10624// Class iterating over elements provided by an implementation of
10625// ParamGeneratorInterface<T>. It wraps ParamIteratorInterface<T>
10626// and implements the const forward iterator concept.
10627template <typename T>
10628class ParamIterator {
10629 public:
10630 typedef T value_type;
10631 typedef const T& reference;
10632 typedef ptrdiff_t difference_type;
10633
10634 // ParamIterator assumes ownership of the impl_ pointer.
10635 ParamIterator(const ParamIterator& other) : impl_(other.impl_->Clone()) {}
10636 ParamIterator& operator=(const ParamIterator& other) {
10637 if (this != &other)
10638 impl_.reset(other.impl_->Clone());
10639 return *this;
10640 }
10641
10642 const T& operator*() const { return *impl_->Current(); }
10643 const T* operator->() const { return impl_->Current(); }
10644 // Prefix version of operator++.
10645 ParamIterator& operator++() {
10646 impl_->Advance();
10647 return *this;
10648 }
10649 // Postfix version of operator++.
10650 ParamIterator operator++(int /*unused*/) {
10651 ParamIteratorInterface<T>* clone = impl_->Clone();
10652 impl_->Advance();
10653 return ParamIterator(clone);
10654 }
10655 bool operator==(const ParamIterator& other) const {
10656 return impl_.get() == other.impl_.get() || impl_->Equals(*other.impl_);
10657 }
10658 bool operator!=(const ParamIterator& other) const {
10659 return !(*this == other);
10660 }
10661
10662 private:
10663 friend class ParamGenerator<T>;
10664 explicit ParamIterator(ParamIteratorInterface<T>* impl) : impl_(impl) {}
10665 std::unique_ptr<ParamIteratorInterface<T> > impl_;
10666};
10667
10668// ParamGeneratorInterface<T> is the binary interface to access generators
10669// defined in other translation units.
10670template <typename T>
10671class ParamGeneratorInterface {
10672 public:
10673 typedef T ParamType;
10674
10675 virtual ~ParamGeneratorInterface() {}
10676
10677 // Generator interface definition
10678 virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Begin() const = 0;
10679 virtual ParamIteratorInterface<T>* End() const = 0;
10680};
10681
10682// Wraps ParamGeneratorInterface<T> and provides general generator syntax
10683// compatible with the STL Container concept.
10684// This class implements copy initialization semantics and the contained
10685// ParamGeneratorInterface<T> instance is shared among all copies
10686// of the original object. This is possible because that instance is immutable.
10687template<typename T>
10688class ParamGenerator {
10689 public:
10690 typedef ParamIterator<T> iterator;
10691
10692 explicit ParamGenerator(ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* impl) : impl_(impl) {}
10693 ParamGenerator(const ParamGenerator& other) : impl_(other.impl_) {}
10694
10695 ParamGenerator& operator=(const ParamGenerator& other) {
10696 impl_ = other.impl_;
10697 return *this;
10698 }
10699
10700 iterator begin() const { return iterator(impl_->Begin()); }
10701 iterator end() const { return iterator(impl_->End()); }
10702
10703 private:
10704 std::shared_ptr<const ParamGeneratorInterface<T> > impl_;
10705};

10707// Generates values from a range of two comparable values. Can be used to
10708// generate sequences of user-defined types that implement operator+() and
10709// operator<().
10710// This class is used in the Range() function.
10711template <typename T, typename IncrementT>
10712class RangeGenerator : public ParamGeneratorInterface<T> {
10713 public:
10714 RangeGenerator(T begin, T end, IncrementT step)
10715 : begin_(begin), end_(end),
10716 step_(step), end_index_(CalculateEndIndex(begin, end, step)) {}
10717 ~RangeGenerator() override {}
10718
10719 ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Begin() const override {
10720 return new Iterator(this, begin_, 0, step_);
10721 }
10722 ParamIteratorInterface<T>* End() const override {
10723 return new Iterator(this, end_, end_index_, step_);
10724 }
10725
10726 private:
10727 class Iterator : public ParamIteratorInterface<T> {
10728 public:
10729 Iterator(const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* base, T value, int index,
10730 IncrementT step)
10731 : base_(base), value_(value), index_(index), step_(step) {}
10732 ~Iterator() override {}
10733
10734 const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* BaseGenerator() const override {
10735 return base_;
10736 }
10737 void Advance() override {
10738 value_ = static_cast<T>(value_ + step_);
10739 index_++;
10740 }
10741 ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Clone() const override {
10742 return new Iterator(*this);
10743 }
10744 const T* Current() const override { return &value_; }
10745 bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<T>& other) const override {
10746 // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
10747 // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
10748 GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
10749 << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
10750 << "from different generators." << std::endl;
10751 const int other_index =
10752 CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other)->index_;
10753 return index_ == other_index;
10754 }
10755
10756 private:
10757 Iterator(const Iterator& other)
10758 : ParamIteratorInterface<T>(),
10759 base_(other.base_), value_(other.value_), index_(other.index_),
10760 step_(other.step_) {}
10761
10762 // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
10763 void operator=(const Iterator& other);
10764
10765 const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* const base_;
10766 T value_;
10767 int index_;
10768 const IncrementT step_;
10769 }; // class RangeGenerator::Iterator
10770
10771 static int CalculateEndIndex(const T& begin,
10772 const T& end,
10773 const IncrementT& step) {
10774 int end_index = 0;
10775 for (T i = begin; i < end; i = static_cast<T>(i + step))
10776 end_index++;
10777 return end_index;
10778 }
10779
10780 // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
10781 void operator=(const RangeGenerator& other);
10782
10783 const T begin_;
10784 const T end_;
10785 const IncrementT step_;
10786 // The index for the end() iterator. All the elements in the generated
10787 // sequence are indexed (0-based) to aid iterator comparison.
10788 const int end_index_;
10789}; // class RangeGenerator

10792// Generates values from a pair of STL-style iterators. Used in the
10793// ValuesIn() function. The elements are copied from the source range
10794// since the source can be located on the stack, and the generator
10795// is likely to persist beyond that stack frame.
10796template <typename T>
10797class ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator : public ParamGeneratorInterface<T> {
10798 public:
10799 template <typename ForwardIterator>
10800 ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator(ForwardIterator begin, ForwardIterator end)
10801 : container_(begin, end) {}
10802 ~ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator() override {}
10803
10804 ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Begin() const override {
10805 return new Iterator(this, container_.begin());
10806 }
10807 ParamIteratorInterface<T>* End() const override {
10808 return new Iterator(this, container_.end());
10809 }
10810
10811 private:
10812 typedef typename ::std::vector<T> ContainerType;
10813
10814 class Iterator : public ParamIteratorInterface<T> {
10815 public:
10816 Iterator(const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* base,
10817 typename ContainerType::const_iterator iterator)
10818 : base_(base), iterator_(iterator) {}
10819 ~Iterator() override {}
10820
10821 const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* BaseGenerator() const override {
10822 return base_;
10823 }
10824 void Advance() override {
10825 ++iterator_;
10826 value_.reset();
10827 }
10828 ParamIteratorInterface<T>* Clone() const override {
10829 return new Iterator(*this);
10830 }
10831 // We need to use cached value referenced by iterator_ because *iterator_
10832 // can return a temporary object (and of type other then T), so just
10833 // having "return &*iterator_;" doesn't work.
10834 // value_ is updated here and not in Advance() because Advance()
10835 // can advance iterator_ beyond the end of the range, and we cannot
10836 // detect that fact. The client code, on the other hand, is
10837 // responsible for not calling Current() on an out-of-range iterator.
10838 const T* Current() const override {
10839 if (value_.get() == nullptr) value_.reset(new T(*iterator_));
10840 return value_.get();
10841 }
10842 bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<T>& other) const override {
10843 // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
10844 // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
10845 GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
10846 << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
10847 << "from different generators." << std::endl;
10848 return iterator_ ==
10849 CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other)->iterator_;
10850 }
10851
10852 private:
10853 Iterator(const Iterator& other)
10854 // The explicit constructor call suppresses a false warning
10855 // emitted by gcc when supplied with the -Wextra option.
10856 : ParamIteratorInterface<T>(),
10857 base_(other.base_),
10858 iterator_(other.iterator_) {}
10859
10860 const ParamGeneratorInterface<T>* const base_;
10861 typename ContainerType::const_iterator iterator_;
10862 // A cached value of *iterator_. We keep it here to allow access by
10863 // pointer in the wrapping iterator's operator->().
10864 // value_ needs to be mutable to be accessed in Current().
10865 // Use of std::unique_ptr helps manage cached value's lifetime,
10866 // which is bound by the lifespan of the iterator itself.
10867 mutable std::unique_ptr<const T> value_;
10868 }; // class ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator::Iterator
10869
10870 // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
10871 void operator=(const ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator& other);
10872
10873 const ContainerType container_;
10874}; // class ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator

10911template <class TestClass>
10912class ParameterizedTestFactory : public TestFactoryBase {
10913 public:
10914 typedef typename TestClass::ParamType ParamType;
10915 explicit ParameterizedTestFactory(ParamType parameter) :
10916 parameter_(parameter) {}
10917 Test* CreateTest() override {
10918 TestClass::SetParam(&parameter_);
10919 return new TestClass();
10920 }

10922 private:
10923 const ParamType parameter_;

10967// to ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo classes. ParameterizedTestSuiteInfoBase
10968// accumulates test information provided by TEST_P macro invocations
10969// and generators provided by INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P macro invocations
10970// and uses that information to register all resulting test instances
10971// in RegisterTests method. The ParameterizeTestSuiteRegistry class holds
10972// a collection of pointers to the ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo objects

10974class ParameterizedTestSuiteInfoBase {

10977

10979 virtual const std::string& GetTestSuiteName() const = 0;
10980 // Test case id to verify identity.
10981 virtual TypeId GetTestSuiteTypeId() const = 0;
10982 // UnitTest class invokes this method to register tests in this
10983 // test suite right before running them in RUN_ALL_TESTS macro.
10984 // This method should not be called more then once on any single
10985 // instance of a ParameterizedTestSuiteInfoBase derived class.
10986 virtual void RegisterTests() = 0;
10987
10988 protected:
10989 ParameterizedTestSuiteInfoBase() {}
10990
10991 private:
10992 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ParameterizedTestSuiteInfoBase);

10995// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
10996//
10997// ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo accumulates tests obtained from TEST_P
10998// macro invocations for a particular test suite and generators
10999// obtained from INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P macro invocations for that
11000// test suite. It registers tests with all values generated by all
11001// generators when asked.
11002template <class TestSuite>
11003class ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo : public ParameterizedTestSuiteInfoBase {
11004 public:
11005 // ParamType and GeneratorCreationFunc are private types but are required
11006 // for declarations of public methods AddTestPattern() and
11007 // AddTestSuiteInstantiation().
11008 using ParamType = typename TestSuite::ParamType;
11009 // A function that returns an instance of appropriate generator type.
11010 typedef ParamGenerator<ParamType>(GeneratorCreationFunc)();
11011 typedef typename ParamNameGenFunc<ParamType>::Type ParamNameGeneratorFunc;
11012
11013 explicit ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo(const char* name,
11014 CodeLocation code_location)
11015 : test_suite_name_(name), code_location_(code_location) {}
11016
11017 // Test case base name for display purposes.
11018 const std::string& GetTestSuiteName() const override {
11019 return test_suite_name_;
11020 }
11021 // Test case id to verify identity.
11022 TypeId GetTestSuiteTypeId() const override { return GetTypeId<TestSuite>(); }
11023 // TEST_P macro uses AddTestPattern() to record information
11024 // about a single test in a LocalTestInfo structure.
11025 // test_suite_name is the base name of the test suite (without invocation
11026 // prefix). test_base_name is the name of an individual test without
11027 // parameter index. For the test SequenceA/FooTest.DoBar/1 FooTest is
11028 // test suite base name and DoBar is test base name.
11029 void AddTestPattern(const char* test_suite_name, const char* test_base_name,
11030 TestMetaFactoryBase<ParamType>* meta_factory) {
11031 tests_.push_back(std::shared_ptr<TestInfo>(
11032 new TestInfo(test_suite_name, test_base_name, meta_factory)));
11033 }
11034 // INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P macro uses AddGenerator() to record information
11035 // about a generator.
11036 int AddTestSuiteInstantiation(const std::string& instantiation_name,
11037 GeneratorCreationFunc* func,
11038 ParamNameGeneratorFunc* name_func,
11039 const char* file, int line) {
11040 instantiations_.push_back(
11041 InstantiationInfo(instantiation_name, func, name_func, file, line));
11042 return 0; // Return value used only to run this method in namespace scope.
11043 }
11044 // UnitTest class invokes this method to register tests in this test suite
11045 // test suites right before running tests in RUN_ALL_TESTS macro.
11046 // This method should not be called more then once on any single
11047 // instance of a ParameterizedTestSuiteInfoBase derived class.
11048 // UnitTest has a guard to prevent from calling this method more then once.
11049 void RegisterTests() override {
11050 for (typename TestInfoContainer::iterator test_it = tests_.begin();
11051 test_it != tests_.end(); ++test_it) {
11052 std::shared_ptr<TestInfo> test_info = *test_it;
11053 for (typename InstantiationContainer::iterator gen_it =
11054 instantiations_.begin(); gen_it != instantiations_.end();
11055 ++gen_it) {
11056 const std::string& instantiation_name = gen_it->name;
11057 ParamGenerator<ParamType> generator((*gen_it->generator)());
11058 ParamNameGeneratorFunc* name_func = gen_it->name_func;
11059 const char* file = gen_it->file;
11060 int line = gen_it->line;
11061
11062 std::string test_suite_name;
11063 if ( !instantiation_name.empty() )
11064 test_suite_name = instantiation_name + "/";
11065 test_suite_name += test_info->test_suite_base_name;
11066
11067 size_t i = 0;
11068 std::set<std::string> test_param_names;
11069 for (typename ParamGenerator<ParamType>::iterator param_it =
11070 generator.begin();
11071 param_it != generator.end(); ++param_it, ++i) {
11072 Message test_name_stream;
11073
11074 std::string param_name = name_func(
11075 TestParamInfo<ParamType>(*param_it, i));
11076
11077 GTEST_CHECK_(IsValidParamName(param_name))
11078 << "Parameterized test name '" << param_name
11079 << "' is invalid, in " << file
11080 << " line " << line << std::endl;
11081
11082 GTEST_CHECK_(test_param_names.count(param_name) == 0)
11083 << "Duplicate parameterized test name '" << param_name
11084 << "', in " << file << " line " << line << std::endl;
11085
11086 test_param_names.insert(param_name);
11087
11088 test_name_stream << test_info->test_base_name << "/" << param_name;
11089 MakeAndRegisterTestInfo(
11090 test_suite_name.c_str(), test_name_stream.GetString().c_str(),
11091 nullptr, // No type parameter.
11092 PrintToString(*param_it).c_str(), code_location_,
11093 GetTestSuiteTypeId(),
11094 SuiteApiResolver<TestSuite>::GetSetUpCaseOrSuite(),
11095 SuiteApiResolver<TestSuite>::GetTearDownCaseOrSuite(),
11096 test_info->test_meta_factory->CreateTestFactory(*param_it));
11097 } // for param_it
11098 } // for gen_it
11099 } // for test_it
11100 } // RegisterTests
11101
11102 private:
11103 // LocalTestInfo structure keeps information about a single test registered
11104 // with TEST_P macro.
11105 struct TestInfo {
11106 TestInfo(const char* a_test_suite_base_name, const char* a_test_base_name,
11107 TestMetaFactoryBase<ParamType>* a_test_meta_factory)
11108 : test_suite_base_name(a_test_suite_base_name),
11109 test_base_name(a_test_base_name),
11110 test_meta_factory(a_test_meta_factory) {}
11111
11112 const std::string test_suite_base_name;
11113 const std::string test_base_name;
11114 const std::unique_ptr<TestMetaFactoryBase<ParamType> > test_meta_factory;
11115 };
11116 using TestInfoContainer = ::std::vector<std::shared_ptr<TestInfo> >;
11117 // Records data received from INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P macros:
11118 // <Instantiation name, Sequence generator creation function,
11119 // Name generator function, Source file, Source line>
11120 struct InstantiationInfo {
11121 InstantiationInfo(const std::string &name_in,
11122 GeneratorCreationFunc* generator_in,
11123 ParamNameGeneratorFunc* name_func_in,
11124 const char* file_in,
11125 int line_in)
11126 : name(name_in),
11127 generator(generator_in),
11128 name_func(name_func_in),
11129 file(file_in),
11130 line(line_in) {}
11131
11132 std::string name;
11133 GeneratorCreationFunc* generator;
11134 ParamNameGeneratorFunc* name_func;
11135 const char* file;
11136 int line;
11137 };
11138 typedef ::std::vector<InstantiationInfo> InstantiationContainer;
11139
11140 static bool IsValidParamName(const std::string& name) {
11141 // Check for empty string
11142 if (name.empty())
11143 return false;
11144
11145 // Check for invalid characters
11146 for (std::string::size_type index = 0; index < name.size(); ++index) {
11147 if (!isalnum(name[index]) && name[index] != '_')
11148 return false;
11149 }
11150
11151 return true;
11152 }
11153
11154 const std::string test_suite_name_;
11155 CodeLocation code_location_;
11156 TestInfoContainer tests_;
11157 InstantiationContainer instantiations_;
11158
11159 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo);
11160}; // class ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo

11168// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
11169//
11170// ParameterizedTestSuiteRegistry contains a map of
11171// ParameterizedTestSuiteInfoBase classes accessed by test suite names. TEST_P
11172// and INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P macros use it to locate their corresponding
11173// ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo descriptors.
11174class ParameterizedTestSuiteRegistry {
11175 public:
11176 ParameterizedTestSuiteRegistry() {}
11177 ~ParameterizedTestSuiteRegistry() {
11178 for (auto& test_suite_info : test_suite_infos_) {
11179 delete test_suite_info;
11180 }
11181 }
11182
11183 // Looks up or creates and returns a structure containing information about
11184 // tests and instantiations of a particular test suite.
11185 template <class TestSuite>
11186 ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo<TestSuite>* GetTestSuitePatternHolder(
11187 const char* test_suite_name, CodeLocation code_location) {
11188 ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo<TestSuite>* typed_test_info = nullptr;
11189 for (auto& test_suite_info : test_suite_infos_) {
11190 if (test_suite_info->GetTestSuiteName() == test_suite_name) {
11191 if (test_suite_info->GetTestSuiteTypeId() != GetTypeId<TestSuite>()) {
11192 // Complain about incorrect usage of Google Test facilities
11193 // and terminate the program since we cannot guaranty correct
11194 // test suite setup and tear-down in this case.
11195 ReportInvalidTestSuiteType(test_suite_name, code_location);
11196 posix::Abort();
11197 } else {
11198 // At this point we are sure that the object we found is of the same
11199 // type we are looking for, so we downcast it to that type
11200 // without further checks.
11201 typed_test_info = CheckedDowncastToActualType<
11202 ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo<TestSuite> >(test_suite_info);
11203 }
11204 break;
11205 }
11206 }
11207 if (typed_test_info == nullptr) {
11208 typed_test_info = new ParameterizedTestSuiteInfo<TestSuite>(
11209 test_suite_name, code_location);
11210 test_suite_infos_.push_back(typed_test_info);
11211 }
11212 return typed_test_info;
11213 }
11214 void RegisterTests() {
11215 for (auto& test_suite_info : test_suite_infos_) {
11216 test_suite_info->RegisterTests();
11217 }
11218 }
11219// Legacy API is deprecated but still available
11220#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
11221 template <class TestCase>
11222 ParameterizedTestCaseInfo<TestCase>* GetTestCasePatternHolder(
11223 const char* test_case_name, CodeLocation code_location) {
11224 return GetTestSuitePatternHolder<TestCase>(test_case_name, code_location);
11225 }
11226
11227#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
11228
11229 private:
11230 using TestSuiteInfoContainer = ::std::vector<ParameterizedTestSuiteInfoBase*>;
11231
11232 TestSuiteInfoContainer test_suite_infos_;
11233
11234 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ParameterizedTestSuiteRegistry);
11235};

11246// Used in the Values() function to provide polymorphic capabilities.
11247
11248template <typename... Ts>
11249class ValueArray {
11250 public:
11251 ValueArray(Ts... v) : v_{std::move(v)...} {}
11252
11253 template <typename T>
11254 operator ParamGenerator<T>() const { // NOLINT
11255 return ValuesIn(MakeVector<T>(MakeIndexSequence<sizeof...(Ts)>()));
11256 }
11257
11258 private:
11259 template <typename T, size_t... I>
11260 std::vector<T> MakeVector(IndexSequence<I...>) const {
11261 return std::vector<T>{static_cast<T>(v_.template Get<I>())...};
11262 }
11263
11264 FlatTuple<Ts...> v_;
11265};

11374 if (current2_ == end2_) {

11540 void ComputeCurrentValue() {
11541 if (!AtEnd())
11542 current_value_.reset(new ParamType(*current1_, *current2_, *current3_));
11543 }
11544 bool AtEnd() const {
11545 // We must report iterator past the end of the range when either of the
11546 // component iterators has reached the end of its range.
11547 return
11548 current1_ == end1_ ||
11549 current2_ == end2_ ||
11550 current3_ == end3_;
11551 }
11552
11553 // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
11554 void operator=(const Iterator& other);
11555
11556 const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* const base_;
11557 // begin[i]_ and end[i]_ define the i-th range that Iterator traverses.
11558 // current[i]_ is the actual traversing iterator.
11559 const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator begin1_;
11560 const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator end1_;
11561 typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator current1_;
11562 const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator begin2_;
11563 const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator end2_;
11564 typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator current2_;
11565 const typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator begin3_;
11566 const typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator end3_;
11567 typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator current3_;
11568 std::shared_ptr<ParamType> current_value_;
11569 }; // class CartesianProductGenerator3::Iterator

11575 const ParamGenerator<T2> g2_;

11601 private:
11602 class Iterator : public ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType> {
11603 public:

11605 const ParamGenerator<T1>& g1,
11606 const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator& current1,
11607 const ParamGenerator<T2>& g2,
11608 const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator& current2,
11609 const ParamGenerator<T3>& g3,
11610 const typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator& current3,
11611 const ParamGenerator<T4>& g4,
11612 const typename ParamGenerator<T4>::iterator& current4)
11613 : base_(base),
11614 begin1_(g1.begin()), end1_(g1.end()), current1_(current1),
11615 begin2_(g2.begin()), end2_(g2.end()), current2_(current2),
11616 begin3_(g3.begin()), end3_(g3.end()), current3_(current3),
11617 begin4_(g4.begin()), end4_(g4.end()), current4_(current4) {
11618 ComputeCurrentValue();
11619 }
11620 ~Iterator() override {}
11621
11622 const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* BaseGenerator() const override {
11623 return base_;
11624 }
11625 // Advance should not be called on beyond-of-range iterators
11626 // so no component iterators must be beyond end of range, either.
11627 void Advance() override {
11628 assert(!AtEnd());
11629 ++current4_;
11630 if (current4_ == end4_) {
11631 current4_ = begin4_;
11632 ++current3_;
11633 }
11634 if (current3_ == end3_) {
11635 current3_ = begin3_;
11636 ++current2_;
11637 }
11638 if (current2_ == end2_) {
11639 current2_ = begin2_;
11640 ++current1_;
11641 }
11642 ComputeCurrentValue();
11643 }

11645 return new Iterator(*this);
11646 }

11648 bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>& other) const override {
11649 // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
11650 // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
11651 GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
11652 << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
11653 << "from different generators." << std::endl;
11654 const Iterator* typed_other =
11655 CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other);
11656 // We must report iterators equal if they both point beyond their
11657 // respective ranges. That can happen in a variety of fashions,
11658 // so we have to consult AtEnd().
11659 return (AtEnd() && typed_other->AtEnd()) ||
11660 (
11661 current1_ == typed_other->current1_ &&
11662 current2_ == typed_other->current2_ &&
11663 current3_ == typed_other->current3_ &&
11664 current4_ == typed_other->current4_);
11665 }

11674 end2_(other.end2_),
11675 current2_(other.current2_),
11676 begin3_(other.begin3_),
11677 end3_(other.end3_),
11678 current3_(other.current3_),
11679 begin4_(other.begin4_),
11680 end4_(other.end4_),
11681 current4_(other.current4_) {
11682 ComputeCurrentValue();
11683 }

11687 current_value_.reset(new ParamType(*current1_, *current2_, *current3_,
11688 *current4_));

12706 const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator end2_;
12707 typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator current2_;

12722 typename ParamGenerator<T7>::iterator current7_;
12723 const typename ParamGenerator<T8>::iterator begin8_;
12724 const typename ParamGenerator<T8>::iterator end8_;

12726 const typename ParamGenerator<T9>::iterator begin9_;
12727 const typename ParamGenerator<T9>::iterator end9_;

12747template <typename T1, typename T2, typename T3, typename T4, typename T5,
12748 typename T6, typename T7, typename T8, typename T9, typename T10>
12749class CartesianProductGenerator10
12750 : public ParamGeneratorInterface< ::std::tuple<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7,
12751 T8, T9, T10> > {
12752 public:
12753 typedef ::std::tuple<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, T9, T10> ParamType;
12754
12755 CartesianProductGenerator10(const ParamGenerator<T1>& g1,
12756 const ParamGenerator<T2>& g2, const ParamGenerator<T3>& g3,
12757 const ParamGenerator<T4>& g4, const ParamGenerator<T5>& g5,
12758 const ParamGenerator<T6>& g6, const ParamGenerator<T7>& g7,
12759 const ParamGenerator<T8>& g8, const ParamGenerator<T9>& g9,
12760 const ParamGenerator<T10>& g10)
12761 : g1_(g1), g2_(g2), g3_(g3), g4_(g4), g5_(g5), g6_(g6), g7_(g7), g8_(g8),
12762 g9_(g9), g10_(g10) {}
12763 ~CartesianProductGenerator10() override {}
12764
12765 ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>* Begin() const override {
12766 return new Iterator(this, g1_, g1_.begin(), g2_, g2_.begin(), g3_,
12767 g3_.begin(), g4_, g4_.begin(), g5_, g5_.begin(), g6_, g6_.begin(), g7_,
12768 g7_.begin(), g8_, g8_.begin(), g9_, g9_.begin(), g10_, g10_.begin());
12769 }
12770 ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>* End() const override {
12771 return new Iterator(this, g1_, g1_.end(), g2_, g2_.end(), g3_, g3_.end(),
12772 g4_, g4_.end(), g5_, g5_.end(), g6_, g6_.end(), g7_, g7_.end(), g8_,
12773 g8_.end(), g9_, g9_.end(), g10_, g10_.end());
12774 }
12775
12776 private:
12777 class Iterator : public ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType> {
12778 public:
12779 Iterator(const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* base,
12780 const ParamGenerator<T1>& g1,
12781 const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator& current1,
12782 const ParamGenerator<T2>& g2,
12783 const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator& current2,
12784 const ParamGenerator<T3>& g3,
12785 const typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator& current3,
12786 const ParamGenerator<T4>& g4,
12787 const typename ParamGenerator<T4>::iterator& current4,
12788 const ParamGenerator<T5>& g5,
12789 const typename ParamGenerator<T5>::iterator& current5,
12790 const ParamGenerator<T6>& g6,
12791 const typename ParamGenerator<T6>::iterator& current6,
12792 const ParamGenerator<T7>& g7,
12793 const typename ParamGenerator<T7>::iterator& current7,
12794 const ParamGenerator<T8>& g8,
12795 const typename ParamGenerator<T8>::iterator& current8,
12796 const ParamGenerator<T9>& g9,
12797 const typename ParamGenerator<T9>::iterator& current9,
12798 const ParamGenerator<T10>& g10,
12799 const typename ParamGenerator<T10>::iterator& current10)
12800 : base_(base),
12801 begin1_(g1.begin()), end1_(g1.end()), current1_(current1),
12802 begin2_(g2.begin()), end2_(g2.end()), current2_(current2),
12803 begin3_(g3.begin()), end3_(g3.end()), current3_(current3),
12804 begin4_(g4.begin()), end4_(g4.end()), current4_(current4),
12805 begin5_(g5.begin()), end5_(g5.end()), current5_(current5),
12806 begin6_(g6.begin()), end6_(g6.end()), current6_(current6),
12807 begin7_(g7.begin()), end7_(g7.end()), current7_(current7),
12808 begin8_(g8.begin()), end8_(g8.end()), current8_(current8),
12809 begin9_(g9.begin()), end9_(g9.end()), current9_(current9),
12810 begin10_(g10.begin()), end10_(g10.end()), current10_(current10) {
12811 ComputeCurrentValue();
12812 }
12813 ~Iterator() override {}
12814
12815 const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* BaseGenerator() const override {
12816 return base_;
12817 }
12818 // Advance should not be called on beyond-of-range iterators
12819 // so no component iterators must be beyond end of range, either.
12820 void Advance() override {
12821 assert(!AtEnd());
12822 ++current10_;
12823 if (current10_ == end10_) {
12824 current10_ = begin10_;
12825 ++current9_;
12826 }
12827 if (current9_ == end9_) {
12828 current9_ = begin9_;
12829 ++current8_;
12830 }
12831 if (current8_ == end8_) {
12832 current8_ = begin8_;
12833 ++current7_;
12834 }
12835 if (current7_ == end7_) {
12836 current7_ = begin7_;
12837 ++current6_;
12838 }
12839 if (current6_ == end6_) {
12840 current6_ = begin6_;
12841 ++current5_;
12842 }
12843 if (current5_ == end5_) {
12844 current5_ = begin5_;
12845 ++current4_;
12846 }
12847 if (current4_ == end4_) {
12848 current4_ = begin4_;
12849 ++current3_;
12850 }
12851 if (current3_ == end3_) {
12852 current3_ = begin3_;
12853 ++current2_;
12854 }
12855 if (current2_ == end2_) {
12856 current2_ = begin2_;
12857 ++current1_;
12858 }
12859 ComputeCurrentValue();
12860 }
12861 ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>* Clone() const override {
12862 return new Iterator(*this);
12863 }
12864 const ParamType* Current() const override { return current_value_.get(); }
12865 bool Equals(const ParamIteratorInterface<ParamType>& other) const override {
12866 // Having the same base generator guarantees that the other
12867 // iterator is of the same type and we can downcast.
12868 GTEST_CHECK_(BaseGenerator() == other.BaseGenerator())
12869 << "The program attempted to compare iterators "
12870 << "from different generators." << std::endl;
12871 const Iterator* typed_other =
12872 CheckedDowncastToActualType<const Iterator>(&other);
12873 // We must report iterators equal if they both point beyond their
12874 // respective ranges. That can happen in a variety of fashions,
12875 // so we have to consult AtEnd().
12876 return (AtEnd() && typed_other->AtEnd()) ||
12877 (
12878 current1_ == typed_other->current1_ &&
12879 current2_ == typed_other->current2_ &&
12880 current3_ == typed_other->current3_ &&
12881 current4_ == typed_other->current4_ &&
12882 current5_ == typed_other->current5_ &&
12883 current6_ == typed_other->current6_ &&
12884 current7_ == typed_other->current7_ &&
12885 current8_ == typed_other->current8_ &&
12886 current9_ == typed_other->current9_ &&
12887 current10_ == typed_other->current10_);
12888 }
12889
12890 private:
12891 Iterator(const Iterator& other)
12892 : base_(other.base_),
12893 begin1_(other.begin1_),
12894 end1_(other.end1_),
12895 current1_(other.current1_),
12896 begin2_(other.begin2_),
12897 end2_(other.end2_),
12898 current2_(other.current2_),
12899 begin3_(other.begin3_),
12900 end3_(other.end3_),
12901 current3_(other.current3_),
12902 begin4_(other.begin4_),
12903 end4_(other.end4_),
12904 current4_(other.current4_),
12905 begin5_(other.begin5_),
12906 end5_(other.end5_),
12907 current5_(other.current5_),
12908 begin6_(other.begin6_),
12909 end6_(other.end6_),
12910 current6_(other.current6_),
12911 begin7_(other.begin7_),
12912 end7_(other.end7_),
12913 current7_(other.current7_),
12914 begin8_(other.begin8_),
12915 end8_(other.end8_),
12916 current8_(other.current8_),
12917 begin9_(other.begin9_),
12918 end9_(other.end9_),
12919 current9_(other.current9_),
12920 begin10_(other.begin10_),
12921 end10_(other.end10_),
12922 current10_(other.current10_) {
12923 ComputeCurrentValue();
12924 }
12925
12926 void ComputeCurrentValue() {
12927 if (!AtEnd())
12928 current_value_.reset(new ParamType(*current1_, *current2_, *current3_,
12929 *current4_, *current5_, *current6_, *current7_, *current8_,
12930 *current9_, *current10_));
12931 }
12932 bool AtEnd() const {
12933 // We must report iterator past the end of the range when either of the
12934 // component iterators has reached the end of its range.
12935 return
12936 current1_ == end1_ ||
12937 current2_ == end2_ ||
12938 current3_ == end3_ ||
12939 current4_ == end4_ ||
12940 current5_ == end5_ ||
12941 current6_ == end6_ ||
12942 current7_ == end7_ ||
12943 current8_ == end8_ ||
12944 current9_ == end9_ ||
12945 current10_ == end10_;
12946 }
12947
12948 // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
12949 void operator=(const Iterator& other);
12950
12951 const ParamGeneratorInterface<ParamType>* const base_;
12952 // begin[i]_ and end[i]_ define the i-th range that Iterator traverses.
12953 // current[i]_ is the actual traversing iterator.
12954 const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator begin1_;
12955 const typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator end1_;
12956 typename ParamGenerator<T1>::iterator current1_;
12957 const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator begin2_;
12958 const typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator end2_;
12959 typename ParamGenerator<T2>::iterator current2_;
12960 const typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator begin3_;
12961 const typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator end3_;
12962 typename ParamGenerator<T3>::iterator current3_;
12963 const typename ParamGenerator<T4>::iterator begin4_;
12964 const typename ParamGenerator<T4>::iterator end4_;
12965 typename ParamGenerator<T4>::iterator current4_;
12966 const typename ParamGenerator<T5>::iterator begin5_;
12967 const typename ParamGenerator<T5>::iterator end5_;
12968 typename ParamGenerator<T5>::iterator current5_;
12969 const typename ParamGenerator<T6>::iterator begin6_;
12970 const typename ParamGenerator<T6>::iterator end6_;
12971 typename ParamGenerator<T6>::iterator current6_;
12972 const typename ParamGenerator<T7>::iterator begin7_;
12973 const typename ParamGenerator<T7>::iterator end7_;
12974 typename ParamGenerator<T7>::iterator current7_;
12975 const typename ParamGenerator<T8>::iterator begin8_;
12976 const typename ParamGenerator<T8>::iterator end8_;
12977 typename ParamGenerator<T8>::iterator current8_;
12978 const typename ParamGenerator<T9>::iterator begin9_;
12979 const typename ParamGenerator<T9>::iterator end9_;
12980 typename ParamGenerator<T9>::iterator current9_;
12981 const typename ParamGenerator<T10>::iterator begin10_;
12982 const typename ParamGenerator<T10>::iterator end10_;
12983 typename ParamGenerator<T10>::iterator current10_;
12984 std::shared_ptr<ParamType> current_value_;
12985 }; // class CartesianProductGenerator10::Iterator
12986
12987 // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
12988 void operator=(const CartesianProductGenerator10& other);
12989
12990 const ParamGenerator<T1> g1_;
12991 const ParamGenerator<T2> g2_;
12992 const ParamGenerator<T3> g3_;
12993 const ParamGenerator<T4> g4_;
12994 const ParamGenerator<T5> g5_;
12995 const ParamGenerator<T6> g6_;
12996 const ParamGenerator<T7> g7_;
12997 const ParamGenerator<T8> g8_;
12998 const ParamGenerator<T9> g9_;
12999 const ParamGenerator<T10> g10_;
13000}; // class CartesianProductGenerator10

13218template <class Generator1, class Generator2, class Generator3,

13221class CartesianProductHolder9 {
13222 public:
13223CartesianProductHolder9(const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2,
13224 const Generator3& g3, const Generator4& g4, const Generator5& g5,
13225 const Generator6& g6, const Generator7& g7, const Generator8& g8,
13226 const Generator9& g9)
13227 : g1_(g1), g2_(g2), g3_(g3), g4_(g4), g5_(g5), g6_(g6), g7_(g7), g8_(g8),
13228 g9_(g9) {}
13229 template <typename T1, typename T2, typename T3, typename T4, typename T5,
13230 typename T6, typename T7, typename T8, typename T9>
13231 operator ParamGenerator< ::std::tuple<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8,
13232 T9> >() const {
13233 return ParamGenerator< ::std::tuple<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, T9> >(
13234 new CartesianProductGenerator9<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, T9>(
13235 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T1> >(g1_),
13236 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T2> >(g2_),
13237 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T3> >(g3_),
13238 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T4> >(g4_),
13239 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T5> >(g5_),
13240 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T6> >(g6_),
13241 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T7> >(g7_),
13242 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T8> >(g8_),
13243 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T9> >(g9_)));
13244 }
13245
13246 private:
13247 // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
13248 void operator=(const CartesianProductHolder9& other);
13249
13250 const Generator1 g1_;
13251 const Generator2 g2_;
13252 const Generator3 g3_;
13253 const Generator4 g4_;
13254 const Generator5 g5_;
13255 const Generator6 g6_;
13256 const Generator7 g7_;
13257 const Generator8 g8_;
13258 const Generator9 g9_;
13259}; // class CartesianProductHolder9
13260
13261template <class Generator1, class Generator2, class Generator3,
13262 class Generator4, class Generator5, class Generator6, class Generator7,
13263 class Generator8, class Generator9, class Generator10>
13264class CartesianProductHolder10 {
13265 public:
13266CartesianProductHolder10(const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2,
13267 const Generator3& g3, const Generator4& g4, const Generator5& g5,
13268 const Generator6& g6, const Generator7& g7, const Generator8& g8,
13269 const Generator9& g9, const Generator10& g10)
13270 : g1_(g1), g2_(g2), g3_(g3), g4_(g4), g5_(g5), g6_(g6), g7_(g7), g8_(g8),
13271 g9_(g9), g10_(g10) {}
13272 template <typename T1, typename T2, typename T3, typename T4, typename T5,
13273 typename T6, typename T7, typename T8, typename T9, typename T10>
13274 operator ParamGenerator< ::std::tuple<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, T9,
13275 T10> >() const {
13276 return ParamGenerator< ::std::tuple<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, T9,
13277 T10> >(
13278 new CartesianProductGenerator10<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, T9,
13279 T10>(
13280 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T1> >(g1_),
13281 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T2> >(g2_),
13282 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T3> >(g3_),
13283 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T4> >(g4_),
13284 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T5> >(g5_),
13285 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T6> >(g6_),
13286 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T7> >(g7_),
13287 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T8> >(g8_),
13288 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T9> >(g9_),
13289 static_cast<ParamGenerator<T10> >(g10_)));
13290 }
13291
13292 private:
13293 // No implementation - assignment is unsupported.
13294 void operator=(const CartesianProductHolder10& other);
13295
13296 const Generator1 g1_;
13297 const Generator2 g2_;
13298 const Generator3 g3_;
13299 const Generator4 g4_;
13300 const Generator5 g5_;
13301 const Generator6 g6_;
13302 const Generator7 g7_;
13303 const Generator8 g8_;
13304 const Generator9 g9_;
13305 const Generator10 g10_;
13306}; // class CartesianProductHolder10

13313namespace testing {
13314
13315// Functions producing parameter generators.
13316//
13317// Google Test uses these generators to produce parameters for value-
13318// parameterized tests. When a parameterized test suite is instantiated
13319// with a particular generator, Google Test creates and runs tests
13320// for each element in the sequence produced by the generator.
13321//
13322// In the following sample, tests from test suite FooTest are instantiated
13323// each three times with parameter values 3, 5, and 8:
13324//
13325// class FooTest : public TestWithParam<int> { ... };
13326//
13327// TEST_P(FooTest, TestThis) {
13328// }
13329// TEST_P(FooTest, TestThat) {
13330// }
13331// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(TestSequence, FooTest, Values(3, 5, 8));
13332//
13333
13334// Range() returns generators providing sequences of values in a range.
13335//
13336// Synopsis:
13337// Range(start, end)
13338// - returns a generator producing a sequence of values {start, start+1,
13339// start+2, ..., }.
13340// Range(start, end, step)
13341// - returns a generator producing a sequence of values {start, start+step,
13342// start+step+step, ..., }.
13343// Notes:
13344// * The generated sequences never include end. For example, Range(1, 5)
13345// returns a generator producing a sequence {1, 2, 3, 4}. Range(1, 9, 2)
13346// returns a generator producing {1, 3, 5, 7}.
13347// * start and end must have the same type. That type may be any integral or
13348// floating-point type or a user defined type satisfying these conditions:
13349// * It must be assignable (have operator=() defined).
13350// * It must have operator+() (operator+(int-compatible type) for
13351// two-operand version).
13352// * It must have operator<() defined.
13353// Elements in the resulting sequences will also have that type.
13354// * Condition start < end must be satisfied in order for resulting sequences
13355// to contain any elements.
13356//
13357template <typename T, typename IncrementT>
13358internal::ParamGenerator<T> Range(T start, T end, IncrementT step) {
13359 return internal::ParamGenerator<T>(
13360 new internal::RangeGenerator<T, IncrementT>(start, end, step));
13361}
13362
13363template <typename T>
13364internal::ParamGenerator<T> Range(T start, T end) {
13365 return Range(start, end, 1);
13366}
13367
13368// ValuesIn() function allows generation of tests with parameters coming from
13369// a container.
13370//
13371// Synopsis:
13372// ValuesIn(const T (&array)[N])
13373// - returns a generator producing sequences with elements from
13374// a C-style array.
13375// ValuesIn(const Container& container)
13376// - returns a generator producing sequences with elements from
13377// an STL-style container.
13378// ValuesIn(Iterator begin, Iterator end)
13379// - returns a generator producing sequences with elements from
13380// a range [begin, end) defined by a pair of STL-style iterators. These
13381// iterators can also be plain C pointers.
13382//
13383// Please note that ValuesIn copies the values from the containers
13384// passed in and keeps them to generate tests in RUN_ALL_TESTS().
13385//
13386// Examples:
13387//
13388// This instantiates tests from test suite StringTest
13389// each with C-string values of "foo", "bar", and "baz":
13390//
13391// const char* strings[] = {"foo", "bar", "baz"};
13392// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(StringSequence, StringTest, ValuesIn(strings));
13393//
13394// This instantiates tests from test suite StlStringTest
13395// each with STL strings with values "a" and "b":
13396//
13397// ::std::vector< ::std::string> GetParameterStrings() {
13398// ::std::vector< ::std::string> v;
13399// v.push_back("a");
13400// v.push_back("b");
13401// return v;
13402// }
13403//
13404// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(CharSequence,
13405// StlStringTest,
13406// ValuesIn(GetParameterStrings()));
13407//
13408//
13409// This will also instantiate tests from CharTest
13410// each with parameter values 'a' and 'b':
13411//
13412// ::std::list<char> GetParameterChars() {
13413// ::std::list<char> list;
13414// list.push_back('a');
13415// list.push_back('b');
13416// return list;
13417// }
13418// ::std::list<char> l = GetParameterChars();
13419// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(CharSequence2,
13420// CharTest,
13421// ValuesIn(l.begin(), l.end()));
13422//
13423template <typename ForwardIterator>
13424internal::ParamGenerator<
13425 typename ::testing::internal::IteratorTraits<ForwardIterator>::value_type>
13426ValuesIn(ForwardIterator begin, ForwardIterator end) {
13427 typedef typename ::testing::internal::IteratorTraits<ForwardIterator>
13428 ::value_type ParamType;
13429 return internal::ParamGenerator<ParamType>(
13430 new internal::ValuesInIteratorRangeGenerator<ParamType>(begin, end));
13431}
13432
13433template <typename T, size_t N>
13434internal::ParamGenerator<T> ValuesIn(const T (&array)[N]) {
13435 return ValuesIn(array, array + N);
13436}
13437
13438template <class Container>
13439internal::ParamGenerator<typename Container::value_type> ValuesIn(
13440 const Container& container) {
13441 return ValuesIn(container.begin(), container.end());
13442}
13443
13444// Values() allows generating tests from explicitly specified list of
13445// parameters.
13446//
13447// Synopsis:
13448// Values(T v1, T v2, ..., T vN)
13449// - returns a generator producing sequences with elements v1, v2, ..., vN.
13450//
13451// For example, this instantiates tests from test suite BarTest each
13452// with values "one", "two", and "three":
13453//
13454// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(NumSequence,
13455// BarTest,
13456// Values("one", "two", "three"));
13457//
13458// This instantiates tests from test suite BazTest each with values 1, 2, 3.5.
13459// The exact type of values will depend on the type of parameter in BazTest.
13460//
13461// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(FloatingNumbers, BazTest, Values(1, 2, 3.5));
13462//
13463//
13464template <typename... T>
13465internal::ValueArray<T...> Values(T... v) {
13466 return internal::ValueArray<T...>(std::move(v)...);
13467}
13468
13469// Bool() allows generating tests with parameters in a set of (false, true).
13470//
13471// Synopsis:
13472// Bool()
13473// - returns a generator producing sequences with elements {false, true}.
13474//
13475// It is useful when testing code that depends on Boolean flags. Combinations
13476// of multiple flags can be tested when several Bool()'s are combined using
13477// Combine() function.
13478//
13479// In the following example all tests in the test suite FlagDependentTest
13480// will be instantiated twice with parameters false and true.
13481//
13482// class FlagDependentTest : public testing::TestWithParam<bool> {
13483// virtual void SetUp() {
13484// external_flag = GetParam();
13485// }
13486// }
13487// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(BoolSequence, FlagDependentTest, Bool());
13488//
13489inline internal::ParamGenerator<bool> Bool() {
13490 return Values(false, true);
13491}
13492
13493// Combine() allows the user to combine two or more sequences to produce
13494// values of a Cartesian product of those sequences' elements.
13495//
13496// Synopsis:
13497// Combine(gen1, gen2, ..., genN)
13498// - returns a generator producing sequences with elements coming from
13499// the Cartesian product of elements from the sequences generated by
13500// gen1, gen2, ..., genN. The sequence elements will have a type of
13501// std::tuple<T1, T2, ..., TN> where T1, T2, ..., TN are the types
13502// of elements from sequences produces by gen1, gen2, ..., genN.
13503//
13504// Combine can have up to 10 arguments.
13505//
13506// Example:
13507//
13508// This will instantiate tests in test suite AnimalTest each one with
13509// the parameter values tuple("cat", BLACK), tuple("cat", WHITE),
13510// tuple("dog", BLACK), and tuple("dog", WHITE):
13511//
13512// enum Color { BLACK, GRAY, WHITE };
13513// class AnimalTest
13514// : public testing::TestWithParam<std::tuple<const char*, Color> > {...};
13515//
13516// TEST_P(AnimalTest, AnimalLooksNice) {...}
13517//
13518// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(AnimalVariations, AnimalTest,
13519// Combine(Values("cat", "dog"),
13520// Values(BLACK, WHITE)));
13521//
13522// This will instantiate tests in FlagDependentTest with all variations of two
13523// Boolean flags:
13524//
13525// class FlagDependentTest
13526// : public testing::TestWithParam<std::tuple<bool, bool> > {
13527// virtual void SetUp() {
13528// // Assigns external_flag_1 and external_flag_2 values from the tuple.
13529// std::tie(external_flag_1, external_flag_2) = GetParam();
13530// }
13531// };
13532//
13533// TEST_P(FlagDependentTest, TestFeature1) {
13534// // Test your code using external_flag_1 and external_flag_2 here.
13535// }
13536// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(TwoBoolSequence, FlagDependentTest,
13537// Combine(Bool(), Bool()));
13538//
13539template <typename Generator1, typename Generator2>
13540internal::CartesianProductHolder2<Generator1, Generator2> Combine(
13541 const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2) {
13542 return internal::CartesianProductHolder2<Generator1, Generator2>(
13543 g1, g2);
13544}
13545
13546template <typename Generator1, typename Generator2, typename Generator3>
13547internal::CartesianProductHolder3<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3> Combine(
13548 const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2, const Generator3& g3) {
13549 return internal::CartesianProductHolder3<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3>(
13550 g1, g2, g3);
13551}
13552
13553template <typename Generator1, typename Generator2, typename Generator3,
13554 typename Generator4>
13555internal::CartesianProductHolder4<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3,
13556 Generator4> Combine(
13557 const Generator1& g1, const Generator2& g2, const Generator3& g3,
13558 const Generator4& g4) {
13559 return internal::CartesianProductHolder4<Generator1, Generator2, Generator3,
13560 Generator4>(
13561 g1, g2, g3, g4);
13562}

13643#define TEST_P(test_suite_name, test_name) \
13644 class GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_suite_name, test_name) \
13645 : public test_suite_name { \
13646 public: \
13647 GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_suite_name, test_name)() {} \
13648 virtual void TestBody(); \
13649 \
13650 private: \
13651 static int AddToRegistry() { \
13652 ::testing::UnitTest::GetInstance() \
13653 ->parameterized_test_registry() \
13654 .GetTestSuitePatternHolder<test_suite_name>( \
13655 #test_suite_name, \
13656 ::testing::internal::CodeLocation(__FILE__, __LINE__)) \
13657 ->AddTestPattern( \
13658 GTEST_STRINGIFY_(test_suite_name), GTEST_STRINGIFY_(test_name), \
13659 new ::testing::internal::TestMetaFactory<GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_( \
13660 test_suite_name, test_name)>()); \
13661 return 0; \
13662 } \
13663 static int gtest_registering_dummy_ GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_; \
13664 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_suite_name, \
13665 test_name)); \
13666 }; \
13667 int GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_suite_name, \
13668 test_name)::gtest_registering_dummy_ = \
13669 GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_suite_name, test_name)::AddToRegistry(); \
13670 void GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(test_suite_name, test_name)::TestBody()
13671
13672// The optional last argument to INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P allows the user
13673// to specify a function or functor that generates custom test name suffixes
13674// based on the test parameters. The function should accept one argument of
13675// type testing::TestParamInfo<class ParamType>, and return std::string.
13676//
13677// testing::PrintToStringParamName is a builtin test suffix generator that
13678// returns the value of testing::PrintToString(GetParam()).
13679//
13680// Note: test names must be non-empty, unique, and may only contain ASCII
13681// alphanumeric characters or underscore. Because PrintToString adds quotes
13682// to std::string and C strings, it won't work for these types.
13683
13684#define INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(prefix, test_suite_name, generator, ...) \
13685 static ::testing::internal::ParamGenerator<test_suite_name::ParamType> \
13686 gtest_##prefix##test_suite_name##_EvalGenerator_() { \
13687 return generator; \
13688 } \
13689 static ::std::string gtest_##prefix##test_suite_name##_EvalGenerateName_( \
13690 const ::testing::TestParamInfo<test_suite_name::ParamType>& info) { \
13691 return ::testing::internal::GetParamNameGen<test_suite_name::ParamType>( \
13692 __VA_ARGS__)(info); \
13693 } \
13694 static int gtest_##prefix##test_suite_name##_dummy_ \
13695 GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ = \
13696 ::testing::UnitTest::GetInstance() \
13697 ->parameterized_test_registry() \
13698 .GetTestSuitePatternHolder<test_suite_name>( \
13699 #test_suite_name, \
13700 ::testing::internal::CodeLocation(__FILE__, __LINE__)) \
13701 ->AddTestSuiteInstantiation( \
13702 #prefix, &gtest_##prefix##test_suite_name##_EvalGenerator_, \
13703 &gtest_##prefix##test_suite_name##_EvalGenerateName_, \
13704 __FILE__, __LINE__)
13705
13706// Legacy API is deprecated but still available
13707#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
13708#define INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P
13709#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_

13749
13750// When you need to test the private or protected members of a class,
13751// use the FRIEND_TEST macro to declare your tests as friends of the
13752// class. For example:
13753//
13754// class MyClass {
13755// private:
13756// void PrivateMethod();
13757// FRIEND_TEST(MyClassTest, PrivateMethodWorks);
13758// };
13759//
13760// class MyClassTest : public testing::Test {
13761// // ...
13762// };
13763//
13764// TEST_F(MyClassTest, PrivateMethodWorks) {
13765// // Can call MyClass::PrivateMethod() here.
13766// }
13767//
13768// Note: The test class must be in the same namespace as the class being tested.
13769// For example, putting MyClassTest in an anonymous namespace will not work.
13770
13771#define FRIEND_TEST(test_case_name, test_name)\
13772friend class test_case_name##_##test_name##_Test
13773
13774#endif // GTEST_INCLUDE_GTEST_GTEST_PROD_H_

13778// Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or without
13779// modification, are permitted provided that the following conditions are

13815namespace testing {
13816
13817// A copyable object representing the result of a test part (i.e. an
13818// assertion or an explicit FAIL(), ADD_FAILURE(), or SUCCESS()).
13819//
13820// Don't inherit from TestPartResult as its destructor is not virtual.
13821class GTEST_API_ TestPartResult {
13822 public:
13823 // The possible outcomes of a test part (i.e. an assertion or an
13824 // explicit SUCCEED(), FAIL(), or ADD_FAILURE()).
13825 enum Type {
13826 kSuccess, // Succeeded.
13827 kNonFatalFailure, // Failed but the test can continue.
13828 kFatalFailure, // Failed and the test should be terminated.
13829 kSkip // Skipped.
13830 };
13831
13832 // C'tor. TestPartResult does NOT have a default constructor.
13833 // Always use this constructor (with parameters) to create a
13834 // TestPartResult object.
13835 TestPartResult(Type a_type, const char* a_file_name, int a_line_number,
13836 const char* a_message)
13837 : type_(a_type),
13838 file_name_(a_file_name == nullptr ? "" : a_file_name),
13839 line_number_(a_line_number),
13840 summary_(ExtractSummary(a_message)),
13841 message_(a_message) {}
13842
13843 // Gets the outcome of the test part.
13844 Type type() const { return type_; }
13845
13846 // Gets the name of the source file where the test part took place, or
13847 // NULL if it's unknown.
13848 const char* file_name() const {
13849 return file_name_.empty() ? nullptr : file_name_.c_str();
13850 }
13851
13852 // Gets the line in the source file where the test part took place,
13853 // or -1 if it's unknown.
13854 int line_number() const { return line_number_; }
13855
13856 // Gets the summary of the failure message.
13857 const char* summary() const { return summary_.c_str(); }
13858
13859 // Gets the message associated with the test part.
13860 const char* message() const { return message_.c_str(); }
13861
13862 // Returns true iff the test part was skipped.
13863 bool skipped() const { return type_ == kSkip; }
13864
13865 // Returns true iff the test part passed.
13866 bool passed() const { return type_ == kSuccess; }
13867
13868 // Returns true iff the test part non-fatally failed.
13869 bool nonfatally_failed() const { return type_ == kNonFatalFailure; }
13870
13871 // Returns true iff the test part fatally failed.
13872 bool fatally_failed() const { return type_ == kFatalFailure; }
13873
13874 // Returns true iff the test part failed.
13875 bool failed() const { return fatally_failed() || nonfatally_failed(); }
13876
13877 private:
13878 Type type_;
13879
13880 // Gets the summary of the failure message by omitting the stack
13881 // trace in it.
13882 static std::string ExtractSummary(const char* message);
13883
13884 // The name of the source file where the test part took place, or
13885 // "" if the source file is unknown.
13886 std::string file_name_;
13887 // The line in the source file where the test part took place, or -1
13888 // if the line number is unknown.
13889 int line_number_;
13890 std::string summary_; // The test failure summary.
13891 std::string message_; // The test failure message.
13892};
13893
13894// Prints a TestPartResult object.
13895std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, const TestPartResult& result);
13896
13897// An array of TestPartResult objects.
13898//
13899// Don't inherit from TestPartResultArray as its destructor is not
13900// virtual.
13901class GTEST_API_ TestPartResultArray {
13902 public:
13903 TestPartResultArray() {}
13904
13905 // Appends the given TestPartResult to the array.
13906 void Append(const TestPartResult& result);
13907
13908 // Returns the TestPartResult at the given index (0-based).
13909 const TestPartResult& GetTestPartResult(int index) const;
13910
13911 // Returns the number of TestPartResult objects in the array.
13912 int size() const;
13913
13914 private:
13915 std::vector<TestPartResult> array_;
13916
13917 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(TestPartResultArray);
13918};
13919
13920// This interface knows how to report a test part result.
13921class GTEST_API_ TestPartResultReporterInterface {
13922 public:
13923 virtual ~TestPartResultReporterInterface() {}
13924
13925 virtual void ReportTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& result) = 0;
13926};
13927
13928namespace internal {
13929
13930// This helper class is used by {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NO_FATAL_FAILURE to check if a
13931// statement generates new fatal failures. To do so it registers itself as the
13932// current test part result reporter. Besides checking if fatal failures were
13933// reported, it only delegates the reporting to the former result reporter.
13934// The original result reporter is restored in the destructor.
13935// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
13936class GTEST_API_ HasNewFatalFailureHelper
13937 : public TestPartResultReporterInterface {
13938 public:
13939 HasNewFatalFailureHelper();
13940 ~HasNewFatalFailureHelper() override;
13941 void ReportTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& result) override;
13942 bool has_new_fatal_failure() const { return has_new_fatal_failure_; }
13943 private:
13944 bool has_new_fatal_failure_;
13945 TestPartResultReporterInterface* original_reporter_;
13946
13947 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(HasNewFatalFailureHelper);
13948};
13949
13950} // namespace internal
13951
13952} // namespace testing

13991
13992// This header implements typed tests and type-parameterized tests.
13993
13994// Typed (aka type-driven) tests repeat the same test for types in a
13995// list. You must know which types you want to test with when writing
13996// typed tests. Here's how you do it:
13997
13998#if 0
13999
14000// First, define a fixture class template. It should be parameterized
14001// by a type. Remember to derive it from testing::Test.
14002template <typename T>
14003class FooTest : public testing::Test {
14004 public:
14005 ...
14006 typedef std::list<T> List;
14007 static T shared_;
14008 T value_;
14009};
14010
14011// Next, associate a list of types with the test suite, which will be
14012// repeated for each type in the list. The typedef is necessary for
14013// the macro to parse correctly.
14014typedef testing::Types<char, int, unsigned int> MyTypes;
14015TYPED_TEST_SUITE(FooTest, MyTypes);
14016
14017// If the type list contains only one type, you can write that type
14018// directly without Types<...>:
14019// TYPED_TEST_SUITE(FooTest, int);
14020
14021// Then, use TYPED_TEST() instead of TEST_F() to define as many typed
14022// tests for this test suite as you want.
14023TYPED_TEST(FooTest, DoesBlah) {
14024 // Inside a test, refer to TypeParam to get the type parameter.
14025 // Since we are inside a derived class template, C++ requires use to
14026 // visit the members of FooTest via 'this'.
14027 TypeParam n = this->value_;
14028
14029 // To visit static members of the fixture, add the TestFixture::
14030 // prefix.
14031 n += TestFixture::shared_;
14032
14033 // To refer to typedefs in the fixture, add the "typename
14034 // TestFixture::" prefix.
14035 typename TestFixture::List values;
14036 values.push_back(n);
14037 ...
14038}
14039
14040TYPED_TEST(FooTest, HasPropertyA) { ... }
14041
14042// TYPED_TEST_SUITE takes an optional third argument which allows to specify a
14043// class that generates custom test name suffixes based on the type. This should
14044// be a class which has a static template function GetName(int index) returning
14045// a string for each type. The provided integer index equals the index of the
14046// type in the provided type list. In many cases the index can be ignored.
14047//
14048// For example:
14049// class MyTypeNames {
14050// public:
14051// template <typename T>
14052// static std::string GetName(int) {
14053// if (std::is_same<T, char>()) return "char";
14054// if (std::is_same<T, int>()) return "int";
14055// if (std::is_same<T, unsigned int>()) return "unsignedInt";
14056// }
14057// };
14058// TYPED_TEST_SUITE(FooTest, MyTypes, MyTypeNames);
14059
14060#endif // 0
14061
14062// Type-parameterized tests are abstract test patterns parameterized
14063// by a type. Compared with typed tests, type-parameterized tests
14064// allow you to define the test pattern without knowing what the type
14065// parameters are. The defined pattern can be instantiated with
14066// different types any number of times, in any number of translation
14067// units.
14068//
14069// If you are designing an interface or concept, you can define a
14070// suite of type-parameterized tests to verify properties that any
14071// valid implementation of the interface/concept should have. Then,
14072// each implementation can easily instantiate the test suite to verify
14073// that it conforms to the requirements, without having to write
14074// similar tests repeatedly. Here's an example:
14075
14076#if 0
14077
14078// First, define a fixture class template. It should be parameterized
14079// by a type. Remember to derive it from testing::Test.
14080template <typename T>
14081class FooTest : public testing::Test {
14082 ...
14083};
14084
14085// Next, declare that you will define a type-parameterized test suite
14086// (the _P suffix is for "parameterized" or "pattern", whichever you
14087// prefer):
14088TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P(FooTest);
14089
14090// Then, use TYPED_TEST_P() to define as many type-parameterized tests
14091// for this type-parameterized test suite as you want.
14092TYPED_TEST_P(FooTest, DoesBlah) {
14093 // Inside a test, refer to TypeParam to get the type parameter.
14094 TypeParam n = 0;
14095 ...
14096}
14097
14098TYPED_TEST_P(FooTest, HasPropertyA) { ... }
14099
14100// Now the tricky part: you need to register all test patterns before
14101// you can instantiate them. The first argument of the macro is the
14102// test suite name; the rest are the names of the tests in this test
14103// case.
14104REGISTER_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P(FooTest,
14105 DoesBlah, HasPropertyA);
14106
14107// Finally, you are free to instantiate the pattern with the types you
14108// want. If you put the above code in a header file, you can #include
14109// it in multiple C++ source files and instantiate it multiple times.
14110//
14111// To distinguish different instances of the pattern, the first
14112// argument to the INSTANTIATE_* macro is a prefix that will be added
14113// to the actual test suite name. Remember to pick unique prefixes for
14114// different instances.
14115typedef testing::Types<char, int, unsigned int> MyTypes;
14116INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P(My, FooTest, MyTypes);
14117
14118// If the type list contains only one type, you can write that type
14119// directly without Types<...>:
14120// INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P(My, FooTest, int);
14121//
14122// Similar to the optional argument of TYPED_TEST_SUITE above,
14123// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P takes an optional fourth argument which allows to
14124// generate custom names.
14125// INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P(My, FooTest, MyTypes, MyTypeNames);
14126
14127#endif // 0
14128
14129
14130// Implements typed tests.
14131
14132#if GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST
14133
14134// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
14135//
14136// Expands to the name of the typedef for the type parameters of the
14137// given test suite.
14138#define GTEST_TYPE_PARAMS_(TestSuiteName) gtest_type_params_##TestSuiteName##_
14139
14140// Expands to the name of the typedef for the NameGenerator, responsible for
14141// creating the suffixes of the name.
14142#define GTEST_NAME_GENERATOR_(TestSuiteName) \
14143 gtest_type_params_##TestSuiteName##_NameGenerator
14144
14145// The 'Types' template argument below must have spaces around it
14146// since some compilers may choke on '>>' when passing a template
14147// instance (e.g. Types<int>)
14148#define TYPED_TEST_SUITE(CaseName, Types, ...) \
14149 typedef ::testing::internal::TypeList<Types>::type GTEST_TYPE_PARAMS_( \
14150 CaseName); \
14151 typedef ::testing::internal::NameGeneratorSelector<__VA_ARGS__>::type \
14152 GTEST_NAME_GENERATOR_(CaseName)
14153
14154# define TYPED_TEST(CaseName, TestName) \
14155 template <typename gtest_TypeParam_> \
14156 class GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(CaseName, TestName) \
14157 : public CaseName<gtest_TypeParam_> { \
14158 private: \
14159 typedef CaseName<gtest_TypeParam_> TestFixture; \
14160 typedef gtest_TypeParam_ TypeParam; \
14161 virtual void TestBody(); \
14162 }; \
14163 static bool gtest_##CaseName##_##TestName##_registered_ \
14164 GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ = \
14165 ::testing::internal::TypeParameterizedTest< \
14166 CaseName, \
14167 ::testing::internal::TemplateSel<GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(CaseName, \
14168 TestName)>, \
14169 GTEST_TYPE_PARAMS_( \
14170 CaseName)>::Register("", \
14171 ::testing::internal::CodeLocation( \
14172 __FILE__, __LINE__), \
14173 #CaseName, #TestName, 0, \
14174 ::testing::internal::GenerateNames< \
14175 GTEST_NAME_GENERATOR_(CaseName), \
14176 GTEST_TYPE_PARAMS_(CaseName)>()); \
14177 template <typename gtest_TypeParam_> \
14178 void GTEST_TEST_CLASS_NAME_(CaseName, \
14179 TestName)<gtest_TypeParam_>::TestBody()
14180
14181// Legacy API is deprecated but still available
14182#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
14183#define TYPED_TEST_CASE TYPED_TEST_SUITE
14184#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
14185
14186#endif // GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST
14187
14188// Implements type-parameterized tests.
14189
14190#if GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST_P
14191
14192// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
14193//
14194// Expands to the namespace name that the type-parameterized tests for
14195// the given type-parameterized test suite are defined in. The exact
14196// name of the namespace is subject to change without notice.
14197#define GTEST_SUITE_NAMESPACE_(TestSuiteName) gtest_suite_##TestSuiteName##_
14198
14199// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
14200//
14201// Expands to the name of the variable used to remember the names of
14202// the defined tests in the given test suite.
14203#define GTEST_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P_STATE_(TestSuiteName) \
14204 gtest_typed_test_suite_p_state_##TestSuiteName##_
14205
14206// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE DIRECTLY.
14207//
14208// Expands to the name of the variable used to remember the names of
14209// the registered tests in the given test suite.
14210#define GTEST_REGISTERED_TEST_NAMES_(TestSuiteName) \
14211 gtest_registered_test_names_##TestSuiteName##_
14212
14213// The variables defined in the type-parameterized test macros are
14214// static as typically these macros are used in a .h file that can be
14215// #included in multiple translation units linked together.
14216#define TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P(SuiteName) \
14217 static ::testing::internal::TypedTestSuitePState \
14218 GTEST_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P_STATE_(SuiteName)
14219
14220// Legacy API is deprecated but still available
14221#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
14222#define TYPED_TEST_CASE_P TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P
14223#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
14224
14225#define TYPED_TEST_P(SuiteName, TestName) \
14226 namespace GTEST_SUITE_NAMESPACE_(SuiteName) { \
14227 template <typename gtest_TypeParam_> \
14228 class TestName : public SuiteName<gtest_TypeParam_> { \
14229 private: \
14230 typedef SuiteName<gtest_TypeParam_> TestFixture; \
14231 typedef gtest_TypeParam_ TypeParam; \
14232 virtual void TestBody(); \
14233 }; \
14234 static bool gtest_##TestName##_defined_ GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ = \
14235 GTEST_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P_STATE_(SuiteName).AddTestName( \
14236 __FILE__, __LINE__, #SuiteName, #TestName); \
14237 } \
14238 template <typename gtest_TypeParam_> \
14239 void GTEST_SUITE_NAMESPACE_( \
14240 SuiteName)::TestName<gtest_TypeParam_>::TestBody()
14241
14242#define REGISTER_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P(SuiteName, ...) \
14243 namespace GTEST_SUITE_NAMESPACE_(SuiteName) { \
14244 typedef ::testing::internal::Templates<__VA_ARGS__>::type gtest_AllTests_; \
14245 } \
14246 static const char* const GTEST_REGISTERED_TEST_NAMES_( \
14247 SuiteName) GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ = \
14248 GTEST_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P_STATE_(SuiteName).VerifyRegisteredTestNames( \
14249 __FILE__, __LINE__, #__VA_ARGS__)
14250
14251// Legacy API is deprecated but still available
14252#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
14253#define REGISTER_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P REGISTER_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P
14254#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
14255
14256// The 'Types' template argument below must have spaces around it
14257// since some compilers may choke on '>>' when passing a template
14258// instance (e.g. Types<int>)
14259#define INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P(Prefix, SuiteName, Types, ...) \
14260 static bool gtest_##Prefix##_##SuiteName GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_ = \
14261 ::testing::internal::TypeParameterizedTestSuite< \
14262 SuiteName, GTEST_SUITE_NAMESPACE_(SuiteName)::gtest_AllTests_, \
14263 ::testing::internal::TypeList<Types>::type>:: \
14264 Register(#Prefix, \
14265 ::testing::internal::CodeLocation(__FILE__, __LINE__), \
14266 &GTEST_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P_STATE_(SuiteName), #SuiteName, \
14267 GTEST_REGISTERED_TEST_NAMES_(SuiteName), \
14268 ::testing::internal::GenerateNames< \
14269 ::testing::internal::NameGeneratorSelector< \
14270 __VA_ARGS__>::type, \
14271 ::testing::internal::TypeList<Types>::type>())
14272
14273// Legacy API is deprecated but still available
14274#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
14275#define INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_CASE_P INSTANTIATE_TYPED_TEST_SUITE_P
14276#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
14277
14278#endif // GTEST_HAS_TYPED_TEST_P
