14284
14285// Depending on the platform, different string classes are available.
14286// On Linux, in addition to ::std::string, Google also makes use of
14287// class ::string, which has the same interface as ::std::string, but
14288// has a different implementation.
14289//
14290// You can define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING to 1 to indicate that
14291// ::string is available AND is a distinct type to ::std::string, or
14292// define it to 0 to indicate otherwise.
14293//
14294// If ::std::string and ::string are the same class on your platform
14295// due to aliasing, you should define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING to 0.
14296//
14297// If you do not define GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING, it is defined
14298// heuristically.
14299
14300namespace testing {
14301
14302// Silence C4100 (unreferenced formal parameter) and 4805
14303// unsafe mix of type 'const int' and type 'const bool'
14304#ifdef _MSC_VER
14305# pragma warning(push)
14306# pragma warning(disable:4805)
14307# pragma warning(disable:4100)
14308#endif
14309
14310
14311// Declares the flags.
14312
14313// This flag temporary enables the disabled tests.
14314GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(also_run_disabled_tests);
14315
14316// This flag brings the debugger on an assertion failure.
14317GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(break_on_failure);
14318
14319// This flag controls whether Google Test catches all test-thrown exceptions
14320// and logs them as failures.
14321GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(catch_exceptions);
14322
14323// This flag enables using colors in terminal output. Available values are
14324// "yes" to enable colors, "no" (disable colors), or "auto" (the default)
14325// to let Google Test decide.
14326GTEST_DECLARE_string_(color);
14327
14328// This flag sets up the filter to select by name using a glob pattern
14329// the tests to run. If the filter is not given all tests are executed.
14330GTEST_DECLARE_string_(filter);
14331
14332// This flag controls whether Google Test installs a signal handler that dumps
14333// debugging information when fatal signals are raised.
14334GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(install_failure_signal_handler);
14335
14336// This flag causes the Google Test to list tests. None of the tests listed
14337// are actually run if the flag is provided.
14338GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(list_tests);
14339
14340// This flag controls whether Google Test emits a detailed XML report to a file
14341// in addition to its normal textual output.
14342GTEST_DECLARE_string_(output);
14343
14344// This flags control whether Google Test prints the elapsed time for each
14345// test.
14346GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(print_time);
14347
14348// This flags control whether Google Test prints UTF8 characters as text.
14349GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(print_utf8);
14350
14351// This flag specifies the random number seed.
14352GTEST_DECLARE_int32_(random_seed);
14353
14354// This flag sets how many times the tests are repeated. The default value
14355// is 1. If the value is -1 the tests are repeating forever.
14356GTEST_DECLARE_int32_(repeat);
14357
14358// This flag controls whether Google Test includes Google Test internal
14359// stack frames in failure stack traces.
14360GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(show_internal_stack_frames);
14361
14362// When this flag is specified, tests' order is randomized on every iteration.
14363GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(shuffle);
14364
14365// This flag specifies the maximum number of stack frames to be
14366// printed in a failure message.
14367GTEST_DECLARE_int32_(stack_trace_depth);
14368
14369// When this flag is specified, a failed assertion will throw an
14370// exception if exceptions are enabled, or exit the program with a
14371// non-zero code otherwise. For use with an external test framework.
14372GTEST_DECLARE_bool_(throw_on_failure);
14373
14374// When this flag is set with a "host:port" string, on supported

14420// A class for indicating whether an assertion was successful. When
14421// the assertion wasn't successful, the AssertionResult object
14422// remembers a non-empty message that describes how it failed.
14423//
14424// To create an instance of this class, use one of the factory functions
14425// (AssertionSuccess() and AssertionFailure()).
14426//
14427// This class is useful for two purposes:
14428// 1. Defining predicate functions to be used with Boolean test assertions
14429// EXPECT_TRUE/EXPECT_FALSE and their ASSERT_ counterparts
14430// 2. Defining predicate-format functions to be
14431// used with predicate assertions (ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT*, etc).
14432//
14433// For example, if you define IsEven predicate:
14434//
14435// testing::AssertionResult IsEven(int n) {
14436// if ((n % 2) == 0)
14437// return testing::AssertionSuccess();
14438// else
14439// return testing::AssertionFailure() << n << " is odd";
14440// }
14441//
14442// Then the failed expectation EXPECT_TRUE(IsEven(Fib(5)))
14443// will print the message
14444//
14445// Value of: IsEven(Fib(5))
14446// Actual: false (5 is odd)
14447// Expected: true
14448//
14449// instead of a more opaque
14450//
14451// Value of: IsEven(Fib(5))
14452// Actual: false
14453// Expected: true
14454//
14455// in case IsEven is a simple Boolean predicate.
14456//
14457// If you expect your predicate to be reused and want to support informative
14458// messages in EXPECT_FALSE and ASSERT_FALSE (negative assertions show up
14459// about half as often as positive ones in our tests), supply messages for
14460// both success and failure cases:
14461//
14462// testing::AssertionResult IsEven(int n) {
14463// if ((n % 2) == 0)
14464// return testing::AssertionSuccess() << n << " is even";
14465// else
14466// return testing::AssertionFailure() << n << " is odd";
14467// }
14468//
14469// Then a statement EXPECT_FALSE(IsEven(Fib(6))) will print
14470//
14471// Value of: IsEven(Fib(6))
14472// Actual: true (8 is even)
14473// Expected: false
14474//
14475// NB: Predicates that support negative Boolean assertions have reduced
14476// performance in positive ones so be careful not to use them in tests
14477// that have lots (tens of thousands) of positive Boolean assertions.
14478//
14479// To use this class with EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT assertions such as:
14480//
14481// // Verifies that Foo() returns an even number.
14482// EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT1(IsEven, Foo());
14483//
14484// you need to define:
14485//
14486// testing::AssertionResult IsEven(const char* expr, int n) {
14487// if ((n % 2) == 0)
14488// return testing::AssertionSuccess();
14489// else
14490// return testing::AssertionFailure()
14491// << "Expected: " << expr << " is even\n Actual: it's " << n;
14492// }
14493//
14494// If Foo() returns 5, you will see the following message:
14495//
14496// Expected: Foo() is even
14497// Actual: it's 5
14498//
14499class GTEST_API_ AssertionResult {
14500 public:
14501 // Copy constructor.
14502 // Used in EXPECT_TRUE/FALSE(assertion_result).
14503 AssertionResult(const AssertionResult& other);
14504
14505#if defined(_MSC_VER) && _MSC_VER < 1910
14506 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(4800 /* forcing value to bool */)
14507#endif
14508
14509 // Used in the EXPECT_TRUE/FALSE(bool_expression).
14510 //
14511 // T must be contextually convertible to bool.
14512 //
14513 // The second parameter prevents this overload from being considered if
14514 // the argument is implicitly convertible to AssertionResult. In that case
14515 // we want AssertionResult's copy constructor to be used.
14516 template <typename T>
14517 explicit AssertionResult(
14518 const T& success,
14519 typename internal::EnableIf<
14520 !std::is_convertible<T, AssertionResult>::value>::type*
14521 /*enabler*/
14522 = nullptr)
14523 : success_(success) {}
14524
14525#if defined(_MSC_VER) && _MSC_VER < 1910
14526 GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_()
14527#endif
14528
14529 // Assignment operator.
14530 AssertionResult& operator=(AssertionResult other) {
14531 swap(other);
14532 return *this;
14533 }
14534
14535 // Returns true iff the assertion succeeded.
14536 operator bool() const { return success_; } // NOLINT
14537
14538 // Returns the assertion's negation. Used with EXPECT/ASSERT_FALSE.
14539 AssertionResult operator!() const;
14540
14541 // Returns the text streamed into this AssertionResult. Test assertions
14542 // use it when they fail (i.e., the predicate's outcome doesn't match the
14543 // assertion's expectation). When nothing has been streamed into the
14544 // object, returns an empty string.
14545 const char* message() const {
14546 return message_.get() != nullptr ? message_->c_str() : "";
14547 }
14548 // Deprecated; please use message() instead.
14549 const char* failure_message() const { return message(); }
14550
14551 // Streams a custom failure message into this object.
14552 template <typename T> AssertionResult& operator<<(const T& value) {
14553 AppendMessage(Message() << value);
14554 return *this;
14555 }
14556
14557 // Allows streaming basic output manipulators such as endl or flush into
14558 // this object.
14559 AssertionResult& operator<<(
14560 ::std::ostream& (*basic_manipulator)(::std::ostream& stream)) {
14561 AppendMessage(Message() << basic_manipulator);
14562 return *this;
14563 }
14564
14565 private:
14566 // Appends the contents of message to message_.
14567 void AppendMessage(const Message& a_message) {
14568 if (message_.get() == nullptr) message_.reset(new ::std::string);
14569 message_->append(a_message.GetString().c_str());
14570 }
14571
14572 // Swap the contents of this AssertionResult with other.
14573 void swap(AssertionResult& other);
14574
14575 // Stores result of the assertion predicate.
14576 bool success_;
14577 // Stores the message describing the condition in case the expectation
14578 // construct is not satisfied with the predicate's outcome.
14579 // Referenced via a pointer to avoid taking too much stack frame space
14580 // with test assertions.
14581 std::unique_ptr< ::std::string> message_;
14582};
14583
14584// Makes a successful assertion result.
14585GTEST_API_ AssertionResult AssertionSuccess();
14586
14587// Makes a failed assertion result.
14588GTEST_API_ AssertionResult AssertionFailure();
14589
14590// Makes a failed assertion result with the given failure message.
14591// Deprecated; use AssertionFailure() << msg.
14592GTEST_API_ AssertionResult AssertionFailure(const Message& msg);
14593
14594} // namespace testing

14640// This header implements a family of generic predicate assertion
14641// macros:
14642//
14643// ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT1(pred_format, v1)
14644// ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(pred_format, v1, v2)
14645// ...
14646//
14647// where pred_format is a function or functor that takes n (in the
14648// case of ASSERT_PRED_FORMATn) values and their source expression
14649// text, and returns a testing::AssertionResult. See the definition
14650// of ASSERT_EQ in gtest.h for an example.
14651//
14652// If you don't care about formatting, you can use the more
14653// restrictive version:
14654//
14655// ASSERT_PRED1(pred, v1)
14656// ASSERT_PRED2(pred, v1, v2)
14657// ...
14658//
14659// where pred is an n-ary function or functor that returns bool,
14660// and the values v1, v2, ..., must support the << operator for
14661// streaming to std::ostream.
14662//
14663// We also define the EXPECT_* variations.
14664//
14665// For now we only support predicates whose arity is at most 5.
14666// Please email googletestframework@googlegroups.com if you need
14667// support for higher arities.
14668
14669// GTEST_ASSERT_ is the basic statement to which all of the assertions
14670// in this file reduce. Don't use this in your code.
14671
14672#define GTEST_ASSERT_(expression, on_failure) \
14673 GTEST_AMBIGUOUS_ELSE_BLOCKER_ \
14674 if (const ::testing::AssertionResult gtest_ar = (expression)) \
14675 ; \
14676 else \
14677 on_failure(gtest_ar.failure_message())
14678

14680// Helper function for implementing {EXPECT|ASSERT}_PRED1. Don't use
14681// this in your code.
14682template <typename Pred,
14683 typename T1>
14684AssertionResult AssertPred1Helper(const char* pred_text,
14685 const char* e1,
14686 Pred pred,
14687 const T1& v1) {
14688 if (pred(v1)) return AssertionSuccess();
14689
14690 return AssertionFailure()
14691 << pred_text << "(" << e1 << ") evaluates to false, where"
14692 << "\n"
14693 << e1 << " evaluates to " << ::testing::PrintToString(v1);
14694}

14959
14960// The abstract class that all tests inherit from.
14961//
14962// In Google Test, a unit test program contains one or many TestSuites, and
14963// each TestSuite contains one or many Tests.
14964//
14965// When you define a test using the TEST macro, you don't need to
14966// explicitly derive from Test - the TEST macro automatically does
14967// this for you.
14968//
14969// The only time you derive from Test is when defining a test fixture
14970// to be used in a TEST_F. For example:
14971//
14972// class FooTest : public testing::Test {
14973// protected:
14974// void SetUp() override { ... }
14975// void TearDown() override { ... }
14976// ...
14977// };
14978//
14979// TEST_F(FooTest, Bar) { ... }
14980// TEST_F(FooTest, Baz) { ... }
14981//
14982// Test is not copyable.
14983class GTEST_API_ Test {
14984 public:
14985 friend class TestInfo;
14986
14987 // The d'tor is virtual as we intend to inherit from Test.
14988 virtual ~Test();
14989
14990 // Sets up the stuff shared by all tests in this test case.
14991 //
14992 // Google Test will call Foo::SetUpTestSuite() before running the first
14993 // test in test case Foo. Hence a sub-class can define its own
14994 // SetUpTestSuite() method to shadow the one defined in the super
14995 // class.
14996 static void SetUpTestSuite() {}
14997
14998 // Tears down the stuff shared by all tests in this test case.
14999 //
15000 // Google Test will call Foo::TearDownTestSuite() after running the last
15001 // test in test case Foo. Hence a sub-class can define its own
15002 // TearDownTestSuite() method to shadow the one defined in the super
15003 // class.
15004 static void TearDownTestSuite() {}
15005
15006 // Legacy API is deprecated but still available
15007#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15008 static void TearDownTestCase() {}
15009 static void SetUpTestCase() {}
15010#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15011
15012 // Returns true iff the current test has a fatal failure.
15013 static bool HasFatalFailure();
15014
15015 // Returns true iff the current test has a non-fatal failure.
15016 static bool HasNonfatalFailure();
15017
15018 // Returns true iff the current test was skipped.
15019 static bool IsSkipped();
15020
15021 // Returns true iff the current test has a (either fatal or
15022 // non-fatal) failure.
15023 static bool HasFailure() { return HasFatalFailure() || HasNonfatalFailure(); }
15024
15025 // Logs a property for the current test, test suite, or for the entire
15026 // invocation of the test program when used outside of the context of a
15027 // test suite. Only the last value for a given key is remembered. These
15028 // are public static so they can be called from utility functions that are
15029 // not members of the test fixture. Calls to RecordProperty made during
15030 // lifespan of the test (from the moment its constructor starts to the
15031 // moment its destructor finishes) will be output in XML as attributes of
15032 // the <testcase> element. Properties recorded from fixture's
15033 // SetUpTestSuite or TearDownTestSuite are logged as attributes of the
15034 // corresponding <testsuite> element. Calls to RecordProperty made in the
15035 // global context (before or after invocation of RUN_ALL_TESTS and from
15036 // SetUp/TearDown method of Environment objects registered with Google
15037 // Test) will be output as attributes of the <testsuites> element.
15038 static void RecordProperty(const std::string& key, const std::string& value);
15039 static void RecordProperty(const std::string& key, int value);
15040
15041 protected:
15042 // Creates a Test object.
15043 Test();
15044
15045 // Sets up the test fixture.
15046 virtual void SetUp();
15047
15048 // Tears down the test fixture.
15049 virtual void TearDown();
15050
15051 private:
15052 // Returns true iff the current test has the same fixture class as
15053 // the first test in the current test suite.
15054 static bool HasSameFixtureClass();
15055
15056 // Runs the test after the test fixture has been set up.
15057 //
15058 // A sub-class must implement this to define the test logic.
15059 //
15060 // DO NOT OVERRIDE THIS FUNCTION DIRECTLY IN A USER PROGRAM.
15061 // Instead, use the TEST or TEST_F macro.
15062 virtual void TestBody() = 0;
15063
15064 // Sets up, executes, and tears down the test.
15065 void Run();
15066
15067 // Deletes self. We deliberately pick an unusual name for this
15068 // internal method to avoid clashing with names used in user TESTs.
15069 void DeleteSelf_() { delete this; }
15070
15071 const std::unique_ptr<GTEST_FLAG_SAVER_> gtest_flag_saver_;
15072
15073 // Often a user misspells SetUp() as Setup() and spends a long time
15074 // wondering why it is never called by Google Test. The declaration of
15075 // the following method is solely for catching such an error at
15076 // compile time:
15077 //
15078 // - The return type is deliberately chosen to be not void, so it
15079 // will be a conflict if void Setup() is declared in the user's
15080 // test fixture.
15081 //
15082 // - This method is private, so it will be another compiler error
15083 // if the method is called from the user's test fixture.
15084 //
15085 // DO NOT OVERRIDE THIS FUNCTION.
15086 //
15087 // If you see an error about overriding the following function or
15088 // about it being private, you have mis-spelled SetUp() as Setup().
15089 struct Setup_should_be_spelled_SetUp {};
15090 virtual Setup_should_be_spelled_SetUp* Setup() { return nullptr; }
15091
15092 // We disallow copying Tests.
15093 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(Test);
15094};
15095
15096typedef internal::TimeInMillis TimeInMillis;
15097
15098// A copyable object representing a user specified test property which can be
15099// output as a key/value string pair.
15100//
15101// Don't inherit from TestProperty as its destructor is not virtual.
15102class TestProperty {
15103 public:
15104 // C'tor. TestProperty does NOT have a default constructor.
15105 // Always use this constructor (with parameters) to create a
15106 // TestProperty object.
15107 TestProperty(const std::string& a_key, const std::string& a_value) :
15108 key_(a_key), value_(a_value) {
15109 }
15110
15111 // Gets the user supplied key.
15112 const char* key() const {
15113 return key_.c_str();
15114 }
15115
15116 // Gets the user supplied value.
15117 const char* value() const {
15118 return value_.c_str();
15119 }
15120
15121 // Sets a new value, overriding the one supplied in the constructor.
15122 void SetValue(const std::string& new_value) {
15123 value_ = new_value;
15124 }
15125
15126 private:
15127 // The key supplied by the user.
15128 std::string key_;
15129 // The value supplied by the user.
15130 std::string value_;
15131};
15132
15133// The result of a single Test. This includes a list of
15134// TestPartResults, a list of TestProperties, a count of how many
15135// death tests there are in the Test, and how much time it took to run
15136// the Test.
15137//
15138// TestResult is not copyable.
15139class GTEST_API_ TestResult {
15140 public:
15141 // Creates an empty TestResult.
15142 TestResult();
15143
15144 // D'tor. Do not inherit from TestResult.
15145 ~TestResult();
15146
15147 // Gets the number of all test parts. This is the sum of the number
15148 // of successful test parts and the number of failed test parts.
15149 int total_part_count() const;
15150
15151 // Returns the number of the test properties.
15152 int test_property_count() const;
15153
15154 // Returns true iff the test passed (i.e. no test part failed).
15155 bool Passed() const { return !Skipped() && !Failed(); }
15156
15157 // Returns true iff the test was skipped.
15158 bool Skipped() const;
15159
15160 // Returns true iff the test failed.
15161 bool Failed() const;
15162
15163 // Returns true iff the test fatally failed.
15164 bool HasFatalFailure() const;
15165
15166 // Returns true iff the test has a non-fatal failure.
15167 bool HasNonfatalFailure() const;
15168
15169 // Returns the elapsed time, in milliseconds.
15170 TimeInMillis elapsed_time() const { return elapsed_time_; }
15171
15172 // Returns the i-th test part result among all the results. i can range from 0
15173 // to total_part_count() - 1. If i is not in that range, aborts the program.
15174 const TestPartResult& GetTestPartResult(int i) const;
15175
15176 // Returns the i-th test property. i can range from 0 to
15177 // test_property_count() - 1. If i is not in that range, aborts the
15178 // program.
15179 const TestProperty& GetTestProperty(int i) const;
15180
15181 private:
15182 friend class TestInfo;
15183 friend class TestSuite;
15184 friend class UnitTest;
15185 friend class internal::DefaultGlobalTestPartResultReporter;
15186 friend class internal::ExecDeathTest;
15187 friend class internal::TestResultAccessor;
15188 friend class internal::UnitTestImpl;
15189 friend class internal::WindowsDeathTest;
15190 friend class internal::FuchsiaDeathTest;
15191
15192 // Gets the vector of TestPartResults.
15193 const std::vector<TestPartResult>& test_part_results() const {
15194 return test_part_results_;
15195 }
15196
15197 // Gets the vector of TestProperties.
15198 const std::vector<TestProperty>& test_properties() const {
15199 return test_properties_;
15200 }
15201
15202 // Sets the elapsed time.
15203 void set_elapsed_time(TimeInMillis elapsed) { elapsed_time_ = elapsed; }
15204
15205 // Adds a test property to the list. The property is validated and may add
15206 // a non-fatal failure if invalid (e.g., if it conflicts with reserved
15207 // key names). If a property is already recorded for the same key, the
15208 // value will be updated, rather than storing multiple values for the same
15209 // key. xml_element specifies the element for which the property is being
15210 // recorded and is used for validation.
15211 void RecordProperty(const std::string& xml_element,
15212 const TestProperty& test_property);
15213
15214 // Adds a failure if the key is a reserved attribute of Google Test
15215 // testsuite tags. Returns true if the property is valid.
15216 // FIXME: Validate attribute names are legal and human readable.
15217 static bool ValidateTestProperty(const std::string& xml_element,
15218 const TestProperty& test_property);
15219
15220 // Adds a test part result to the list.
15221 void AddTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& test_part_result);
15222
15223 // Returns the death test count.
15224 int death_test_count() const { return death_test_count_; }
15225
15226 // Increments the death test count, returning the new count.
15227 int increment_death_test_count() { return ++death_test_count_; }
15228
15229 // Clears the test part results.
15230 void ClearTestPartResults();
15231
15232 // Clears the object.
15233 void Clear();
15234
15235 // Protects mutable state of the property vector and of owned
15236 // properties, whose values may be updated.
15237 internal::Mutex test_properites_mutex_;
15238
15239 // The vector of TestPartResults
15240 std::vector<TestPartResult> test_part_results_;
15241 // The vector of TestProperties
15242 std::vector<TestProperty> test_properties_;
15243 // Running count of death tests.
15244 int death_test_count_;
15245 // The elapsed time, in milliseconds.
15246 TimeInMillis elapsed_time_;
15247
15248 // We disallow copying TestResult.
15249 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(TestResult);
15250}; // class TestResult

15252// A TestInfo object stores the following information about a test:
15253//
15254// Test suite name
15255// Test name
15256// Whether the test should be run
15257// A function pointer that creates the test object when invoked
15258// Test result
15259//
15260// The constructor of TestInfo registers itself with the UnitTest
15261// singleton such that the RUN_ALL_TESTS() macro knows which tests to
15262// run.
15263class GTEST_API_ TestInfo {
15264 public:
15265 // Destructs a TestInfo object. This function is not virtual, so
15266 // don't inherit from TestInfo.
15267 ~TestInfo();
15268
15269 // Returns the test suite name.
15270 const char* test_suite_name() const { return test_suite_name_.c_str(); }
15271
15272// Legacy API is deprecated but still available
15273#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15274 const char* test_case_name() const { return test_suite_name(); }
15275#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15276
15277 // Returns the test name.
15278 const char* name() const { return name_.c_str(); }
15279
15280 // Returns the name of the parameter type, or NULL if this is not a typed
15281 // or a type-parameterized test.
15282 const char* type_param() const {
15283 if (type_param_.get() != nullptr) return type_param_->c_str();
15284 return nullptr;
15285 }
15286
15287 // Returns the text representation of the value parameter, or NULL if this
15288 // is not a value-parameterized test.
15289 const char* value_param() const {
15290 if (value_param_.get() != nullptr) return value_param_->c_str();
15291 return nullptr;
15292 }
15293
15294 // Returns the file name where this test is defined.
15295 const char* file() const { return location_.file.c_str(); }
15296
15297 // Returns the line where this test is defined.
15298 int line() const { return location_.line; }
15299
15300 // Return true if this test should not be run because it's in another shard.
15301 bool is_in_another_shard() const { return is_in_another_shard_; }
15302
15303 // Returns true if this test should run, that is if the test is not
15304 // disabled (or it is disabled but the also_run_disabled_tests flag has
15305 // been specified) and its full name matches the user-specified filter.
15306 //
15307 // Google Test allows the user to filter the tests by their full names.
15308 // The full name of a test Bar in test suite Foo is defined as
15309 // "Foo.Bar". Only the tests that match the filter will run.
15310 //
15311 // A filter is a colon-separated list of glob (not regex) patterns,
15312 // optionally followed by a '-' and a colon-separated list of
15313 // negative patterns (tests to exclude). A test is run if it
15314 // matches one of the positive patterns and does not match any of
15315 // the negative patterns.
15316 //
15317 // For example, *A*:Foo.* is a filter that matches any string that
15318 // contains the character 'A' or starts with "Foo.".
15319 bool should_run() const { return should_run_; }
15320
15321 // Returns true iff this test will appear in the XML report.
15322 bool is_reportable() const {
15323 // The XML report includes tests matching the filter, excluding those
15324 // run in other shards.
15325 return matches_filter_ && !is_in_another_shard_;
15326 }
15327
15328 // Returns the result of the test.
15329 const TestResult* result() const { return &result_; }
15330
15331 private:
15332#if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
15333 friend class internal::DefaultDeathTestFactory;
15334#endif // GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
15335 friend class Test;
15336 friend class TestSuite;
15337 friend class internal::UnitTestImpl;
15338 friend class internal::StreamingListenerTest;
15339 friend TestInfo* internal::MakeAndRegisterTestInfo(
15340 const char* test_suite_name, const char* name, const char* type_param,
15341 const char* value_param, internal::CodeLocation code_location,
15342 internal::TypeId fixture_class_id, internal::SetUpTestSuiteFunc set_up_tc,
15343 internal::TearDownTestSuiteFunc tear_down_tc,
15344 internal::TestFactoryBase* factory);
15345
15346 // Constructs a TestInfo object. The newly constructed instance assumes
15347 // ownership of the factory object.
15348 TestInfo(const std::string& test_suite_name, const std::string& name,
15349 const char* a_type_param, // NULL if not a type-parameterized test
15350 const char* a_value_param, // NULL if not a value-parameterized test
15351 internal::CodeLocation a_code_location,
15352 internal::TypeId fixture_class_id,
15353 internal::TestFactoryBase* factory);
15354
15355 // Increments the number of death tests encountered in this test so
15356 // far.
15357 int increment_death_test_count() {
15358 return result_.increment_death_test_count();
15359 }
15360
15361 // Creates the test object, runs it, records its result, and then
15362 // deletes it.
15363 void Run();
15364
15365 static void ClearTestResult(TestInfo* test_info) {
15366 test_info->result_.Clear();
15367 }
15368
15369 // These fields are immutable properties of the test.
15370 const std::string test_suite_name_; // test suite name
15371 const std::string name_; // Test name
15372 // Name of the parameter type, or NULL if this is not a typed or a
15373 // type-parameterized test.
15374 const std::unique_ptr<const ::std::string> type_param_;
15375 // Text representation of the value parameter, or NULL if this is not a
15376 // value-parameterized test.
15377 const std::unique_ptr<const ::std::string> value_param_;
15378 internal::CodeLocation location_;
15379 const internal::TypeId fixture_class_id_; // ID of the test fixture class
15380 bool should_run_; // True iff this test should run
15381 bool is_disabled_; // True iff this test is disabled
15382 bool matches_filter_; // True if this test matches the
15383 // user-specified filter.
15384 bool is_in_another_shard_; // Will be run in another shard.
15385 internal::TestFactoryBase* const factory_; // The factory that creates
15386 // the test object
15387
15388 // This field is mutable and needs to be reset before running the
15389 // test for the second time.
15390 TestResult result_;
15391
15392 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(TestInfo);
15393};

15395// A test suite, which consists of a vector of TestInfos.
15396//
15397// TestSuite is not copyable.
15398class GTEST_API_ TestSuite {
15399 public:
15400 // Creates a TestSuite with the given name.
15401 //
15402 // TestSuite does NOT have a default constructor. Always use this
15403 // constructor to create a TestSuite object.
15404 //
15405 // Arguments:
15406 //
15407 // name: name of the test suite
15408 // a_type_param: the name of the test's type parameter, or NULL if
15409 // this is not a type-parameterized test.
15410 // set_up_tc: pointer to the function that sets up the test suite
15411 // tear_down_tc: pointer to the function that tears down the test suite
15412 TestSuite(const char* name, const char* a_type_param,
15413 internal::SetUpTestSuiteFunc set_up_tc,
15414 internal::TearDownTestSuiteFunc tear_down_tc);
15415
15416 // Destructor of TestSuite.
15417 virtual ~TestSuite();
15418
15419 // Gets the name of the TestSuite.
15420 const char* name() const { return name_.c_str(); }
15421
15422 // Returns the name of the parameter type, or NULL if this is not a
15423 // type-parameterized test suite.
15424 const char* type_param() const {
15425 if (type_param_.get() != nullptr) return type_param_->c_str();
15426 return nullptr;
15427 }
15428
15429 // Returns true if any test in this test suite should run.
15430 bool should_run() const { return should_run_; }
15431
15432 // Gets the number of successful tests in this test suite.
15433 int successful_test_count() const;
15434
15435 // Gets the number of skipped tests in this test suite.
15436 int skipped_test_count() const;
15437
15438 // Gets the number of failed tests in this test suite.
15439 int failed_test_count() const;
15440
15441 // Gets the number of disabled tests that will be reported in the XML report.
15442 int reportable_disabled_test_count() const;
15443
15444 // Gets the number of disabled tests in this test suite.
15445 int disabled_test_count() const;
15446
15447 // Gets the number of tests to be printed in the XML report.
15448 int reportable_test_count() const;
15449
15450 // Get the number of tests in this test suite that should run.
15451 int test_to_run_count() const;
15452
15453 // Gets the number of all tests in this test suite.
15454 int total_test_count() const;
15455
15456 // Returns true iff the test suite passed.
15457 bool Passed() const { return !Failed(); }
15458
15459 // Returns true iff the test suite failed.
15460 bool Failed() const { return failed_test_count() > 0; }
15461
15462 // Returns the elapsed time, in milliseconds.
15463 TimeInMillis elapsed_time() const { return elapsed_time_; }
15464
15465 // Returns the i-th test among all the tests. i can range from 0 to
15466 // total_test_count() - 1. If i is not in that range, returns NULL.
15467 const TestInfo* GetTestInfo(int i) const;
15468
15469 // Returns the TestResult that holds test properties recorded during
15470 // execution of SetUpTestSuite and TearDownTestSuite.
15471 const TestResult& ad_hoc_test_result() const { return ad_hoc_test_result_; }
15472
15473 private:
15474 friend class Test;
15475 friend class internal::UnitTestImpl;
15476
15477 // Gets the (mutable) vector of TestInfos in this TestSuite.
15478 std::vector<TestInfo*>& test_info_list() { return test_info_list_; }
15479
15480 // Gets the (immutable) vector of TestInfos in this TestSuite.
15481 const std::vector<TestInfo*>& test_info_list() const {
15482 return test_info_list_;
15483 }
15484
15485 // Returns the i-th test among all the tests. i can range from 0 to
15486 // total_test_count() - 1. If i is not in that range, returns NULL.
15487 TestInfo* GetMutableTestInfo(int i);
15488
15489 // Sets the should_run member.
15490 void set_should_run(bool should) { should_run_ = should; }
15491
15492 // Adds a TestInfo to this test suite. Will delete the TestInfo upon
15493 // destruction of the TestSuite object.
15494 void AddTestInfo(TestInfo * test_info);
15495
15496 // Clears the results of all tests in this test suite.
15497 void ClearResult();
15498
15499 // Clears the results of all tests in the given test suite.
15500 static void ClearTestSuiteResult(TestSuite* test_suite) {
15501 test_suite->ClearResult();
15502 }
15503
15504 // Runs every test in this TestSuite.
15505 void Run();
15506
15507 // Runs SetUpTestSuite() for this TestSuite. This wrapper is needed
15508 // for catching exceptions thrown from SetUpTestSuite().
15509 void RunSetUpTestSuite() {
15510 if (set_up_tc_ != nullptr) {
15511 (*set_up_tc_)();
15512 }
15513 }
15514
15515 // Runs TearDownTestSuite() for this TestSuite. This wrapper is
15516 // needed for catching exceptions thrown from TearDownTestSuite().
15517 void RunTearDownTestSuite() {
15518 if (tear_down_tc_ != nullptr) {
15519 (*tear_down_tc_)();
15520 }
15521 }
15522
15523 // Returns true iff test passed.
15524 static bool TestPassed(const TestInfo* test_info) {
15525 return test_info->should_run() && test_info->result()->Passed();
15526 }
15527
15528 // Returns true iff test skipped.
15529 static bool TestSkipped(const TestInfo* test_info) {
15530 return test_info->should_run() && test_info->result()->Skipped();
15531 }
15532
15533 // Returns true iff test failed.
15534 static bool TestFailed(const TestInfo* test_info) {
15535 return test_info->should_run() && test_info->result()->Failed();
15536 }
15537
15538 // Returns true iff the test is disabled and will be reported in the XML
15539 // report.
15540 static bool TestReportableDisabled(const TestInfo* test_info) {
15541 return test_info->is_reportable() && test_info->is_disabled_;
15542 }
15543
15544 // Returns true iff test is disabled.
15545 static bool TestDisabled(const TestInfo* test_info) {
15546 return test_info->is_disabled_;
15547 }
15548
15549 // Returns true iff this test will appear in the XML report.
15550 static bool TestReportable(const TestInfo* test_info) {
15551 return test_info->is_reportable();
15552 }
15553
15554 // Returns true if the given test should run.
15555 static bool ShouldRunTest(const TestInfo* test_info) {
15556 return test_info->should_run();
15557 }
15558
15559 // Shuffles the tests in this test suite.
15560 void ShuffleTests(internal::Random* random);
15561
15562 // Restores the test order to before the first shuffle.
15563 void UnshuffleTests();
15564
15565 // Name of the test suite.
15566 std::string name_;
15567 // Name of the parameter type, or NULL if this is not a typed or a
15568 // type-parameterized test.
15569 const std::unique_ptr<const ::std::string> type_param_;
15570 // The vector of TestInfos in their original order. It owns the
15571 // elements in the vector.
15572 std::vector<TestInfo*> test_info_list_;
15573 // Provides a level of indirection for the test list to allow easy
15574 // shuffling and restoring the test order. The i-th element in this
15575 // vector is the index of the i-th test in the shuffled test list.
15576 std::vector<int> test_indices_;
15577 // Pointer to the function that sets up the test suite.
15578 internal::SetUpTestSuiteFunc set_up_tc_;
15579 // Pointer to the function that tears down the test suite.
15580 internal::TearDownTestSuiteFunc tear_down_tc_;
15581 // True iff any test in this test suite should run.
15582 bool should_run_;
15583 // Elapsed time, in milliseconds.
15584 TimeInMillis elapsed_time_;
15585 // Holds test properties recorded during execution of SetUpTestSuite and
15586 // TearDownTestSuite.
15587 TestResult ad_hoc_test_result_;
15588
15589 // We disallow copying TestSuites.
15590 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(TestSuite);
15591};
15592
15593// An Environment object is capable of setting up and tearing down an
15594// environment. You should subclass this to define your own
15595// environment(s).
15596//
15597// An Environment object does the set-up and tear-down in virtual
15598// methods SetUp() and TearDown() instead of the constructor and the
15599// destructor, as:
15600//
15601// 1. You cannot safely throw from a destructor. This is a problem
15602// as in some cases Google Test is used where exceptions are enabled, and
15603// we may want to implement ASSERT_* using exceptions where they are
15604// available.
15605// 2. You cannot use ASSERT_* directly in a constructor or
15606// destructor.
15607class Environment {
15608 public:
15609 // The d'tor is virtual as we need to subclass Environment.
15610 virtual ~Environment() {}
15611
15612 // Override this to define how to set up the environment.
15613 virtual void SetUp() {}
15614
15615 // Override this to define how to tear down the environment.
15616 virtual void TearDown() {}
15617 private:
15618 // If you see an error about overriding the following function or
15619 // about it being private, you have mis-spelled SetUp() as Setup().
15620 struct Setup_should_be_spelled_SetUp {};
15621 virtual Setup_should_be_spelled_SetUp* Setup() { return nullptr; }
15622};
15623
15624#if GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
15625
15626// Exception which can be thrown from TestEventListener::OnTestPartResult.
15627class GTEST_API_ AssertionException
15628 : public internal::GoogleTestFailureException {
15629 public:
15630 explicit AssertionException(const TestPartResult& result)
15631 : GoogleTestFailureException(result) {}
15632};
15633
15634#endif // GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
15635
15636// The interface for tracing execution of tests. The methods are organized in
15637// the order the corresponding events are fired.
15638class TestEventListener {
15639 public:
15640 virtual ~TestEventListener() {}
15641
15642 // Fired before any test activity starts.
15643 virtual void OnTestProgramStart(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
15644
15645 // Fired before each iteration of tests starts. There may be more than
15646 // one iteration if GTEST_FLAG(repeat) is set. iteration is the iteration
15647 // index, starting from 0.
15648 virtual void OnTestIterationStart(const UnitTest& unit_test,
15649 int iteration) = 0;
15650
15651 // Fired before environment set-up for each iteration of tests starts.
15652 virtual void OnEnvironmentsSetUpStart(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
15653
15654 // Fired after environment set-up for each iteration of tests ends.
15655 virtual void OnEnvironmentsSetUpEnd(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
15656
15657 // Fired before the test suite starts.
15658 virtual void OnTestSuiteStart(const TestSuite& /*test_suite*/) {}
15659
15660 // Legacy API is deprecated but still available
15661#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15662 virtual void OnTestCaseStart(const TestCase& /*test_case*/) {}
15663#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15664
15665 // Fired before the test starts.
15666 virtual void OnTestStart(const TestInfo& test_info) = 0;
15667
15668 // Fired after a failed assertion or a SUCCEED() invocation.
15669 // If you want to throw an exception from this function to skip to the next
15670 // TEST, it must be AssertionException defined above, or inherited from it.
15671 virtual void OnTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& test_part_result) = 0;
15672
15673 // Fired after the test ends.
15674 virtual void OnTestEnd(const TestInfo& test_info) = 0;
15675
15676 // Fired after the test suite ends.
15677 virtual void OnTestSuiteEnd(const TestSuite& /*test_suite*/) {}
15678
15679// Legacy API is deprecated but still available
15680#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15681 virtual void OnTestCaseEnd(const TestCase& /*test_case*/) {}
15682#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15683
15684 // Fired before environment tear-down for each iteration of tests starts.
15685 virtual void OnEnvironmentsTearDownStart(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
15686
15687 // Fired after environment tear-down for each iteration of tests ends.
15688 virtual void OnEnvironmentsTearDownEnd(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
15689
15690 // Fired after each iteration of tests finishes.
15691 virtual void OnTestIterationEnd(const UnitTest& unit_test,
15692 int iteration) = 0;
15693
15694 // Fired after all test activities have ended.
15695 virtual void OnTestProgramEnd(const UnitTest& unit_test) = 0;
15696};
15697
15698// The convenience class for users who need to override just one or two
15699// methods and are not concerned that a possible change to a signature of
15700// the methods they override will not be caught during the build. For
15701// comments about each method please see the definition of TestEventListener
15702// above.
15703class EmptyTestEventListener : public TestEventListener {
15704 public:
15705 void OnTestProgramStart(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) override {}
15706 void OnTestIterationStart(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/,
15707 int /*iteration*/) override {}
15708 void OnEnvironmentsSetUpStart(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) override {}
15709 void OnEnvironmentsSetUpEnd(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) override {}
15710 void OnTestSuiteStart(const TestSuite& /*test_suite*/) override {}
15711// Legacy API is deprecated but still available
15712#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15713 void OnTestCaseStart(const TestCase& /*test_case*/) override {}
15714#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15715
15716 void OnTestStart(const TestInfo& /*test_info*/) override {}
15717 void OnTestPartResult(const TestPartResult& /*test_part_result*/) override {}
15718 void OnTestEnd(const TestInfo& /*test_info*/) override {}
15719 void OnTestSuiteEnd(const TestSuite& /*test_suite*/) override {}
15720#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15721 void OnTestCaseEnd(const TestCase& /*test_case*/) override {}
15722#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15723
15724 void OnEnvironmentsTearDownStart(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) override {}
15725 void OnEnvironmentsTearDownEnd(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) override {}
15726 void OnTestIterationEnd(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/,
15727 int /*iteration*/) override {}
15728 void OnTestProgramEnd(const UnitTest& /*unit_test*/) override {}
15729};

15731// TestEventListeners lets users add listeners to track events in Google Test.
15732class GTEST_API_ TestEventListeners {
15733 public:
15734 TestEventListeners();
15735 ~TestEventListeners();
15736
15737 // Appends an event listener to the end of the list. Google Test assumes
15738 // the ownership of the listener (i.e. it will delete the listener when
15739 // the test program finishes).
15740 void Append(TestEventListener* listener);
15741
15742 // Removes the given event listener from the list and returns it. It then
15743 // becomes the caller's responsibility to delete the listener. Returns
15744 // NULL if the listener is not found in the list.
15745 TestEventListener* Release(TestEventListener* listener);
15746
15747 // Returns the standard listener responsible for the default console
15748 // output. Can be removed from the listeners list to shut down default
15749 // console output. Note that removing this object from the listener list
15750 // with Release transfers its ownership to the caller and makes this
15751 // function return NULL the next time.
15752 TestEventListener* default_result_printer() const {
15753 return default_result_printer_;
15754 }
15755
15756 // Returns the standard listener responsible for the default XML output
15757 // controlled by the --gtest_output=xml flag. Can be removed from the
15758 // listeners list by users who want to shut down the default XML output
15759 // controlled by this flag and substitute it with custom one. Note that
15760 // removing this object from the listener list with Release transfers its
15761 // ownership to the caller and makes this function return NULL the next
15762 // time.
15763 TestEventListener* default_xml_generator() const {
15764 return default_xml_generator_;
15765 }
15766
15767 private:
15768 friend class TestSuite;
15769 friend class TestInfo;
15770 friend class internal::DefaultGlobalTestPartResultReporter;
15771 friend class internal::NoExecDeathTest;
15772 friend class internal::TestEventListenersAccessor;
15773 friend class internal::UnitTestImpl;
15774
15775 // Returns repeater that broadcasts the TestEventListener events to all
15776 // subscribers.
15777 TestEventListener* repeater();
15778
15779 // Sets the default_result_printer attribute to the provided listener.
15780 // The listener is also added to the listener list and previous
15781 // default_result_printer is removed from it and deleted. The listener can
15782 // also be NULL in which case it will not be added to the list. Does
15783 // nothing if the previous and the current listener objects are the same.
15784 void SetDefaultResultPrinter(TestEventListener* listener);
15785
15786 // Sets the default_xml_generator attribute to the provided listener. The
15787 // listener is also added to the listener list and previous
15788 // default_xml_generator is removed from it and deleted. The listener can
15789 // also be NULL in which case it will not be added to the list. Does
15790 // nothing if the previous and the current listener objects are the same.
15791 void SetDefaultXmlGenerator(TestEventListener* listener);
15792
15793 // Controls whether events will be forwarded by the repeater to the
15794 // listeners in the list.
15795 bool EventForwardingEnabled() const;
15796 void SuppressEventForwarding();
15797
15798 // The actual list of listeners.
15799 internal::TestEventRepeater* repeater_;
15800 // Listener responsible for the standard result output.
15801 TestEventListener* default_result_printer_;
15802 // Listener responsible for the creation of the XML output file.
15803 TestEventListener* default_xml_generator_;
15804
15805 // We disallow copying TestEventListeners.
15806 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(TestEventListeners);
15807};

15809// A UnitTest consists of a vector of TestSuites.
15810//
15811// This is a singleton class. The only instance of UnitTest is
15812// created when UnitTest::GetInstance() is first called. This
15813// instance is never deleted.
15814//
15815// UnitTest is not copyable.
15816//
15817// This class is thread-safe as long as the methods are called
15818// according to their specification.
15819class GTEST_API_ UnitTest {
15820 public:
15821 // Gets the singleton UnitTest object. The first time this method
15822 // is called, a UnitTest object is constructed and returned.
15823 // Consecutive calls will return the same object.
15824 static UnitTest* GetInstance();
15825
15826 // Runs all tests in this UnitTest object and prints the result.
15827 // Returns 0 if successful, or 1 otherwise.
15828 //
15829 // This method can only be called from the main thread.
15830 //
15831 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
15832 int Run() GTEST_MUST_USE_RESULT_;
15833
15834 // Returns the working directory when the first TEST() or TEST_F()
15835 // was executed. The UnitTest object owns the string.
15836 const char* original_working_dir() const;
15837
15838 // Returns the TestSuite object for the test that's currently running,
15839 // or NULL if no test is running.
15840 const TestSuite* current_test_suite() const GTEST_LOCK_EXCLUDED_(mutex_);
15841
15842// Legacy API is still available but deprecated
15843#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_
15844 const TestCase* current_test_case() const GTEST_LOCK_EXCLUDED_(mutex_);
15845#endif
15846
15847 // Returns the TestInfo object for the test that's currently running,
15848 // or NULL if no test is running.
15849 const TestInfo* current_test_info() const
15850 GTEST_LOCK_EXCLUDED_(mutex_);
15851
15852 // Returns the random seed used at the start of the current test run.
15853 int random_seed() const;
15854
15855 // Returns the ParameterizedTestSuiteRegistry object used to keep track of
15856 // value-parameterized tests and instantiate and register them.
15857 //
15858 // INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
15859 internal::ParameterizedTestSuiteRegistry& parameterized_test_registry()
15860 GTEST_LOCK_EXCLUDED_(mutex_);
15861
15862 // Gets the number of successful test suites.
15863 int successful_test_suite_count() const;
15864
15865 // Gets the number of failed test suites.
15866 int failed_test_suite_count() const;
15867
15868 // Gets the number of all test suites.
15869 int total_test_suite_count() const;

15871 // Gets the number of all test suites that contain at least one test
15872 // that should run.
15873 int test_suite_to_run_count() const;

15879 int total_test_case_count() const;

15881#endif // EMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI

15887 int skipped_test_count() const;
15888

15890 int failed_test_count() const;
15891

15893 int reportable_disabled_test_count() const;
15894
15895 // Gets the number of disabled tests.
15896 int disabled_test_count() const;

15898 // Gets the number of tests to be printed in the XML report.
15899 int reportable_test_count() const;

15902 int total_test_count() const;
15903
15904 // Gets the number of tests that should run.
15905 int test_to_run_count() const;

15907 // Gets the time of the test program start, in ms from the start of the
15908 // UNIX epoch.
15909 TimeInMillis start_timestamp() const;
15910
15911 // Gets the elapsed time, in milliseconds.
15912 TimeInMillis elapsed_time() const;
15913
15914 // Returns true iff the unit test passed (i.e. all test suites passed).
15915 bool Passed() const;
15916
15917 // Returns true iff the unit test failed (i.e. some test suite failed
15918 // or something outside of all tests failed).
15919 bool Failed() const;

15922 // total_test_suite_count() - 1. If i is not in that range, returns NULL.

15926#ifndef GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_

15928#endif // GTEST_REMOVE_LEGACY_TEST_CASEAPI_

15931 // properties logged outside of individual test suites.
15932 const TestResult& ad_hoc_test_result() const;

15935 // inside Google Test.
15936 TestEventListeners& listeners();
15937

15939 // Registers and returns a global test environment. When a test
15940 // program is run, all global test environments will be set-up in
15941 // the order they were registered. After all tests in the program
15942 // have finished, all global test environments will be torn-down in
15943 // the *reverse* order they were registered.
15944 //
15945 // The UnitTest object takes ownership of the given environment.
15946 //
15947 // This method can only be called from the main thread.
15948 Environment* AddEnvironment(Environment* env);
15949
15950 // Adds a TestPartResult to the current TestResult object. All
15951 // Google Test assertion macros (e.g. ASSERT_TRUE, EXPECT_EQ, etc)
15952 // eventually call this to report their results. The user code
15953 // should use the assertion macros instead of calling this directly.

15956 int line_number,

15958 const std::string& os_stack_trace)

15962 // inside a test, to current TestSuite's ad_hoc_test_result_ when invoked
15963 // from SetUpTestSuite or TearDownTestSuite, or to the global property set
15964 // when invoked elsewhere. If the result already contains a property with
15965 // the same key, the value will be updated.
15966 void RecordProperty(const std::string& key, const std::string& value);
15967
15968 // Gets the i-th test suite among all the test suites. i can range from 0 to
15969 // total_test_suite_count() - 1. If i is not in that range, returns NULL.
15970 TestSuite* GetMutableTestSuite(int i);
15971
15972 // Accessors for the implementation object.
15973 internal::UnitTestImpl* impl() { return impl_; }
15974 const internal::UnitTestImpl* impl() const { return impl_; }
15975
15976 // These classes and functions are friends as they need to access private
15977 // members of UnitTest.
15978 friend class ScopedTrace;
15979 friend class Test;
15980 friend class internal::AssertHelper;
15981 friend class internal::StreamingListenerTest;
15982 friend class internal::UnitTestRecordPropertyTestHelper;
15983 friend Environment* AddGlobalTestEnvironment(Environment* env);
15984 friend internal::UnitTestImpl* internal::GetUnitTestImpl();
15985 friend void internal::ReportFailureInUnknownLocation(
15986 TestPartResult::Type result_type,
15987 const std::string& message);
15988
15989 // Creates an empty UnitTest.
15990 UnitTest();
15991
15992 // D'tor
15993 virtual ~UnitTest();
15994
15995 // Pushes a trace defined by SCOPED_TRACE() on to the per-thread
15996 // Google Test trace stack.
15997 void PushGTestTrace(const internal::TraceInfo& trace)
15998 GTEST_LOCK_EXCLUDED_(mutex_);
15999
16000 // Pops a trace from the per-thread Google Test trace stack.
16001 void PopGTestTrace()
16002 GTEST_LOCK_EXCLUDED_(mutex_);
16003
16004 // Protects mutable state in *impl_. This is mutable as some const
16005 // methods need to lock it too.
16006 mutable internal::Mutex mutex_;
16007
16008 // Opaque implementation object. This field is never changed once
16009 // the object is constructed. We don't mark it as const here, as
16010 // doing so will cause a warning in the constructor of UnitTest.
16011 // Mutable state in *impl_ is protected by mutex_.
16012 internal::UnitTestImpl* impl_;
16013
16014 // We disallow copying UnitTest.
16015 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(UnitTest);
16016};

16018// A convenient wrapper for adding an environment for the test
16019// program.
16020//
16021// You should call this before RUN_ALL_TESTS() is called, probably in
16022// main(). If you use gtest_main, you need to call this before main()
16023// starts for it to take effect. For example, you can define a global
16024// variable like this:
16025//
16026// testing::Environment* const foo_env =
16027// testing::AddGlobalTestEnvironment(new FooEnvironment);
16028//
16029// However, we strongly recommend you to write your own main() and
16030// call AddGlobalTestEnvironment() there, as relying on initialization
16031// of global variables makes the code harder to read and may cause
16032// problems when you register multiple environments from different
16033// translation units and the environments have dependencies among them
16034// (remember that the compiler doesn't guarantee the order in which
16035// global variables from different translation units are initialized).
16036inline Environment* AddGlobalTestEnvironment(Environment* env) {
16037 return UnitTest::GetInstance()->AddEnvironment(env);
16038}
16039
16040// Initializes Google Test. This must be called before calling
16041// RUN_ALL_TESTS(). In particular, it parses a command line for the
16042// flags that Google Test recognizes. Whenever a Google Test flag is
16043// seen, it is removed from argv, and *argc is decremented.
16044//
16045// No value is returned. Instead, the Google Test flag variables are
16046// updated.
16047//
16048// Calling the function for the second time has no user-visible effect.
16049GTEST_API_ void InitGoogleTest(int* argc, char** argv);
16050
16051// This overloaded version can be used in Windows programs compiled in
16052// UNICODE mode.
16053GTEST_API_ void InitGoogleTest(int* argc, wchar_t** argv);

16055namespace internal {
16056
16057// Separate the error generating code from the code path to reduce the stack
16058// frame size of CmpHelperEQ. This helps reduce the overhead of some sanitizers
16059// when calling EXPECT_* in a tight loop.
16060template <typename T1, typename T2>
16061AssertionResult CmpHelperEQFailure(const char* lhs_expression,
16062 const char* rhs_expression,
16063 const T1& lhs, const T2& rhs) {
16064 return EqFailure(lhs_expression,
16065 rhs_expression,
16066 FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(lhs, rhs),
16067 FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(rhs, lhs),
16068 false);
16069}
16070
16071// This block of code defines operator==/!=
16072// to block lexical scope lookup.
16073// It prevents using invalid operator==/!= defined at namespace scope.
16074struct faketype {};
16075inline bool operator==(faketype, faketype) { return true; }
16076inline bool operator!=(faketype, faketype) { return false; }
16077
16078// The helper function for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ.
16079template <typename T1, typename T2>
16080AssertionResult CmpHelperEQ(const char* lhs_expression,
16081 const char* rhs_expression,
16082 const T1& lhs,
16083 const T2& rhs) {
16084 if (lhs == rhs) {
16085 return AssertionSuccess();
16086 }
16087
16088 return CmpHelperEQFailure(lhs_expression, rhs_expression, lhs, rhs);
16089}
16090
16091// With this overloaded version, we allow anonymous enums to be used
16092// in {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ when compiled with gcc 4, as anonymous enums
16093// can be implicitly cast to BiggestInt.
16094GTEST_API_ AssertionResult CmpHelperEQ(const char* lhs_expression,
16095 const char* rhs_expression,
16096 BiggestInt lhs,
16097 BiggestInt rhs);
16098
16099// The helper class for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ. The template argument
16100// lhs_is_null_literal is true iff the first argument to ASSERT_EQ()
16101// is a null pointer literal. The following default implementation is
16102// for lhs_is_null_literal being false.
16103template <bool lhs_is_null_literal>
16104class EqHelper {
16105 public:
16106 // This templatized version is for the general case.
16107 template <typename T1, typename T2>
16108 static AssertionResult Compare(const char* lhs_expression,
16109 const char* rhs_expression,
16110 const T1& lhs,
16111 const T2& rhs) {
16112 return CmpHelperEQ(lhs_expression, rhs_expression, lhs, rhs);
16113 }
16114
16115 // With this overloaded version, we allow anonymous enums to be used
16116 // in {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ when compiled with gcc 4, as anonymous
16117 // enums can be implicitly cast to BiggestInt.
16118 //
16119 // Even though its body looks the same as the above version, we
16120 // cannot merge the two, as it will make anonymous enums unhappy.
16121 static AssertionResult Compare(const char* lhs_expression,
16122 const char* rhs_expression,
16123 BiggestInt lhs,
16124 BiggestInt rhs) {
16125 return CmpHelperEQ(lhs_expression, rhs_expression, lhs, rhs);
16126 }
16127};
16128
16129// This specialization is used when the first argument to ASSERT_EQ()
16130// is a null pointer literal, like NULL, false, or 0.
16131template <>
16132class EqHelper<true> {
16133 public:
16134 // We define two overloaded versions of Compare(). The first
16135 // version will be picked when the second argument to ASSERT_EQ() is
16136 // NOT a pointer, e.g. ASSERT_EQ(0, AnIntFunction()) or
16137 // EXPECT_EQ(false, a_bool).
16138 template <typename T1, typename T2>
16139 static AssertionResult Compare(
16140 const char* lhs_expression, const char* rhs_expression, const T1& lhs,
16141 const T2& rhs,
16142 // The following line prevents this overload from being considered if T2
16143 // is not a pointer type. We need this because ASSERT_EQ(NULL, my_ptr)
16144 // expands to Compare("", "", NULL, my_ptr), which requires a conversion
16145 // to match the Secret* in the other overload, which would otherwise make
16146 // this template match better.
16147 typename EnableIf<!std::is_pointer<T2>::value>::type* = nullptr) {
16148 return CmpHelperEQ(lhs_expression, rhs_expression, lhs, rhs);
16149 }
16150
16151 // This version will be picked when the second argument to ASSERT_EQ() is a
16152 // pointer, e.g. ASSERT_EQ(NULL, a_pointer).
16153 template <typename T>
16154 static AssertionResult Compare(
16155 const char* lhs_expression,
16156 const char* rhs_expression,
16157 // We used to have a second template parameter instead of Secret*. That
16158 // template parameter would deduce to 'long', making this a better match
16159 // than the first overload even without the first overload's EnableIf.
16160 // Unfortunately, gcc with -Wconversion-null warns when "passing NULL to
16161 // non-pointer argument" (even a deduced integral argument), so the old
16162 // implementation caused warnings in user code.
16163 Secret* /* lhs (NULL) */,
16164 T* rhs) {
16165 // We already know that 'lhs' is a null pointer.
16166 return CmpHelperEQ(lhs_expression, rhs_expression, static_cast<T*>(nullptr),
16167 rhs);
16168 }
16169};
16170
16171// Separate the error generating code from the code path to reduce the stack
16172// frame size of CmpHelperOP. This helps reduce the overhead of some sanitizers
16173// when calling EXPECT_OP in a tight loop.
16174template <typename T1, typename T2>
16175AssertionResult CmpHelperOpFailure(const char* expr1, const char* expr2,
16176 const T1& val1, const T2& val2,
16177 const char* op) {
16178 return AssertionFailure()
16179 << "Expected: (" << expr1 << ") " << op << " (" << expr2
16180 << "), actual: " << FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(val1, val2)
16181 << " vs " << FormatForComparisonFailureMessage(val2, val1);
16182}
16183
16184// A macro for implementing the helper functions needed to implement
16185// ASSERT_?? and EXPECT_??. It is here just to avoid copy-and-paste
16186// of similar code.
16187//
16188// For each templatized helper function, we also define an overloaded
16189// version for BiggestInt in order to reduce code bloat and allow
16190// anonymous enums to be used with {ASSERT|EXPECT}_?? when compiled
16191// with gcc 4.
16192//
16193// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
16194
16195#define GTEST_IMPL_CMP_HELPER_(op_name, op)\
16196template <typename T1, typename T2>\
16197AssertionResult CmpHelper##op_name(const char* expr1, const char* expr2, \
16198 const T1& val1, const T2& val2) {\
16199 if (val1 op val2) {\
16200 return AssertionSuccess();\
16201 } else {\
16202 return CmpHelperOpFailure(expr1, expr2, val1, val2, #op);\
16203 }\
16204}\
16205GTEST_API_ AssertionResult CmpHelper##op_name(\
16206 const char* expr1, const char* expr2, BiggestInt val1, BiggestInt val2)
16207
16208// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
16209
16210// Implements the helper function for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NE
16211GTEST_IMPL_CMP_HELPER_(NE, !=);
16212// Implements the helper function for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_LE
16213GTEST_IMPL_CMP_HELPER_(LE, <=);
16214// Implements the helper function for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_LT
16215GTEST_IMPL_CMP_HELPER_(LT, <);
16216// Implements the helper function for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_GE
16217GTEST_IMPL_CMP_HELPER_(GE, >=);
16218// Implements the helper function for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_GT
16219GTEST_IMPL_CMP_HELPER_(GT, >);
16220
16221#undef GTEST_IMPL_CMP_HELPER_
16222
16223// The helper function for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STREQ.
16224//
16225// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
16226GTEST_API_ AssertionResult CmpHelperSTREQ(const char* s1_expression,
16227 const char* s2_expression,
16228 const char* s1,
16229 const char* s2);
16230
16231// The helper function for {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STRCASEEQ.
16232//
16233// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
16234GTEST_API_ AssertionResult CmpHelperSTRCASEEQ(const char* s1_expression,
16235 const char* s2_expression,
16236 const char* s1,
16237 const char* s2);

16275// first argument to {EXPECT,ASSERT}_PRED_FORMAT2(), not by

16277// (NULL is considered a substring of itself only), and return an
16278// appropriate error message when they fail.

16281// expressions that generated the two real arguments.

16290 const char* needle, const char* haystack);
16291GTEST_API_ AssertionResult IsNotSubstring(
16292 const char* needle_expr, const char* haystack_expr,
16293 const wchar_t* needle, const wchar_t* haystack);
16294GTEST_API_ AssertionResult IsSubstring(
16295 const char* needle_expr, const char* haystack_expr,
16296 const ::std::string& needle, const ::std::string& haystack);
16297GTEST_API_ AssertionResult IsNotSubstring(
16298 const char* needle_expr, const char* haystack_expr,
16299 const ::std::string& needle, const ::std::string& haystack);

16310namespace internal {

16312// Helper template function for comparing floating-points.
16313//
16314// Template parameter:
16315//
16316// RawType: the raw floating-point type (either float or double)
16317//
16318// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN A USER PROGRAM.
16319template <typename RawType>
16320AssertionResult CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ(const char* lhs_expression,
16321 const char* rhs_expression,
16322 RawType lhs_value,
16323 RawType rhs_value) {
16324 const FloatingPoint<RawType> lhs(lhs_value), rhs(rhs_value);
16325
16326 if (lhs.AlmostEquals(rhs)) {
16327 return AssertionSuccess();
16328 }
16329
16330 ::std::stringstream lhs_ss;
16331 lhs_ss << std::setprecision(std::numeric_limits<RawType>::digits10 + 2)
16332 << lhs_value;
16333
16334 ::std::stringstream rhs_ss;
16335 rhs_ss << std::setprecision(std::numeric_limits<RawType>::digits10 + 2)
16336 << rhs_value;
16337
16338 return EqFailure(lhs_expression,
16339 rhs_expression,
16340 StringStreamToString(&lhs_ss),
16341 StringStreamToString(&rhs_ss),
16342 false);
16343}

16348GTEST_API_ AssertionResult DoubleNearPredFormat(const char* expr1,
16349 const char* expr2,
16350 const char* abs_error_expr,
16351 double val1,
16352 double val2,
16353 double abs_error);

16355// INTERNAL IMPLEMENTATION - DO NOT USE IN USER CODE.
16356// A class that enables one to stream messages to assertion macros
16357class GTEST_API_ AssertHelper {
16358 public:
16359 // Constructor.
16360 AssertHelper(TestPartResult::Type type,
16361 const char* file,
16362 int line,
16363 const char* message);
16364 ~AssertHelper();
16365
16366 // Message assignment is a semantic trick to enable assertion
16367 // streaming; see the GTEST_MESSAGE_ macro below.
16368 void operator=(const Message& message) const;
16369
16370 private:
16371 // We put our data in a struct so that the size of the AssertHelper class can
16372 // be as small as possible. This is important because gcc is incapable of
16373 // re-using stack space even for temporary variables, so every EXPECT_EQ
16374 // reserves stack space for another AssertHelper.
16375 struct AssertHelperData {
16376 AssertHelperData(TestPartResult::Type t,
16377 const char* srcfile,
16378 int line_num,
16379 const char* msg)
16380 : type(t), file(srcfile), line(line_num), message(msg) { }
16381
16382 TestPartResult::Type const type;
16383 const char* const file;
16384 int const line;
16385 std::string const message;
16386
16387 private:
16388 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(AssertHelperData);
16389 };
16390
16391 AssertHelperData* const data_;
16392
16393 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(AssertHelper);
16394};

16399 const char* fmt,
