16404// The pure interface class that all value-parameterized tests inherit from.
16405// A value-parameterized class must inherit from both ::testing::Test and
16406// ::testing::WithParamInterface. In most cases that just means inheriting
16407// from ::testing::TestWithParam, but more complicated test hierarchies
16408// may need to inherit from Test and WithParamInterface at different levels.
16409//
16410// This interface has support for accessing the test parameter value via
16411// the GetParam() method.
16412//
16413// Use it with one of the parameter generator defining functions, like Range(),
16414// Values(), ValuesIn(), Bool(), and Combine().
16415//
16416// class FooTest : public ::testing::TestWithParam<int> {
16417// protected:
16418// FooTest() {
16419// // Can use GetParam() here.
16420// }
16421// virtual ~FooTest() {
16422// // Can use GetParam() here.
16423// }
16424// virtual void SetUp() {
16425// // Can use GetParam() here.
16426// }
16427// virtual void TearDown {
16428// // Can use GetParam() here.
16429// }
16430// };
16431// TEST_P(FooTest, DoesBar) {
16432// // Can use GetParam() method here.
16433// Foo foo;
16434// ASSERT_TRUE(foo.DoesBar(GetParam()));
16435// }
16436// INSTANTIATE_TEST_SUITE_P(OneToTenRange, FooTest, ::testing::Range(1, 10));
16437
16438template <typename T>
16439class WithParamInterface {
16440 public:
16441 typedef T ParamType;
16442 virtual ~WithParamInterface() {}
16443
16444 // The current parameter value. Is also available in the test fixture's
16445 // constructor.
16446 static const ParamType& GetParam() {
16447 GTEST_CHECK_(parameter_ != nullptr)
16448 << "GetParam() can only be called inside a value-parameterized test "
16449 << "-- did you intend to write TEST_P instead of TEST_F?";
16450 return *parameter_;
16451 }
16452
16453 private:
16454 // Sets parameter value. The caller is responsible for making sure the value
16455 // remains alive and unchanged throughout the current test.
16456 static void SetParam(const ParamType* parameter) {
16457 parameter_ = parameter;
16458 }
16459
16460 // Static value used for accessing parameter during a test lifetime.
16461 static const ParamType* parameter_;
16462
16463 // TestClass must be a subclass of WithParamInterface<T> and Test.
16464 template <class TestClass> friend class internal::ParameterizedTestFactory;
16465};
16466
16467template <typename T>
16468const T* WithParamInterface<T>::parameter_ = nullptr;
16469
16470// Most value-parameterized classes can ignore the existence of
16471// WithParamInterface, and can just inherit from ::testing::TestWithParam.
16472
16473template <typename T>
16474class TestWithParam : public Test, public WithParamInterface<T> {
16475};
16476
16477// Macros for indicating success/failure in test code.
16478
16479// Skips test in runtime.
16480// Skipping test aborts current function.
16481// Skipped tests are neither successful nor failed.
16482#define GTEST_SKIP() GTEST_SKIP_("Skipped")
16483
16484// ADD_FAILURE unconditionally adds a failure to the current test.
16485// SUCCEED generates a success - it doesn't automatically make the
16486// current test successful, as a test is only successful when it has
16487// no failure.
16488//
16489// EXPECT_* verifies that a certain condition is satisfied. If not,
16490// it behaves like ADD_FAILURE. In particular:
16491//
16492// EXPECT_TRUE verifies that a Boolean condition is true.
16493// EXPECT_FALSE verifies that a Boolean condition is false.
16494//
16495// FAIL and ASSERT_* are similar to ADD_FAILURE and EXPECT_*, except
16496// that they will also abort the current function on failure. People
16497// usually want the fail-fast behavior of FAIL and ASSERT_*, but those
16498// writing data-driven tests often find themselves using ADD_FAILURE
16499// and EXPECT_* more.
16500
16501// Generates a nonfatal failure with a generic message.
16502#define ADD_FAILURE() GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_("Failed")
16503
16504// Generates a nonfatal failure at the given source file location with
16505// a generic message.
16506#define ADD_FAILURE_AT(file, line) \
16507 GTEST_MESSAGE_AT_(file, line, "Failed", \
16508 ::testing::TestPartResult::kNonFatalFailure)
16509
16510// Generates a fatal failure with a generic message.
16511#define GTEST_FAIL() GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_("Failed")
16512
16513// Define this macro to 1 to omit the definition of FAIL(), which is a
16514// generic name and clashes with some other libraries.
16515#if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_FAIL
16516# define FAIL() GTEST_FAIL()
16517#endif
16518
16519// Generates a success with a generic message.
16520#define GTEST_SUCCEED() GTEST_SUCCESS_("Succeeded")
16521
16522// Define this macro to 1 to omit the definition of SUCCEED(), which
16523// is a generic name and clashes with some other libraries.
16524#if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_SUCCEED
16525# define SUCCEED() GTEST_SUCCEED()
16526#endif
16527
16528// Macros for testing exceptions.
16529//
16530// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_THROW(statement, expected_exception):
16531// Tests that the statement throws the expected exception.
16532// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NO_THROW(statement):
16533// Tests that the statement doesn't throw any exception.
16534// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_ANY_THROW(statement):
16535// Tests that the statement throws an exception.
16536
16537#define EXPECT_THROW(statement, expected_exception) \
16538 GTEST_TEST_THROW_(statement, expected_exception, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
16539#define EXPECT_NO_THROW(statement) \
16540 GTEST_TEST_NO_THROW_(statement, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
16541#define EXPECT_ANY_THROW(statement) \
16542 GTEST_TEST_ANY_THROW_(statement, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
16543#define ASSERT_THROW(statement, expected_exception) \
16544 GTEST_TEST_THROW_(statement, expected_exception, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
16545#define ASSERT_NO_THROW(statement) \
16546 GTEST_TEST_NO_THROW_(statement, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
16547#define ASSERT_ANY_THROW(statement) \
16548 GTEST_TEST_ANY_THROW_(statement, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
16549
16550// Boolean assertions. Condition can be either a Boolean expression or an
16551// AssertionResult. For more information on how to use AssertionResult with
16552// these macros see comments on that class.
16553#define EXPECT_TRUE(condition) \
16554 GTEST_TEST_BOOLEAN_(condition, #condition, false, true, \
16555 GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
16556#define EXPECT_FALSE(condition) \
16557 GTEST_TEST_BOOLEAN_(!(condition), #condition, true, false, \
16558 GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
16559#define ASSERT_TRUE(condition) \
16560 GTEST_TEST_BOOLEAN_(condition, #condition, false, true, \
16561 GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
16562#define ASSERT_FALSE(condition) \
16563 GTEST_TEST_BOOLEAN_(!(condition), #condition, true, false, \
16564 GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
16565
16566// Macros for testing equalities and inequalities.
16567//
16568// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ(v1, v2): Tests that v1 == v2
16569// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NE(v1, v2): Tests that v1 != v2
16570// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_LT(v1, v2): Tests that v1 < v2
16571// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_LE(v1, v2): Tests that v1 <= v2
16572// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_GT(v1, v2): Tests that v1 > v2
16573// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_GE(v1, v2): Tests that v1 >= v2
16574//
16575// When they are not, Google Test prints both the tested expressions and
16576// their actual values. The values must be compatible built-in types,
16577// or you will get a compiler error. By "compatible" we mean that the
16578// values can be compared by the respective operator.
16579//
16580// Note:
16581//
16582// 1. It is possible to make a user-defined type work with
16583// {ASSERT|EXPECT}_??(), but that requires overloading the
16584// comparison operators and is thus discouraged by the Google C++
16585// Usage Guide. Therefore, you are advised to use the
16586// {ASSERT|EXPECT}_TRUE() macro to assert that two objects are
16587// equal.
16588//
16589// 2. The {ASSERT|EXPECT}_??() macros do pointer comparisons on
16590// pointers (in particular, C strings). Therefore, if you use it
16591// with two C strings, you are testing how their locations in memory
16592// are related, not how their content is related. To compare two C
16593// strings by content, use {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STR*().
16594//
16595// 3. {ASSERT|EXPECT}_EQ(v1, v2) is preferred to
16596// {ASSERT|EXPECT}_TRUE(v1 == v2), as the former tells you
16597// what the actual value is when it fails, and similarly for the
16598// other comparisons.
16599//
16600// 4. Do not depend on the order in which {ASSERT|EXPECT}_??()
16601// evaluate their arguments, which is undefined.
16602//
16603// 5. These macros evaluate their arguments exactly once.
16604//
16605// Examples:
16606//
16607// EXPECT_NE(Foo(), 5);
16608// EXPECT_EQ(a_pointer, NULL);
16609// ASSERT_LT(i, array_size);
16610// ASSERT_GT(records.size(), 0) << "There is no record left.";
16611
16612#define EXPECT_EQ(val1, val2) \
16613 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal:: \
16614 EqHelper<GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(val1)>::Compare, \
16615 val1, val2)
16616#define EXPECT_NE(val1, val2) \
16617 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperNE, val1, val2)
16618#define EXPECT_LE(val1, val2) \
16619 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperLE, val1, val2)
16620#define EXPECT_LT(val1, val2) \
16621 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperLT, val1, val2)
16622#define EXPECT_GE(val1, val2) \
16623 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperGE, val1, val2)
16624#define EXPECT_GT(val1, val2) \
16625 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperGT, val1, val2)
16626
16627#define GTEST_ASSERT_EQ(val1, val2) \
16628 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal:: \
16629 EqHelper<GTEST_IS_NULL_LITERAL_(val1)>::Compare, \
16630 val1, val2)
16631#define GTEST_ASSERT_NE(val1, val2) \
16632 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperNE, val1, val2)
16633#define GTEST_ASSERT_LE(val1, val2) \
16634 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperLE, val1, val2)
16635#define GTEST_ASSERT_LT(val1, val2) \
16636 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperLT, val1, val2)
16637#define GTEST_ASSERT_GE(val1, val2) \
16638 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperGE, val1, val2)
16639#define GTEST_ASSERT_GT(val1, val2) \
16640 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperGT, val1, val2)
16641
16642// Define macro GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_ASSERT_XY to 1 to omit the definition of
16643// ASSERT_XY(), which clashes with some users' own code.
16644
16645#if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_ASSERT_EQ
16646# define ASSERT_EQ(val1, val2) GTEST_ASSERT_EQ(val1, val2)
16647#endif
16648
16649#if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_ASSERT_NE
16650# define ASSERT_NE(val1, val2) GTEST_ASSERT_NE(val1, val2)
16651#endif
16652
16653#if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_ASSERT_LE
16654# define ASSERT_LE(val1, val2) GTEST_ASSERT_LE(val1, val2)
16655#endif
16656
16657#if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_ASSERT_LT
16658# define ASSERT_LT(val1, val2) GTEST_ASSERT_LT(val1, val2)
16659#endif
16660
16661#if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_ASSERT_GE
16662# define ASSERT_GE(val1, val2) GTEST_ASSERT_GE(val1, val2)
16663#endif
16664
16665#if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_ASSERT_GT
16666# define ASSERT_GT(val1, val2) GTEST_ASSERT_GT(val1, val2)
16667#endif
16668
16669// C-string Comparisons. All tests treat NULL and any non-NULL string
16670// as different. Two NULLs are equal.
16671//
16672// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STREQ(s1, s2): Tests that s1 == s2
16673// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STRNE(s1, s2): Tests that s1 != s2
16674// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STRCASEEQ(s1, s2): Tests that s1 == s2, ignoring case
16675// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_STRCASENE(s1, s2): Tests that s1 != s2, ignoring case
16676//
16677// For wide or narrow string objects, you can use the
16678// {ASSERT|EXPECT}_??() macros.
16679//
16680// Don't depend on the order in which the arguments are evaluated,
16681// which is undefined.
16682//
16683// These macros evaluate their arguments exactly once.
16684
16685#define EXPECT_STREQ(s1, s2) \
16686 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTREQ, s1, s2)
16687#define EXPECT_STRNE(s1, s2) \
16688 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRNE, s1, s2)
16689#define EXPECT_STRCASEEQ(s1, s2) \
16690 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRCASEEQ, s1, s2)
16691#define EXPECT_STRCASENE(s1, s2)\
16692 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRCASENE, s1, s2)
16693
16694#define ASSERT_STREQ(s1, s2) \
16695 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTREQ, s1, s2)
16696#define ASSERT_STRNE(s1, s2) \
16697 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRNE, s1, s2)
16698#define ASSERT_STRCASEEQ(s1, s2) \
16699 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRCASEEQ, s1, s2)
16700#define ASSERT_STRCASENE(s1, s2)\
16701 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperSTRCASENE, s1, s2)
16702
16703// Macros for comparing floating-point numbers.
16704//
16705// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_FLOAT_EQ(val1, val2):
16706// Tests that two float values are almost equal.
16707// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_DOUBLE_EQ(val1, val2):
16708// Tests that two double values are almost equal.
16709// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NEAR(v1, v2, abs_error):
16710// Tests that v1 and v2 are within the given distance to each other.
16711//
16712// Google Test uses ULP-based comparison to automatically pick a default
16713// error bound that is appropriate for the operands. See the
16714// FloatingPoint template class in gtest-internal.h if you are
16715// interested in the implementation details.
16716
16717#define EXPECT_FLOAT_EQ(val1, val2)\
16718 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ<float>, \
16719 val1, val2)
16720
16721#define EXPECT_DOUBLE_EQ(val1, val2)\
16722 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ<double>, \
16723 val1, val2)
16724
16725#define ASSERT_FLOAT_EQ(val1, val2)\
16726 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ<float>, \
16727 val1, val2)
16728
16729#define ASSERT_DOUBLE_EQ(val1, val2)\
16730 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT2(::testing::internal::CmpHelperFloatingPointEQ<double>, \
16731 val1, val2)
16732
16733#define EXPECT_NEAR(val1, val2, abs_error)\
16734 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT3(::testing::internal::DoubleNearPredFormat, \
16735 val1, val2, abs_error)
16736
16737#define ASSERT_NEAR(val1, val2, abs_error)\
16738 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT3(::testing::internal::DoubleNearPredFormat, \
16739 val1, val2, abs_error)
16740
16741// These predicate format functions work on floating-point values, and
16742// can be used in {ASSERT|EXPECT}_PRED_FORMAT2*(), e.g.
16743//
16744// EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT2(testing::DoubleLE, Foo(), 5.0);
16745
16746// Asserts that val1 is less than, or almost equal to, val2. Fails
16747// otherwise. In particular, it fails if either val1 or val2 is NaN.
16748GTEST_API_ AssertionResult FloatLE(const char* expr1, const char* expr2,
16749 float val1, float val2);
16750GTEST_API_ AssertionResult DoubleLE(const char* expr1, const char* expr2,
16751 double val1, double val2);

16754#if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
16755
16756// Macros that test for HRESULT failure and success, these are only useful
16757// on Windows, and rely on Windows SDK macros and APIs to compile.
16758//
16759// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_HRESULT_{SUCCEEDED|FAILED}(expr)
16760//
16761// When expr unexpectedly fails or succeeds, Google Test prints the
16762// expected result and the actual result with both a human-readable
16763// string representation of the error, if available, as well as the
16764// hex result code.
16765# define EXPECT_HRESULT_SUCCEEDED(expr) \
16766 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT1(::testing::internal::IsHRESULTSuccess, (expr))
16767
16768# define ASSERT_HRESULT_SUCCEEDED(expr) \
16769 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT1(::testing::internal::IsHRESULTSuccess, (expr))
16770
16771# define EXPECT_HRESULT_FAILED(expr) \
16772 EXPECT_PRED_FORMAT1(::testing::internal::IsHRESULTFailure, (expr))
16773
16774# define ASSERT_HRESULT_FAILED(expr) \
16775 ASSERT_PRED_FORMAT1(::testing::internal::IsHRESULTFailure, (expr))
16776
16777#endif // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
16778
16779// Macros that execute statement and check that it doesn't generate new fatal
16780// failures in the current thread.
16781//
16782// * {ASSERT|EXPECT}_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(statement);
16783//
16784// Examples:
16785//
16786// EXPECT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(Process());
16787// ASSERT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(Process()) << "Process() failed";
16788//
16789#define ASSERT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(statement) \
16790 GTEST_TEST_NO_FATAL_FAILURE_(statement, GTEST_FATAL_FAILURE_)
16791#define EXPECT_NO_FATAL_FAILURE(statement) \
16792 GTEST_TEST_NO_FATAL_FAILURE_(statement, GTEST_NONFATAL_FAILURE_)
16793
16794// Causes a trace (including the given source file path and line number,
16795// and the given message) to be included in every test failure message generated
16796// by code in the scope of the lifetime of an instance of this class. The effect
16797// is undone with the destruction of the instance.
16798//
16799// The message argument can be anything streamable to std::ostream.
16800//
16801// Example:
16802// testing::ScopedTrace trace("file.cc", 123, "message");
16803//
16804class GTEST_API_ ScopedTrace {
16805 public:
16806 // The c'tor pushes the given source file location and message onto
16807 // a trace stack maintained by Google Test.
16808
16809 // Template version. Uses Message() to convert the values into strings.
16810 // Slow, but flexible.
16811 template <typename T>
16812 ScopedTrace(const char* file, int line, const T& message) {
16813 PushTrace(file, line, (Message() << message).GetString());
16814 }
16815
16816 // Optimize for some known types.
16817 ScopedTrace(const char* file, int line, const char* message) {
16818 PushTrace(file, line, message ? message : "(null)");
16819 }
16820
16821#if GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_STRING
16822 ScopedTrace(const char* file, int line, const ::string& message) {
16823 PushTrace(file, line, message);
16824 }
16825#endif
16826
16827 ScopedTrace(const char* file, int line, const std::string& message) {
16828 PushTrace(file, line, message);
16829 }
16830
16831 // The d'tor pops the info pushed by the c'tor.
16832 //
16833 // Note that the d'tor is not virtual in order to be efficient.
16834 // Don't inherit from ScopedTrace!
16835 ~ScopedTrace();
16836
16837 private:
16838 void PushTrace(const char* file, int line, std::string message);
16839
16840 GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ScopedTrace);
16841} GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED_; // A ScopedTrace object does its job in its
16842 // c'tor and d'tor. Therefore it doesn't
16843 // need to be used otherwise.
16844
16845// Causes a trace (including the source file path, the current line
16846// number, and the given message) to be included in every test failure
16847// message generated by code in the current scope. The effect is
16848// undone when the control leaves the current scope.
16849//
16850// The message argument can be anything streamable to std::ostream.
16851//
16852// In the implementation, we include the current line number as part
16853// of the dummy variable name, thus allowing multiple SCOPED_TRACE()s
16854// to appear in the same block - as long as they are on different
16855// lines.
16856//
16857// Assuming that each thread maintains its own stack of traces.
16858// Therefore, a SCOPED_TRACE() would (correctly) only affect the
16859// assertions in its own thread.
16860#define SCOPED_TRACE(message) \
16861 ::testing::ScopedTrace GTEST_CONCAT_TOKEN_(gtest_trace_, __LINE__)(\
16862 __FILE__, __LINE__, (message))
16863
16864
16865// Compile-time assertion for type equality.
16866// StaticAssertTypeEq<type1, type2>() compiles iff type1 and type2 are
16867// the same type. The value it returns is not interesting.
16868//
16869// Instead of making StaticAssertTypeEq a class template, we make it a
16870// function template that invokes a helper class template. This
16871// prevents a user from misusing StaticAssertTypeEq<T1, T2> by
16872// defining objects of that type.
16873//
16874// CAVEAT:
16875//
16876// When used inside a method of a class template,
16877// StaticAssertTypeEq<T1, T2>() is effective ONLY IF the method is
16878// instantiated. For example, given:
16879//
16880// template <typename T> class Foo {
16881// public:
16882// void Bar() { testing::StaticAssertTypeEq<int, T>(); }
16883// };
16884//
16885// the code:
16886//
16887// void Test1() { Foo<bool> foo; }
16888//
16889// will NOT generate a compiler error, as Foo<bool>::Bar() is never
16890// actually instantiated. Instead, you need:
16891//
16892// void Test2() { Foo<bool> foo; foo.Bar(); }
16893//
16894// to cause a compiler error.
16895template <typename T1, typename T2>
16896bool StaticAssertTypeEq() {
16897 (void)internal::StaticAssertTypeEqHelper<T1, T2>();
16898 return true;
16899}
16900
16901// Defines a test.
16902//
16903// The first parameter is the name of the test suite, and the second
16904// parameter is the name of the test within the test suite.
16905//
16906// The convention is to end the test suite name with "Test". For
16907// example, a test suite for the Foo class can be named FooTest.
16908//
16909// Test code should appear between braces after an invocation of
16910// this macro. Example:
16911//
16912// TEST(FooTest, InitializesCorrectly) {
16913// Foo foo;
16914// EXPECT_TRUE(foo.StatusIsOK());
16915// }
16916
16917// Note that we call GetTestTypeId() instead of GetTypeId<
16918// ::testing::Test>() here to get the type ID of testing::Test. This
16919// is to work around a suspected linker bug when using Google Test as
16920// a framework on Mac OS X. The bug causes GetTypeId<
16921// ::testing::Test>() to return different values depending on whether
16922// the call is from the Google Test framework itself or from user test
16923// code. GetTestTypeId() is guaranteed to always return the same
16924// value, as it always calls GetTypeId<>() from the Google Test
16925// framework.
16926#define GTEST_TEST(test_suite_name, test_name) \
16927 GTEST_TEST_(test_suite_name, test_name, ::testing::Test, \
16928 ::testing::internal::GetTestTypeId())
16929
16930// Define this macro to 1 to omit the definition of TEST(), which
16931// is a generic name and clashes with some other libraries.
16932#if !GTEST_DONT_DEFINE_TEST
16933#define TEST(test_suite_name, test_name) GTEST_TEST(test_suite_name, test_name)
16934#endif
16935
16936// Defines a test that uses a test fixture.
16937//
16938// The first parameter is the name of the test fixture class, which
16939// also doubles as the test suite name. The second parameter is the
16940// name of the test within the test suite.
16941//
16942// A test fixture class must be declared earlier. The user should put
16943// the test code between braces after using this macro. Example:
16944//
16945// class FooTest : public testing::Test {
16946// protected:
16947// virtual void SetUp() { b_.AddElement(3); }
16948//
16949// Foo a_;
16950// Foo b_;
16951// };
16952//
16953// TEST_F(FooTest, InitializesCorrectly) {
16954// EXPECT_TRUE(a_.StatusIsOK());
16955// }
16956//
16957// TEST_F(FooTest, ReturnsElementCountCorrectly) {
16958// EXPECT_EQ(a_.size(), 0);
16959// EXPECT_EQ(b_.size(), 1);
16960// }
16961
16962#define TEST_F(test_fixture, test_name)\
16963 GTEST_TEST_(test_fixture, test_name, test_fixture, \
16964 ::testing::internal::GetTypeId<test_fixture>())
16965
16966// Returns a path to temporary directory.
16967// Tries to determine an appropriate directory for the platform.
16968GTEST_API_ std::string TempDir();

16970#ifdef _MSC_VER
16971# pragma warning(pop)
16972#endif

16974// Dynamically registers a test with the framework.
16975//
16976// This is an advanced API only to be used when the `TEST` macros are
16977// insufficient. The macros should be preferred when possible, as they avoid
16978// most of the complexity of calling this function.
16979//
16980// The `factory` argument is a factory callable (move-constructible) object or
16981// function pointer that creates a new instance of the Test object. It
16982// handles ownership to the caller. The signature of the callable is
16983// `Fixture*()`, where `Fixture` is the test fixture class for the test. All
16984// tests registered with the same `test_suite_name` must return the same
16985// fixture type. This is checked at runtime.
16986//
16987// The framework will infer the fixture class from the factory and will call
16988// the `SetUpTestSuite` and `TearDownTestSuite` for it.
16989//
16990// Must be called before `RUN_ALL_TESTS()` is invoked, otherwise behavior is
16991// undefined.
16992//
16993// Use case example:
16994//
16995// class MyFixture : public ::testing::Test {
16996// public:
16997// // All of these optional, just like in regular macro usage.
16998// static void SetUpTestSuite() { ... }
16999// static void TearDownTestSuite() { ... }
17000// void SetUp() override { ... }
17001// void TearDown() override { ... }
17002// };
17003//
17004// class MyTest : public MyFixture {
17005// public:
17006// explicit MyTest(int data) : data_(data) {}
17007// void TestBody() override { ... }
17008//
17009// private:
17010// int data_;
17011// };
17012//
17013// void RegisterMyTests(const std::vector<int>& values) {
17014// for (int v : values) {
17015// ::testing::RegisterTest(
17016// "MyFixture", ("Test" + std::to_string(v)).c_str(), nullptr,
17017// std::to_string(v).c_str(),
17018// __FILE__, __LINE__,
17019// // Important to use the fixture type as the return type here.
17020// [=]() -> MyFixture* { return new MyTest(v); });
17021// }
17022// }
17023// ...
17024// int main(int argc, char** argv) {
17025// std::vector<int> values_to_test = LoadValuesFromConfig();
17026// RegisterMyTests(values_to_test);
17027// ...
17028// return RUN_ALL_TESTS();
17029// }
17030//
17031template <int&... ExplicitParameterBarrier, typename Factory>
17032TestInfo* RegisterTest(const char* test_suite_name, const char* test_name,
17033 const char* type_param, const char* value_param,
17034 const char* file, int line, Factory factory) {
17035 using TestT = typename std::remove_pointer<decltype(factory())>::type;
17036
17037 class FactoryImpl : public internal::TestFactoryBase {
17038 public:
17039 explicit FactoryImpl(Factory f) : factory_(std::move(f)) {}
17040 Test* CreateTest() override { return factory_(); }
17041
17042 private:
17043 Factory factory_;
17044 };
17045
17046 return internal::MakeAndRegisterTestInfo(
17047 test_suite_name, test_name, type_param, value_param,
17048 internal::CodeLocation(file, line), internal::GetTypeId<TestT>(),
17049 internal::SuiteApiResolver<TestT>::GetSetUpCaseOrSuite(),
17050 internal::SuiteApiResolver<TestT>::GetTearDownCaseOrSuite(),
17051 new FactoryImpl{std::move(factory)});
17052}
17053
17054} // namespace testing
17055
17056// Use this function in main() to run all tests. It returns 0 if all
17057// tests are successful, or 1 otherwise.
17058//
17059// RUN_ALL_TESTS() should be invoked after the command line has been
17060// parsed by InitGoogleTest().
17061//
17062// This function was formerly a macro; thus, it is in the global
17063// namespace and has an all-caps name.
17064int RUN_ALL_TESTS() GTEST_MUST_USE_RESULT_;
17065
17066inline int RUN_ALL_TESTS() {
17067 return ::testing::UnitTest::GetInstance()->Run();
17068}
